{"title_page": "Trans-Pacific Partnership", "text_new": "{{short description|2016 proposed trade agreement between several Pacific Rim countries}}\n{{about|the defunct proposed trade agreement|its 11 nation successor|Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name = Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| long_name =\n| image =[[File:Leaders of TPP member states.jpg|frameless|upright=1.15]]\n| caption =Leaders from 10 of the 12 prospective member states at a TPP summit in 2010\n| type = [[Trade agreement]]\n| date_drafted ={{start date and age|2015|10|05|df=yes}}<ref name=BBC51015>{{cite news |title=Trans-Pacific free trade deal agreed creating vast partnership |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-34444799 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 October 2015 |accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=12 Pacific countries seal huge free trade deal |url= https://news.yahoo.com/12-pacific-countries-seal-huge-free-trade-deal-130306553.html |first=Paul |last=Handley |date=5 October 2015 |agency=AFP |work=Yahoo! News |accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Financial Times |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/d4a31d08-6b4c-11e5-8171-ba1968cf791a.html |title=US and 11 nations seal Pacific trade deal |quote=the TPP must still be signed formally by the leader of each country and ratified by their parliaments}}{{paywall}}</ref>\n| date_signed = {{start date and age|2016|02|04|df=yes}}\n| location_signed = [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]\n| date_sealed =\n| date_effective = Not in force\n| condition_effective = Ratification by all original signatories, or (2 years after signature) ratification by at least 6 states corresponding to 85% of GDP of original signatories<ref name=Diplomat>{{cite news | newspaper=The Diplomat |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/heres-what-needs-to-happen-in-order-for-the-trans-pacific-partnership-to-become-binding/ |title=Here's What Needs to Happen in Order for the Trans-Pacific Partnership to Become Binding}}</ref>\n| signatories =\n* 11\n* {{flag|Australia}}\n* {{flag|Brunei}}\n* {{flag|Canada}}\n* {{flag|Chile}}\n* {{flag|Japan}}\n* {{flag|Malaysia}}\n* {{flag|Mexico}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|Singapore}}\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| parties =\n| ratifiers =\n* 2\n* {{flag|Japan}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| depositor =New Zealand\n| languages = [[English language|English]] (prevailing in the case of conflict or divergence), [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[French language|French]]\n| wikisource =Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| date_expiration =\n}}\n\nThe  '''Trans-Pacific Partnership''' ('''TPP'''), also called the '''Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement''', was a proposed [[trade agreement]] between Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore, Vietnam, and the United States signed on 4 February 2016, which was not ratified as required and did not come into effect. After the newly elected US president [[Donald Trump]] withdrew the US signature from TPP in January 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/01/23/news/economy/tpp-trump-china/ |title=Trump's decision to kill TPP leaves door open for China|last=Riley|first=Charles|date=23 January 2017|work=CNN|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> the agreement could not enter into force. The remaining countries negotiated a new trade agreement called [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]], which incorporates most of the provisions of the TPP and which entered into force on 30 December 2018.\n\nThe TPP began as an expansion of the [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]] (TPSEP or P4) signed by Brunei, Chile, New Zealand and Singapore in 2005. Beginning in 2008, additional countries joined the discussion for a broader agreement: Australia, Canada, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, Peru, the United States, and Vietnam, bringing the negotiating countries to twelve. In January 2017, the United States withdrew from the agreement.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Trump, Donald J.|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2017/01/25/2017-01845/withdrawal-of-the-united-states-from-the-trans--pacific-partnership-negotiations-and-agreement|title=Withdrawal of the United States From the Trans- Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[Federal Register]]}}</ref> The other 11 TPP countries agreed in May 2017 to revive it<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/20/tpp-nations-agree-to-pursue-trade-deal-without-us.html |title=TPP nations agree to pursue trade deal without US |last=Shaffer |first=Sri Jegarajah, Craig Dale, Leslie |date=2017-05-21 |work=[[CNBC]] |access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/saving-the-trans-pacific-partnership-what-are-the-tpps-prospects-after-the-us |title=Saving the Trans-Pacific Partnership: What are the TPP's prospects after the US withdrawal? |last=hermesauto |date=2017-05-21 |work=The Straits Times |access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref> and reached agreement in January 2018. In March 2018, the 11 countries signed the revised version of the agreement, called [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/tpp-11-countries-sign-trade-agreement-as-trump-implements-tariffs.html |title=Global trade just had a 'one step forward, one step back' day |last=Ming |first=Cheang |date=2018-03-09 |work=[[CNBC]] |access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref> After ratification by six of them (Australia, Canada, Japan, Mexico, New Zealand and Singapore), the agreement came into force for those countries on 30 December 2018.\n\nThe original TPP contained measures to lower both [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff]] and tariff [[Trade barriers|barriers to trade]],<ref name=\"GuardianAU2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/06/australia-and-the-trans-pacific-partnership-what-we-do-and-dont-know |title=Australia and the Trans-Pacific Partnership: what we do and don't know |date=6 October 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> and establish an [[investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) mechanism.<ref name=\"ustr100620152\">{{cite web |url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/press-releases/2015/october/summary-trans-pacific-partnership |title=Summary of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement |date=4 October 2015 |publisher=USTR |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/cards/trans-pacific-partnethership/what-is-the-trans-pacific-partnership |title=What is the Trans-Pacific Partnership? |date= |publisher=Vox |accessdate=2 July 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> The [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]],<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usitc.gov/publications/332/pub4607.pdf |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement: Likely Impact on the U.S. Economy and on Specific Industry Sectors |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=United States International Trade Commission |access-date=}}</ref> the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], the [[World Bank]] and the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada found the final agreement would, if ratified, lead to net positive economic outcomes for all signatories, while an analysis using an alternative methodology by two [[Tufts University]] economists found the agreement would adversely affect the signatories.{{refn|group=\"Note\"|The Tufts University working paper used the [https://www.un.org/development/desa/dpad/publication/united-nations-global-policy-model/ United Nations Global Policy Model] to evaluate TPP; sources for the Tufts paper:<ref name=\":110\">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212030617/http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-02-12 |title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership |publisher=World Bank  }}</ref><ref name=\":122\">{{cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/making-sense/column-why-the-trans-pacific-partnership-isnt-a-bum-deal/ |title=Why the Trans-Pacific Partnership isn't a bum deal |date=5 February 2016 |publisher=[[PBS]] |last1=Hufbauer |first1=Gary Clyde |accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TUJC16Jan20162\">[http://www.ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/wp/16-01Capaldo-IzurietaTPP.pdf Trading Down:Unemployment, Inequality and Other Risks of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement] J. Capaldo and A. Izurieta, Global Development and Environment Institute, Working Paper No. 16\u201301 Jan (2016)</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{cite news |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2931351/trans-pacific-partnership-would-boost-gdp-by-4-3-billion-study/ |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership would boost GDP by $4.3 billion: study |author=Staff writers |access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/tpp-debate-economic-benefits-by-dani-rodrik-2016-02?barrier=true |title=The Trade Numbers Game |last=Rodrik |first=Dani |date=10 February 2016 |website=Project Syndicate |access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://piie.com/blogs/trade-investment-policy-watch/studies-tpp-which-credible |title=Studies of TPP: Which Is Credible? {{!}} PIIE |website=piie.com |access-date=22 May 2016|date=30 January 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{cite web |url=http://ecipe.org/publications/splendid-isolation-capaldo-study-ttip/ |title=\"Splendid Isolation\" as Trade Policy: Mercantilism and Crude Keynesianism in \"the Capaldo Study\" of TTIP - ECIPE |access-date=10 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R44278.pdf |title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP): In Brief |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Congressional Research Service |access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=http://voxeu.org/article/tpp-structural-reform-let-s-evaluate-it-structural-models |title=TPP is a structural reform: Let's evaluate it with structural models |website=VoxEU.org |access-date=3 July 2016|date=3 July 2016 }}</ref>}} Many observers have argued the trade deal would have served a geopolitical purpose, namely to reduce the signatories' dependence on Chinese trade and bring the signatories closer to the United States.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":26\" />\n\n== Membership ==\n[[File:Trans-Pacific Partnership status.svg|thumb|{{legend|green|Parties}}\n{{legend|lightgreen|Signatories}}\n{{legend|red|Withdrawn signatory}}]]\nTwelve countries participated in negotiations for the TPP: the four parties to the 2005 [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]] and eight additional countries. All twelve signed the TPP on 4 February 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-35480600|title=Trans Pacific Partnership trade deal signed in Auckland|newspaper=BBC News|date=4 February 2016}}</ref> The agreement would have entered into force after ratification by all signatories, if this had occurred within two years. If the agreement had not been ratified by all before 4 February 2018, it would have entered into force after ratification by at least 6 states which together have a GDP of more than 85% of the GDP of all signatories. The withdrawal of the United States from the agreement in January 2017 effectively ended any prospect of the agreement entering into force. In response the remaining parties successfully negotiated a new version of the agreement that lacked the 85% GDP threshold, the [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership|CPTPP]], which entered into force in December 2018. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status in [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 TPSEP agreement]]\n! Start of TPP<br />Negotiations\n! Signature of TPP\n! Ratification of TPP\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Singapore}}\n| Party (28 May 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{N/A}} \n|-\n| {{flag|Brunei}}\n| Party (28 May 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| Party (12 July 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{dts|11 May 2017}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Chile}}\n| Party (8 November 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Australia}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Peru}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Malaysia}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|October 2010}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Mexico}}\n| Non-Party\n| {{dts|October 2012}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Canada}}<ref>{{cite press release |quote=Canada formally joined the TPP on October 8, 2012. |url=http://www.international.gc.ca/media_commerce/comm/news-communiques/2012/12/03a.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |title=Canada Joins Trans-Pacific Partnership Round |date=3 December 2012 |accessdate=13 December 2012 |publisher=Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada}}</ref>\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|October 2012}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Japan}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|May 2013}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{dts|20 January 2017}}\n|}\n\n===Withdrawn member===\nOn 23 January 2017, US President [[Donald Trump]] signed a [[presidential memorandum]] to [[s:Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement|withdraw the United States' signature from the agreement]], making its ratification as it was in February 2016 virtually impossible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/23/politics/trans-pacific-partnership-trade-deal-withdrawal-trumps-first-executive-action-monday-sources-say/|publisher=CNN.com|title=Trump signs order withdrawing from TPP, reinstate 'Mexico City policy' on abortion|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 TPSEP agreement]]\n! Start of TPP<br />Negotiations\n! Signature of TPP\n!Withdrawn\n|-\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|23 January 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38721056|title=Trump executive order pulls out of TPP trade deal|date=23 January 2017|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\nOn April 13, 2018, Trump said the United States may rejoin the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43747211|title=Trump to reconsider TPP trade pact|date=13 April 2018|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/donald-trump-considers-major-tpp-backflip-considers-rejoining-the-trans-pacific-partnership/news-story/75cb5a67d7e069e9af2869282758a962|title=Trump mulls major TPP backflip|website=news.com.au|date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-13/donald-trump-reportedly-exploring-rejoining-tpp-trade-deal-talks/9652202|title=Australian farmers shocked but cautious about news Trump wants 'another look' at the TPP|date=13 April 2018|website=abc.net.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/13/elizabeth-warren-bernie-sanders-slam-trumps-move-on-tpp-trade-deal.html|title='A ridiculous reversal': Top Democrats who sided with Trump on trade slam TPP move|first=Jacob|last=Pramuk|date=13 April 2018|website=cnbc.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Potential members ===\n[[APEC]] members may accede to the TPP, as may any other jurisdiction to which existing TPP members agree. After an application for membership is received, a commission of parties to the treaty negotiates conditions for accession.\n\nSouth Korea did not participate in the 2006 agreement, but showed interest in entering the TPP,<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE6AD05L20101114|title= South Korea mulling U.S.-led TPP trade initiative: report |date= 13 November 2010|accessdate= 15 November 2010|agency= Reuters|first= Yoko|last= Nishikawa}}</ref> and was invited to the TPP negotiating rounds in December 2010 by the U.S. after the successful conclusion of its [[Free trade agreement between the United States of America and the Republic of Korea]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?bicode=020000&biid=2010121816208|title=US requests Korea's joining of regional FTA|publisher=The Donga-A Ilbo|date=18 December 2010}}</ref> South Korea already had bilateral trade agreements with some TPP members, but areas such as vehicle manufacturing and agriculture still needed to be agreed upon, making further multilateral TPP negotiations somewhat complicated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_international/605796.html|title=Seoul appears set to join Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=4 October 2013|accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref> South Korea may join the TPP as part of a second wave of expansion for the trade agreement.<ref name=afifield>{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Anna|title=South Korea asks to join Pacific trade deal. Washington says not so fast.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/south-korea-asks-to-join-pacific-trade-deal-washington-says-not-so-fast/2015/04/15/85d7396a-e39e-11e4-ae0f-f8c46aa8c3a4_story.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=Washington Post|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther countries and regions that are interested in TPP membership include Taiwan,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201011100039|title=Taiwan aims to join Trans-Pacific Partnership: minister |date=10 November 2010|accessdate=13 November 2010}}</ref> the Philippines,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.ph/2010/09/24/speech-of-president-aquino-at-the-council-on-foreign-relations-new-york-city/|title=Speech of President Aquino at the Council on Foreign Relations, New York City |date=23 September 2010 |accessdate=2 November 2010}}</ref> and [[Colombia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tppdigest.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=145:colombia-hopes-to-join-tpp-negotiations&catid=1:latest-news|title=Colombia Hopes To Join TPP Negotiations|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=22 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215104815/http://tppdigest.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=145:colombia-hopes-to-join-tpp-negotiations&catid=1:latest-news|archivedate=15 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as of 2010; [[Thailand]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voxy.co.nz/politics/thailands-quest-join-tppa-will-strengthen-opposition/5/141000 |title=Thailand's quest to join the TPPA 'will strengthen opposition' |accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref> and [[Laos]]<ref name=\"canonigs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canon-igs.org/en/column/macroeconomics/20120710_1414.html|title=Current Status of the TPP Negotiations|publisher=Canon Institute for Global Studies|date=10 July 2012|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> as of 2012; and [[Indonesia]],<ref>{{cite news|title=US-ASEAN businessmen lobby Indonesia on TPP|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/06/25/us-asean-businessmen-lobby-indonesia-tpp.html|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[Cambodia]],<ref name=Cambodia>{{cite news|last=Theara|first=Khoun|title='No Rush' For Cambodia on Trans-Pacific Trade Agreement, Experts Say|url=http://www.voacambodia.com/content/no-rush-for-cambodia-on-trans-pacific-trade-agreement-experts-say-cambodia/1794961.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Voice of America Khmer|date=22 November 2013}}</ref> [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=Dhaka>{{cite news|last=Sobhan|first=Md Abus|title=Trans Pacific Partnership the way forward| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/op-ed/2013/sep/15/trans-pacific-partnership-way-forward| accessdate=19 September 2013|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|date=15 September 2013}}</ref> and [[India]]<ref name=India>{{cite news|last=Kumar|first=Arun|title='India's admission to TPP would be an economic coup'|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-admission-to-tpp-would-be-an-economic-coup-113080200419_1.html|accessdate=19 September 2013|newspaper=Business Standard|date=2 August 2013}}</ref> as of 2013. According to law professor Edmund Sim in 2013, many of these countries would need to change their [[protectionism|protectionist]] trade policies in order to join the TPP.<ref name=hookway>{{cite news|last1=Hookway|first1=James|last2=Brereton-Fukui|first2=Natasha|title=Trade Is Also Key to Influence in East Asia|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indonesiarealtime/2013/06/28/trade-is-also-key-to-influence-in-east-asia/|accessdate=14 May 2015|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe largest economy in the [[Pacific Rim]] not involved in the negotiations is [[China]]. According to the [[Brookings Institution]] in 2013, the most fundamental challenge for the TPP project regarding China was that \"it may not constitute a powerful enough enticement to propel China to sign on to these new standards on trade and investment. China so far has reacted by accelerating its own trade initiatives in Asia.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mireya|first1=Solis|title=The Containment Fallacy: China and the TPP|url=http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/up-front/posts/2013/05/24-china-transpacific-partnership-solis|website=Brookings Institution|accessdate=26 June 2014|date=30 November 2001}}</ref> In 2013, it was thought China might still be interested in joining the TPP eventually.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Needham|first1=Vicki|title=China's interest grows in joining an Asia-Pacific trade deal|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/on-the-money/1005-trade/322789-chinas-interest-grows-in-joining-an-asia-pacific-trade-deal|work=TheHill.com|date=17 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920192532/http://thehill.com/blogs/on-the-money/1005-trade/322789-chinas-interest-grows-in-joining-an-asia-pacific-trade-deal|archivedate=20 September 2013}}</ref>  An academic analysis has shown that while the TPP would be more successful if China participated in it, the benefits to China are intangible.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Devadason|first1=Evelyn S.|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP): the Chinese perspective|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary China]]|date=17 January 2014|volume=23|issue=87|pages=462\u2013479|doi=10.1080/10670564.2013.843890}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]] declared Indonesia's intention to join the TPP.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">\n{{cite news\n|author= Agence France-Presse in Washington\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/27/indonesia-will-join-trans-pacific-partnership-jokowi-tells-obama\n|title= Indonesia will join Trans-Pacific Partnership, Jokowi tells Obama &#124; World news\n|newspaper= The Guardian |date= 27 October 2015 |accessdate= 18 November 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Sri Lanka]] has announced interest of joining the TPP and is currently studying its feasibility.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/colombo-contemplating-joining-transpacific-partnership-samaraweera/article8285976.ece\n| title = Colombo contemplating joining Trans-Pacific Partnership: Samaraweera\n| date = 26 February 2016\n| newspaper = The Hindu\n| language = en-IN\n| issn = 0971-751X\n| access-date = 27 February 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2015/11/16/business/govt-pushing-gsp-tpp-membership-dr-harsha\n| title = Govt pushing for GSP+, TPP membership - Dr. Harsha {{!}} Daily News\n| work = dailynews.lk\n| access-date = 27 February 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 agreement]]\n! Status TPP\n! Announced Interest\n|-\n| {{flag|Colombia}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|January 2010}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Philippines}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|September 2010}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Thailand}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|November 2012}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Republic of China}} (Taiwan)\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|September 2013}}\n|-\n| {{flag|South Korea}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|November 2013}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Indonesia}}\n| Non-party\n| Declared Intent to Join<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" />\n| {{dts|October 2015}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2015/11/16/business/govt-pushing-gsp-tpp-membership-dr-harsha\n| title = Govt pushing for GSP+, TPP membership - Dr. Harsha {{!}} Daily News\n| work = dailynews.lk\n| access-date = 27 February 2016}}</ref>\n| {{dts|November 2015}}\n|}\n\n== History ==\n=== Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement ===\n{{main|Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement}}\n\nBrunei, Chile, Singapore and New Zealand are parties to the Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement (TPSEP), which was signed in 2005, and entered into force in 2006. The original TPSEP agreement contains an accession clause and affirms the members' \"commitment to encourage the accession to this Agreement by other economies\".<ref name=\"mfat.govt.nz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Trade-and-Economic-Relations/2-Trade-Relationships-and-Agreements/Trans-Pacific/0-history.php|title=History of the Trans-Pacific SEP Agreement P4|work=mfat.govt.nz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210151458/http://mfat.govt.nz/Trade-and-Economic-Relations/2-Trade-Relationships-and-Agreements/Trans-Pacific/0-history.php|archivedate=10 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf |title=TRANS-PACIFIC STRATEGIC ECONOMIC PARTNERSHIP AGREEMENT |work=mfat.govt.nz |accessdate=5 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514005708/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf |archivedate=14 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is a comprehensive agreement, affecting trade in goods, rules of origin, trade remedies, [[Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures|sanitary and phytosanitary measures]], technical barriers to trade, trade in services, intellectual property, government procurement and competition policy. Among other things, it called for a 90-percent reduction of all [[tariff]]s between member countries by 1 January 2006, and reduction of all trade tariffs to zero by the year 2015.<ref name=\"TPP2005\">{{cite web|url= http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf|title= Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|publisher= NZ Ministry of Foreign Affairs & Trade|year= 2005 |accessdate= 28 January 2012|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150514005708/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf|archivedate= 14 May 2015|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough original and negotiating parties are members of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), TPSEP is not an APEC initiative. However, the TPP is considered{{by whom|date=April 2019}} to be a pathfinder for the proposed [[Free Trade Area of the Asia Pacific]] (FTAAP), an APEC initiative.\n\n=== Original negotiations ===\n{{main|Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations}}\n\nIn January 2008, the U.S. entered talks with the Pacific 4 (P4) members regarding [[trade liberalisation]] in financial services.<ref name=\"NZH\">{{cite news| url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/3/story.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10491556|title= First step to wider free trade|work= The New Zealand Herald |accessdate= 9 February 2008|first= Chris|last= Daniels|date= 10 February 2008}}</ref> This led to 19 formal negotiation rounds and a subsequent series of additional meetings, such as Chief Negotiators Meetings and Ministers Meetings, and resulted in the agreement announced on 5 October 2015.\n\n=== Ratification of the original agreement ===\nThe original agreement was ratified by Japan and New Zealand.\n\nJapan's main competition in the region is China, these two nations holding polar views on how South-East Asia's economy should develop. Prior to TPP, Japan tried to achieve dominance by establishing the Asian Monetary Fund (AMF), which the U.S blocked.  By 2011 Japan managed to establish a cooperative agreement with China and Korea called the \"PRC\u2013Japan\u2013Republic of Korea Free trade agreement\", also known as the CJK FTA, which did not include the U.S.  Japan's intention with this was to use the People's Republic of China card in order to shift TPP negotiations away from China towards Japan's agendas with support of the United States.<ref name=\"ADB working paper series on regional economic integration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/152753/reiwp-146.pdf|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership versus Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership: Control of Membership and Agenda setting|author=Shintaro Hamanaka|date=January 2014}}</ref> Ratification in Japan required political reforms that shifted some authority from the agriculture ministry to the prime minister.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ishiguro |first1=Kaoru |title=TPP negotiations and political economy reforms in Japan\u2019s executive policy making: a two-level game analysis |journal=International Relations of the Asia-Pacific |date=20 June 2016 |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=171-201 |doi=10.1093/irap/lcw010}}</ref>\nOn 9 December 2016, [[resolution (law)|resolution]] of participation was made in the [[House of Councillors (Japan)|House of Councillors]], and notified completion of domestic procedures for ratification to the depositary of the treaty (New Zealand) as the first ratified country on 20 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/press/release/press4e_001443.html|title=Notification of Completion of Domestic Procedures for the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Agreement|accessdate=22 January 2017|date=20 January 2017|publisher =[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]]}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealand ratified the TPP on May 11, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/92466121/government-ratifies-tpp-as-bill-english-heads-to-japan-for-trade-talks|title=Government ratifies TPP as Bill English heads to Japan for trade talks|website=Stuff|access-date=2017-05-11}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] will seek to renegotiate the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) agreement in Vietnam in time to allow the government to ban foreign speculators from buying existing New Zealand homes. She said \"Our view is that it will be possible to balance our desire to make sure that we provide housing that's affordable, by easing demand and banning foreign speculators from buying existing homes, while meeting our trade goals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/political/342124/ardern-to-push-for-tpp-changes|title=Ardern to push for TPP changes|website=Radio New Zealand|access-date=2017-10-30|date=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== United States withdrawal ===\n[[File:Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement.pdf|thumb|Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement (2017)]]\n\nDuring a speech on the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential campaign]], [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] nominee [[Donald Trump]] vowed to withdraw the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership if elected. He argued that the agreement would \"undermine\" the U.S. economy and its independence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/28/donald-trump-vows-to-cancel-trans-pacific-partners/|title=Donald Trump vows to cancel Trans-Pacific Partnership as president, puts NAFTA on notice|work=[[The Washington Times]]|access-date=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"atlantic-wonthelp\">{{cite web|title=TPP's Death Won't Help the American Middle Class|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/11/tpps-death-wont-help-the-american-middle-class/507683/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=22 January 2017|date=15 November 2016}}</ref> On 21 November 2016, in a video message, Trump introduced an economic strategy of \"putting America first\", stating that he would negotiate \"fair, bilateral trade deals that bring jobs and industry back onto American shores.\" As part of this plan, Trump confirmed his intent for the United States to withdraw from the Trans-Pacific Partnership on his first day in office.<ref name=\"bbc-trumpvideo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38059623|title=Trump: US to quit TPP trade deal on first day in office|date=21 November 2016|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shear|first1=Michael D.|last2=Davis|first2=Julie Hirschfeld|title=Trump, on YouTube, Pledges to Create Jobs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/politics/donald-trump-presidency.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 November 2016|date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"gandm-100days\">{{cite web|title=Trump vows to withdraw from TPP deal, silent on NAFTA|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/trump-says-he-will-withdraw-from-tpp-deal-on-first-day-in-office/article32970902/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=22 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119030112/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/trump-says-he-will-withdraw-from-tpp-deal-on-first-day-in-office/article32970902/|archivedate=19 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> McConnell affirmed that the TPP would not be considered during the lame-duck session of Congress preceding the inauguration of Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/12/business/economy/donald-trump-trade-tpp-trans-pacific-partnership.html|title=What Is Lost by Burying the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|last=Calmes|first=Jackie|date=11 November 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump signed a [[Presidential memorandum]]<ref group=\"Note\">The official title of the document is: Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement [https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/01/23/presidential-memorandum-regarding-withdrawal-united-states-trans-pacific]</ref> to withdraw the U.S. from the TPP on 23 January 2017.<ref name=\"bbc-exexutiveorder\">{{cite web|title=Trump executive order pulls out of TPP trade deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38721056|website=BBC News|accessdate=23 January 2017 | quote = Mr Trump's executive order on TPP is seen as mainly symbolic since the deal was never ratified by a divided US Congress.}}</ref> U.S. Senator [[John McCain]] criticized the withdrawal, saying \"it will send a troubling signal of American disengagement in the Asia-Pacific region at a time we can least afford it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/china-eyes-opportunity-as-us-pulls-out-of-transpacific-partnership-20170123-gtxbi1.html|title=China eyes opportunity as US pulls out of Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=24 January 2017|work=Bloomberg / Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] applauded the move, saying \"For the last 30 years, we have had a series of trade deals[...] which have cost us millions of decent-paying jobs and caused a \u2018race to the bottom\u2019 which has lowered wages for American workers.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sanders-mccain-trump-trans-pacific-partnership-2017-1|title=Reaction to Trump's withdrawal from TPP doesn't fit cleanly along party lines|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== United States public opinion ===\nIn a 2018 study conducted on general foreign trade, researchers have found that a sizable majority of U.S. adults view foreign trade as conducive to U.S. growth rather than a foreign threat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/228317/positive-attitudes-toward-foreign-trade-stay-high.aspx|title=In U.S., Positive Attitudes Toward Foreign Trade Stay High|last=Inc.|first=Gallup|work=Gallup.com|access-date=2018-04-23|language=en-us}}</ref>  In an international context, Americans generally are among the least likely to support the Trans-Pacific Partnership and a clear partisan divide exists among the U.S. public in supporting the trade deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/23/americans-favor-tpp-but-less-than-other-countries-do/|title=Americans favor TPP, but less than those in other countries do|date=2015-06-23|work=Pew Research Center|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US}}</ref></p>\n\nPresident Donald Trump has expressed opposition to the TPP as a tenet of his 2016 election platform, which contributed to his popularity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Blendon|first=Robert J.|date=April 2017|title=Public Opinion and Trump's Jobs and Trade Policies|journal=Challenge|volume=60|issue=3|pages=228\u2013244|doi=10.1080/05775132.2017.1308763}}</ref>\n\nCritics complained that while Trump has worked to contain the economic and geostrategic influence of China, withdrawing from the TPP reduced the effectiveness of a treaty that was designed to do exactly that.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/09/23/arc-trump-administration-bends-toward-stupidity/ The arc of the Trump administration bends toward stupidity ]</ref>\n\n=== New negotiations and CPTPP ===\n{{main|Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership}} \nTPP's future was uncertain after the United States withdrew. Several signatories, however, signaled their intention to rework TPP without US participation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-asia-idUSKBN15800V|title=After U.S. exit, Asian nations try to save TPP trade deal|date=2017-01-24|newspaper=Reuters|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the remaining eleven countries agreed on a revised TPP, now renamed the \"[[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]]\" (CPTPP). CPTPP is substantially the same as TPP, but omits 20 provisions that had been added to TPP at US insistence and that are now no longer binding.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/world/6-things-to-know-about-the-trans-pacific-trade-pact-cptpp|title=6 things to know about the trans-Pacific trade pact CPTPP |last=hermesauto|date=2018-01-23|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref> These provisions primarily relate to investment, [[government procurement]] and [[intellectual property]].<ref>{{cite web|title= TPP11: Unpacking the Suspended Provisions|url= http://www.asiantradecentre.org/talkingtrade//tpp11-unpacking-the-suspended-provisions|website= Asian Trade Centre|accessdate= 23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom held informal talks to join the renewed negotiations after [[Brexit]] and has expressed an interest in joining CPTPP.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url= https://www.ft.com/content/73943036-efa9-11e7-b220-857e26d1aca4\n|title= UK looks to join Pacific trade group after Brexit |last= |first= |date= |website= Financial Times |access-date= 2018-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== Contents ==\nA version of the text of the agreement \"subject to legal review\" was released by prospective member parties on 5 November 2015.<ref>{{Citation\n| date = 5 November 2015\n| title = Text of the Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| publisher = New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade\n| url = http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Treaties-and-International-Law/01-Treaties-for-which-NZ-is-Depositary/0-Trans-Pacific-Partnership.php\n| accessdate = 5 November 2015}}</ref> Portions of drafts of the full agreement were previously leaked to the public.<ref>{{cite web|title = Leaked: What's in Obama's trade deal|url = http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2015/06/tpp-deal-leaked-pharma-000126|website = The Agenda|accessdate = 5 November 2015}}</ref> Many of the provisions in the leaked documents are modeled on previous trade agreements.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe contents of the TPP go far beyond the standards drafted by the [[World Trade Organization]].  The TPP includes a [[Negative list|negative-list]] of all sectors covered for the liberalizing trade, except for those clearly stated.  The TPP includes new regulation for [[E-commerce|online commerce]], treatment of foreign investors, far more comprehensive protection for intellectual property, labor codes, and an agreement for neutrality regarding [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned enterprises]].<ref name=\"Tropical Issue\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf|title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership|publisher=Global Economic Prospect|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 study by [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] political scientists Todd Allee and Andrew Lugg finds that out of the 74 previous trade agreements that TPP members signed since 1995, the text of the TPP most resembles that from earlier U.S. trade agreements.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Allee|first=Todd|last2=Lugg|first2=Andrew|date=1 July 2016|title=Who wrote the rules for the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|journal=Research & Politics|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|page=2053168016658919|doi=10.1177/2053168016658919|issn=2053-1680}}</ref> A 2017 study found that the TPP scored high relative to other trade agreements in terms of a government's ability to freely legislate and implement regulations in given public policy domains.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Broude|first=Tomer|last2=Haftel|first2=Yoram Z.|last3=Thompson|first3=Alexander|date=2017-06-01|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership and Regulatory Space: A Comparison of Treaty Texts|journal=Journal of International Economic Law|language=en|volume=20|issue=2|pages=391\u2013417|doi=10.1093/jiel/jgx016|issn=1369-3034}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade barriers ===\nThe agreement cuts over 18,000 tariffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#made-in-america|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#made-in-america|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tariffs on all U.S. manufactured goods and almost all U.S. farm products would be eliminated completely, with most eliminations occurring immediately.<ref name=WSJ11272015>{{cite news |author=Ed Gerwin |title=Small Businesses With a Big Stake in the Pacific Trade Deal |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=27 November 2015}}</ref> According to the [[Congressional Research Service]], TPP \"would be the largest U.S. [[Free Trade Agreement|FTA]] by trade flows ($905 billion in U.S. goods and services exports and $980 billion in imports in 2014)\".<ref name=\":8\"/> Including the US, the signatories represent roughly 40% of global GDP, and one-third of world trade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/business/international/the-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-accord-explained.html|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership Trade Accord Explained|last=Granville|first=Kevin|date=26 July 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the agreement mandates expedited customs procedures for express shipments and prohibits customs duties from being applied to electronic transmissions. It also requires additional privacy, security, and consumer protections for online transactions and encourages the publication of online customs forms. These provisions are expected to be particularly beneficial to small businesses.<ref name=WSJ11272015 />\n\n=== Environmental protection ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the \"TPP includes the most robust enforceable environment commitments of any trade agreement in history\".<ref name=\":20\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#preserving-the-environment|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#preserving-the-environment|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The USTR notes that the TPP requires signatories to fulfill their obligations under the [[CITES|Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES)]] to protect and conserve iconic species.<ref name=\":20\" /> According to the USTR, TPP is the first trade agreement to prohibit harmful fisheries subsidies, such as those that contribute to [[overfishing]].<ref name=\":20\" /> The USTR asserts that TPP signatories are required to \"combat illegal fishing\", \"promote sustainable fisheries management practices\", and \"protect wetlands and important natural areas\", \"combat wildlife trafficking, [[illegal logging]], and illegal fishing\"  and \"protect the marine environment from ship pollution, including by implementing their obligations under [[MARPOL 73/78|MARPOL]] (an international agreement to prevent marine pollution)\".<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nMorin and Baumier of the [[Canada Research Chair in International Political Economy]] (writing for the International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development) argue that while the TPP contains an impressive number of environmental provisions and a wide range of environmental protection areas, very few of these standards are innovative, most of which being copied from previous US agreements, and that the TPP missed an opportunity to be an original and progressive contribution to the environmental agenda. However, the TPP is innovative in its utilization of a combination of the American and the European approaches in environmental protection. Indeed, in doing so, the TPP became much more detailed and specific than regular US agreements while being legally more enforceable than European agreements.<ref>Morin, Jean-Frederic and Guillaume Baumier, TPP environmental commitments: Combining the US legalistic and the EU sectoral approaches, ICTSD, 2016, http://www.chaire-epi.ulaval.ca/sites/chaire-epi.ulaval.ca/files/publications/tpp_environmental_commitments.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2013 when TPP was still being negotiated, [[Sierra Club]]'s director of responsible trade, Ilana Solomon, argued that the TPP \"could directly threaten our climate and our environment [including] new rights that would be given to corporations, and new constraints on the fossil fuel industry all have a huge impact on our climate, water, and land.\"<ref>Ibrahim Balkhy (9 December 2013). [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/09/obama-trans-pacific-partnership_n_4414891.html \"Obama's Trans-Pacific Partnership May Undermine Public Health, Environment, Internet All At Once\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref> Upon the release of a draft of the Environment Chapter in January 2014, the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] joined with the Sierra Club in criticizing the TPP.<ref>Howard, Brian Clark (17 January 2014). [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/01/140117-trans-pacific-partnership-free-trade-environment-obama/ 4 Ways Green Groups Say Trans-Pacific Partnership Will Hurt Environment]. ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]''. Retrieved 23 January 2014.</ref> After the announcement of the United Nations [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) on 25 September 2015 and the finalisation of the TPP a week later, critics discussed the interactions between the SDGs and the TPP.  While one critic sees the TPP as providing a mixed bag of benefits and drawbacks to the SDGs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/pacific-trade-deal-needs-harmonize-sustainable-development-goals|title=Pacific Trade Deal Needs To Harmonize With Sustainable Development Goals|date=23 October 2015|publisher=YaleGlobal Online|author=Shuaihua Wallace Cheng|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> another regards the TPP as being incompatible with the SDGs, highlighting that if the development provisions clash with any other aspect of the TPP, the other aspect takes priority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership-poses-a-grave-threat-to-sustainable-development-50398|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership poses a grave threat to sustainable development|date=|publisher=[[The Conversation Australia]]|author=Matthew Rimmer|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> The [[Friends of the Earth]] have spoken out against the TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foe.org.au/articles/2015-10-02/briefing-tpp-and-sustainable-development-goals|title=Briefing on the TPP and Sustainable Development Goals &#124; Friends of the Earth Australia|date=2 October 2015|publisher=Friends of the Earth Australia|author=Cam Walker|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/2015/10/tpp-irreconcilable-with-un-sustainable-development-goals-say-critics/|title=TPP irreconcilable with UN sustainable development goals, say critics|date=6 October 2015|publisher=[[Asian Correspondent]]|author=Rowena Dela Rosa Yoon|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House Office|White House]] has cited supportive statements from the [http://www.worldwildlife.org/press-releases/wwf-statement-on-the-close-of-the-trans-pacific-partnership-negotiations World Wildlife Fund], the [[The Nature Conservancy|Nature Conservancy]], the [[The Humane Society of the United States|Humane Society]], the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]], [[Defenders of Wildlife]], [[International Fund for Animal Welfare]], [[World Animal Protection]] and other environmental groups in favor of the TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/03/31/what-theyre-saying-environmental-advocates-point-trans-pacific-partnership-historic-|title=What They're Saying: Environmental Advocates Point to the Trans-Pacific Partnership as a Historic Opportunity to Protect Our Oceans, Forests, and Wildlife|work=whitehouse.gov|date=31 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/economy/trade|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership|website=The White House|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715213957/https://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/economy/trade|archivedate=15 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] argues that the TPP is \"the most environmentally friendly trade deal ever negotiated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/newsroom/short-videos/tpp-and-environment|title=TPP and the Environment {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=20 July 2016|date=22 April 2016}}</ref> In regards to ISDS, PIIE analysts note that there is little evidence of constraints on environmental policies resulting from ISDS litigation.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nA September 2016 report by the [[Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy]] (IATP) predicts that \"as countries take action to protect the climate, conflicts between trade rules and climate goals will escalate\".<ref name=\"lilliston-2016\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Lilliston | first = Ben\n | title = The climate cost of free trade: how the TPP and trade deals undermine the Paris climate agreement\n | date = September 2016\n | publisher = [[Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy]] (IATP)\n | location = Minneapolis, MN, USA\n | url = http://www.iatp.org/files/2016_09_06_ClimateCostFreeTrade.pdf\n | access-date = 25 September 2016\n}}\n</ref>{{rp|1}}  The report goes on to say that trade agreements like the TPP set broad-reaching rules for the economy and government policy, thereby expanding trade, often in extractive sectors, and protecting corporations and financial firms from future measures to stabilize the climate.<ref name=\"lilliston-2016\"/>\n\n=== Good governance ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], signatories are required to join the [[United Nations Convention Against Corruption]] (UNCAC); criminalize bribery of public officials; have in place a code of conduct for public officials; take measures to decrease conflicts of interest; effectively enforce anti-corruption laws and regulations; and involve private organizations in the fight against corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#strengthening-good-governance|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#strengthening-good-governance|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP prohibits exploitative child labor and forced labor; ensures the right to [[collective bargaining]]; and prohibits employment discrimination.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#standing-up-for-human-rights|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#standing-up-for-human-rights|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The USTR asserts that \"research by the International Labor Organization and the World Trade Organization finds that combining expanded trade opportunities with strong protections for workers can help workers move from informal-sector jobs into formal work in wage-paying, regulated export industries which offer a minimum wage, benefits, and safety programs\".<ref name=\":19\" /> The USTR asserts that \"research also shows that trade improves human rights conditions by fostering pluralistic institutions and increasing open exchanges of information.\"<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n''[[PolitiFact.com|PolitiFact]]'' rates President Obama's claim that due to the Trans-Pacific Partnership \"we've got a country like [[Malaysia]] taking really serious efforts to crack down on [[human trafficking]]\" as \"mostly true\".<ref name=\":28\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/global-news/statements/2016/aug/05/barack-obama/obama-claims-positive-relationship-between-trans-p/|title=Checking an Obama claim on TPP and Malaysian human rights|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref> ''PolitiFact'' notes that Malaysia began to comply with the TPP in June 2015, amending its law to improve the treatment of trafficking victims.<ref name=\":28\" /> Among the changes, Malaysia gave victims better access to government shelters, transitional housing and more victim-friendly restitution procedures.<ref name=\":28\" /> Malaysia has also taken steps to stop human trafficking within the construction industry.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\nIn August 2017, Reuters reported that the [[Government of Vietnam|Vietnamese government]] was intensifying repression of human rights, in part because of the Trump administration's decision to drop the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-vietnam-arrests-idUSKBN1AI0LF|title=Trump factor weighs as Vietnam intensifies crackdown on dissidents|last=|first=|date=2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> Membership of the TPP had previously encouraged Vietnam to show a good human rights record.<ref name=\":35\" />\n\n=== Intellectual property ===\nThe intellectual property section of a leaked draft of the TPP lays out a minimum level of protection parties to the Agreement must grant for [[trademark]]s, [[copyright]], and [[patents]].<ref name=Gold_standard>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/eastwest-center/tpp-the-new-gold-standard_b_9544428.html|title=TPP: The New Gold Standard for Intellectual Property Protection in Trade Agreements?|work=Huffington Post|author=Carlos A. Primo Braga|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Copyright is granted at a length of life of the author plus 70 years,<ref name=Gold_standard /> and requires countries to set criminal penalties for violating copyright protections such as [[Digital Rights Management]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotlight-on-digital-rights-as-tpp-text-revealed-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Spotlight on digital rights as full Trans-Pacific Partnership text finally revealed|publisher=Cnet|author=Claire Reilly|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP will spur innovation by requiring signatories to establish strong patentability standard and adopt strong copyright protections.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#promoting-innovation|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#promoting-innovation|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWalter Park, Professor of Economics at [[American University]], argues, based on the existing literature, that the pharmaceutical protections in TPP will potentially enhance unaffiliated licensing in developing countries, lead to tech transfers that contribute to local learning-by-doing, stimulate new drug launches in more countries, expand marketing and distribution networks, and encourage early-stage pharmaceutical innovations.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/events/tpp-pharmaceutical-protections-too-strong-too-weak-or-just-right|title=The TPP and Pharmaceutical Protections: Too Strong, Too Weak, or Just Right?|date=25 May 2016|access-date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2011, some provisions relating to the enforcement of patents and copyrights alleged to be present in the US proposal for the agreement had been criticised as being excessively restrictive, beyond those in the Korea\u2013US trade agreement and [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA).<ref name=\"pijip\">{{cite journal |last=Flynn |first=Sean |last2=Kaminski |first2=Margot E. |last3=Baker |first3=Brook K. |last4=Koo |first4=Jimmy H. |title=Public Interest Analysis of the US TPP Proposal for an IP Chapter |publisher=Program on Information Justice and Intellectual Property |date=6 December 2011 |url=http://digitalcommons.wcl.american.edu/research/21/}}</ref><ref name=efftpp />\n\nThe [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]<ref name=efftpp /> was highly critical of the leaked draft chapter on intellectual property covering copyright, trademarks, and patents. In the US, they believed this was likely to further entrench controversial aspects of US copyright law (such as the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]]) and restrict the ability of Congress to engage in domestic law reform to meet the evolving intellectual property needs of American citizens and the innovative technology sector. Standardization of copyright provisions by other signatories would also require significant changes to other countries' copyright laws. These, according to EFF, include obligations for countries to expand [[copyright term]]s, restrict [[fair use]], adopt criminal sanctions for copyright infringement that is done without a commercial motivation (ex. [[file sharing]] of copyrighted digital media), place greater liability on [[Internet intermediary|internet intermediaries]], escalate protections for [[digital lock]]s and create new threats for journalists and whistleblowers.<ref name=efftpp>{{cite web|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement|url=https://www.eff.org/issues/tpp|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth the copyright term expansion and the non-complaint provision (i.e., competent authorities may initiate legal action without the need for a formal complaint) previously failed to pass in Japan because they were so controversial.<ref name=effjap /> In early 2015, \"a group of artists, archivists, academics, and activists  ... in Japan [asked] their negotiators to oppose requirements in the TPP that would require their country, and five of the other 11 nations negotiating this secretive agreement, to expand their copyright terms to match the United States' already excessive length of copyright.\"<ref name=effjap>{{cite web|title=Massive Coalition of Japanese Organizations Campaigns Against TPP Copyright Provisions|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/03/massive-coalition-japanese-organizations-campaign-against-tpp-copyright-provisions|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> The [[s:Trans-Pacific Partnership/Chapter 18#Article 18c: Term of Protection for Copyright and Related Rights|final agreement]] nonetheless sets a term of copyright equal to the one that obtains under U.S. law\u2014life of the author plus 70 years.\n\n[[Ken Akamatsu]], creator of Japanese manga series ''[[Love Hina]]'' and ''[[Mahou Sensei Negima!]]'', expressed concern the agreement could decimate the derivative [[d\u014djinshi]] (self-published) works prevalent in Japan. Akamatsu argued that the TPP \"would destroy derivative d\u014djinshi. And as a result, the power of the entire [[manga]] industry would also diminish.\"<ref>[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-10-31/negima-akamatsu-warns-against-changing-japan-copyright-law \"Negima's Akamatsu Warns Against Changing Japan's Copyright Law\"], [[Anime News Network]], 31 October 2011. Retrieved 10 November 2011</ref>\n\n==== Pharmaceuticals ====\nIn May 2015, Nobel Memorial prize winning economist [[Paul Krugman]] expressed concern that the TPP would tighten the patent laws and allow corporations such as big pharmaceutical companies and Hollywood to gain advantages, in terms of increasing rewards, at the cost of consumers, and that people in developing countries would not be able to access the medicines under the TPP regime.<ref name=TNYTPRK22May2015TPPA>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/22/opinion/paul-krugman-trade-and-trust.html \"Trade and Trust\"] Paul Krugman, ''The New York Times'', 22 May 2015</ref> However, Walter Park, Professor of Economics at American University, argues that it is far from clear in economic research that this would necessarily happen: clarifying intellectual property rights on drugs, for some developing countries, has not led to greater prices and less access to drugs.<ref name=\":14\"/> Park also argues, based on the existing literature, that the pharmaceutical protections in TPP will potentially enhance unaffiliated licensing in developing countries, lead to tech transfers that contribute to local learning-by-doing, stimulate new drug launches in more countries, expand marketing and distribution networks, and encourage early stage pharmaceutical innovations.<ref name=\":14\" /> The [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] notes that the TPP \"aligns with the Doha Declaration on TRIPS and Public Health\", which allows developing countries to circumvent [[patent]] rights for better access to [[essential medicines]].<ref name=\":18\"/>\n\nPharmaceutical companies have criticized TPP for having too lenient intellectual property protections.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-05/drugmakers-say-pacific-trade-pact-to-stifle-investment-in-cures|title=Drugmakers Say Pacific Trade Agreement to Stifle Investment|last=DoniBloomfield|first=Anna Edney annaedney Doni Bloomfield|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/10/5/9456757/trans-pacific-partnership-explained|title=The just-completed Trans-Pacific Partnership deal, explained|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=5 October 2015|website=Vox|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kff.org/news-summary/tpps-pharmaceutical-provisions-likely-to-draw-criticism-from-industry-aid-agencies/|title=TPP's Pharmaceutical Provisions Likely To Draw Criticism From Industry, Aid Agencies|language=en-US|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, an editorial in the ''New England Journal of Medicine'' cited concerns by [[M\u00e9decins sans Fronti\u00e8res]] and [[Oxfam]] that a spike in drug prices caused by patent extensions could threaten millions of lives.<ref name=\"Kapczynski\">{{cite journal|date=16 July 2015|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership \u2014 Is It Bad for Your Health?|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=373|issue=3|pages=201\u2013203|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1506158|pmid=26061752|last1=Kapczynski|first1=Amy}}</ref> Extending \"data exclusivity\" provisions would \"prevent drug regulatory agencies such as the [[Food and Drug Administration]] from registering a generic version of a drug for a certain number of years.\" The article arugues that TPP could theoretically require corporations be paid compensation for any \"lost profits\" found to result from a nation's health regulations.<ref name=\"Kapczynski\" /> The article argues that the provisions in the TPP concerning generic drugs directly target [[Pharmaceutical industry in India|India's pharmaceutical industry]].<ref name=\"Kapczynski\" /> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in November 2015 that it was \"extremely concerned about the inclusion of dangerous provisions that would dismantle public health safeguards enshrined in international law and restrict access to price-lowering generic medicines for millions of people.\"<ref name=\"doctorswithoutborders_2015_TPP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/statement-msf-official-release-full-text-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-agreement|title=Statement by MSF on the Official Release of the Full Text of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Trade Agreement|date=5 November 2015|work=Doctors Without Borders|accessdate=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107112340/http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/statement-msf-official-release-full-text-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-agreement|archive-date=7 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DemNowTPPout\">{{Citation|last=Goodman|first=Amy|title=Full Text of TPP Trade Deal Revealed -- and Critics Say It's Even Worse Than They Thought|date=6 November 2015|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/11/6/full_text_of_tpp_trade_deal|last2=Gonz\u00e1lez|last3=Wallach|first2=Juan|first3=Lori|author-link=Amy Goodman|author2-link=Juan Gonzalez (journalist)|author3-link=Lori Wallach|publisher=Democracy Now|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> The Australian Public Health Association (PHAA) published a media release in February 2014 that highlighted \"the ways in which some of the expected economic gains from the TPPA may be undermined by poor health outcomes, and the economic costs associated with these poor health outcomes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO1402/S00215/protecting-the-health-of-australians-in-the-tppa.htm|title=Protecting the Health of Australians in the TPPA|date=18 February 2014|newspaper=Scoop Independent News|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nA number of United States Congressional members,<ref name=\"10reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Ten-Representatives-on-TPP-08022011.pdf|title=Letter from 10 Representatives asking for a meeting to discuss IP policies that could \"undermine public health and access to medicines.\"|date=3 August 2011|publisher=infojustice.org|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> including Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref name=\"sanders letter\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/Sen_Sanders_letter_to_USTR_TPP_negotiations_12-1-2011.pdf|title=Letter from Senator Sanders to US Trade Representative Ron Kirk|date=1 December 2011|publisher=keionline.org|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> and Representatives [[Sander M. Levin]], [[John Conyers]], [[Jim McDermott]] and the now-retired [[Henry Waxman]], as well as<ref name=\"four reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Four-Democrat-Reps-10192011.pdf|title=Letter from Representatives Levin, Waxman, McDermott and Conyers to US Trade Representative Ron Kirk|date=19 October 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]], [[Charles B. Rangel]], [[Earl Blumenauer]], [[Lloyd Doggett]] and then-congressman [[Pete Stark]],<ref name=\"five reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Five-MOCs-September-8-2011.pdf|title=Letter from Reps. Lewis, Stark, Rangel, Blumenauer, and Doggett asking that the May 10th agreement serve as a 'non-negotiable starting point' for access to medicines|date=8 September 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> have expressed concerns about access to medicine. By protecting intellectual property in the form of the TPP mandating patent extensions, access by patients to affordable medicine in the developing world could be hindered, particularly in Vietnam.<ref name=\"10reps letter\" /> Additionally, they worried that the TPP would not be flexible enough to accommodate existing non-discriminatory drug reimbursement programs and the diverse health systems of member countries.<ref name=\"five reps letter\" /> In February 2015, former U.S. Labor Secretary [[Robert Reich]] stated he opposed the TPP because it would delay cheaper generic versions of drugs and because of its provisions for international tribunals that can require corporations be paid \"compensation for any lost profits found to result from a nation's regulations.\"<ref>''[http://www.salon.com/2015/02/05/robert_reich_a_trans_pacific_partnership_would_be_devastating_partner Robert Reich: A Trans-Pacific Partnership Would Be Devastating].'' Salon.com, 5 February 2015</ref>\n\n=== Investor-state arbitration ===\nThe TPP agreement establishes an [[investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) mechanism,<ref>{{cite web |title=TPP Final Text Chapter 9 Investment |url=https://ustr.gov/sites/default/files/TPP-Final-Text-Investment.pdf |accessdate=17 January 2016 }}</ref> which grants investors the right to sue foreign governments for treaty violations. For example, if an investor invests in country \"A\", a member of a trade treaty, and country A breaches that treaty, then the investor may sue country A's government for the breach.<ref>Hernando Otero and Omar Garc\u00eda-Bol\u00edvar, [http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/International_Arbitration_Foreign_Investors_Host_States.htm \"International Arbitration between Foreign Investors and Host States\"] Hauser Global Law School Program. NYU, December 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2014</ref> ISDS is meant to provide investors in foreign countries basic protections from foreign government actions such as \"freedom from discrimination\", \"protection against uncompensated expropriation of property\", \"protection against denial of justice\" and \"right to transfer capital\":<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/fact-sheets/2015/march/investor-state-dispute-settlement-isds|title=FACT SHEET: Investor-State Dispute Settlement (ISDS) {{!}} United States Trade Representative|website=ustr.gov|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":15\" />\n* Freedom from discrimination: An assurance that those doing business abroad will face a level playing field and will not be treated less favorably than local investors or competitors from other countries.\n* Protection against uncompensated seizure of property: An assurance that property of investors won't be seized by the government without just compensation.\n* Protection against denial of justice: An assurance that investors will not be denied justice in criminal, civil, or administrative adjudicatory proceedings.\n* Right to transfer capital: An assurance that investors will be able to move capital relating to their investments freely, subject to safeguards to provide government flexibility, including to respond to financial crises and ensure the integrity and stability of the financial system.\nISDS cannot overturn local laws (unlike the [[World Trade Organization]]) which violate trade agreements,<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/piie-briefings/assessing-trans-pacific-partnership-volume-1-market-access-and-sectoral|title=Assessing the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Volume 1: Market Access and Sectoral Issues {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibanet.org/Document/Default.aspx?DocumentUid=f30e1893-08fb-4c8e-93bd-eac8442faf5e|title=Investor-state dispute settlement: the importance of an informed, fact-based debate|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=International Bar Association|access-date=}}</ref> but can grant monetary damages to investors adversely affected by such laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jun/10/obscure-legal-system-lets-corportations-sue-states-ttip-icsid|title=The obscure legal system that lets corporations sue countries|newspaper=The Guardian|author= Claire Provost and Matt Kennard|date=10 June 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> As pointed out by the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], ISDS requires specific treaty violations, and does not allow corporations to sue solely over \"lost profits\".<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/blog/2015/march/isds-important-questions-and-answers|title=ISDS: Important Questions and Answers {{!}} United States Trade Representative|website=ustr.gov|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe TPP specifically excludes tobacco industries from the ISDS process.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/trade/tpp-tobacco-exception-proves-new-rule-trade/p37509|title=TPP Tobacco Exception Proves the New Rule in Trade|website=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=17 June 2016}}</ref> The carve-out came as a response to concerns about ISDS cases against anti-smoking laws, including [[Philip Morris v. Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newsweek.com/war-tobacco-makes-it-tpp-free-trade-deal-426206|title=The War on Tobacco Makes It Into the TPP Free Trade Deal|magazine=Newsweek|author= Thomas J. Bollyky |date=13 February 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> The exemption of tobacco from ISDS is a first for an international trade agreement.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nOn the basis of leaks, economists [[Joseph Stiglitz]] and Adam S. Hersh criticized the ISDS provisions of the TPP for interfering with the ability of governments to prevent public harm, alleging that if asbestos been discovered today, governments would have been unable to impose regulations without creating grounds for an ISDS suit.<ref name=StiglitzOct5>{{Citation |last=Stiglitz |first=Joseph |last2=Hersh |first2=Adam S. |author-link=Joseph Stiglitz |date=5 October 2015 |title=Opinion: The Trans-Pacific Partnership charade: TPP isn't about 'free' trade at all |publisher=MarketWatch |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-trans-pacific-partnership-charade-tpp-isnt-about-free-trade-at-all-2015-10-05\n|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref> Stiglitz also claimed that the TPP would give oil companies the right to sue governments for efforts to reduce carbon emissions and [[global warming]].<ref name=StiglitzOct27>{{Citation\n|last=Goodman |first=Amy |last2=Stiglitz |first2=Joseph |author-link=Amy Goodman\n|author-link2=Joseph Stiglitz |date=27 October 2015 |title=Joseph Stiglitz: Under TPP, Polluters Could Sue U.S. for Setting Carbon Emissions Limits |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/10/27/joseph_stiglitz_under_tpp_polluters_could|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Columbia professor [[Jeffrey Sachs]] concluded that the ISDS system of the TPP grants huge power to investors, and damages the judicial systems of all the member countries. He alleges that [[ISDS]] has been already used by corporations to upset governments so as to weaken the regulations that have negative effects on their profits.<ref name=THP11Nov2015JSOTPP>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeffrey-sachs/tpp-flawed-vote-congress_b_8534286.html Why the TPP Is Too Flawed for a 'Yes' Vote in Congress] J. Sachs, ''The Huffington Post'', 11 November 2015</ref> In February 2016, Lise Johnson and Lisa Sachs of the Columbia Center on Sustainable Investment and [[Jeffrey Sachs]] of the Earth Institute allege that foreign corporations can sue a national government in international arbitration over a government's actions if the measures (including those for public health, national security, environment, food and drug, and responses to economic crises) have a negative effect on their profits and economic interests.<ref name=\"cnn190216LJ\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2016/02/19/opinions/tpp-threatens-sustainable-development-sachs/ The real danger in TPP] L. Johnson, L. Sachs and J. Sachs, CNN, 19 February 2016</ref> [[Lori Wallach]] of Public Citizen's [[Global Trade Watch]] raised similar concerns while TPP was being negotiated.<ref name=\"nation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/168627/nafta-steroids#|title=NAFTA on Steroids|date=16 July 2012|last1=Wallach|first1=Lori|work=The Nation|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2016 op-ed against the TPP, Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] used the example of a French company suing Egypt because Egypt raised its minimum wage as an argument against the ISDS provisions of the TPP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/kill-the-dispute-settlement-language-in-the-trans-pacific-partnership/2015/02/25/ec7705a2-bd1e-11e4-b274-e5209a3bc9a9_story.html|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership clause everyone should oppose|last=Warren|first=Elizabeth|date=25 February 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref> The Washington Post editorial board has however challenged this characterization of the case, noting that \"[[Veolia]] of France, a waste management company, invoked ISDS to enforce a contract with the government of [[Alexandria|Alexandria, Egypt]], that it says required compensation if costs increased; the company maintains that the wage increases triggered this provision. Incidentally, Veolia was working with Alexandria on a [[World Bank]]-supported project to reduce greenhouse gases, not some corporate plot to exploit the people. The case \u2014 which would result, at most, in a monetary award to Veolia, not the overthrow of the minimum wage \u2014 remains in litigation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/dont-buy-the-trade-deal-alarmism/2015/03/11/41575fee-c1d5-11e4-9271-610273846239_story.html|title=Don't buy the trade deal alarmism|last=Board|first=Editorial|date=11 March 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] challenges the notion that ISDS challenges \"the sovereign ability of governments impose any measure they wish to protect labor rights, the environment, or other issues of public welfare\".<ref name=\":15\" /> The [[International Bar Association|International Bar Association (IBA)]] mirrors these sentiments, noting that \"while investment treaties limit states\u2019 ability to inflict arbitrary or discriminatory treatment, they do not limit (and, in fact, expressly safeguard) a state's sovereign right to regulate in the public interest in a fair, reasonable and non-discriminatory manner.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> The [[White House Office|White House]] notes that investment protections are a component of more than 3,000 trade agreements, the vast majority of which have some form of neutral arbitration.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/02/26/investor-state-dispute-settlement-isds-questions-and-answers|title=Investor-State Dispute Settlement (ISDS) Questions and Answers|date=26 February 2015|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> The United States is party to at least 50 such agreements, has only faced 13 ISDS cases and never lost an ISDS case.<ref name=\":17\" /> The White House asserts that the ISDS components of the TPP are an upgrade and improvement on ISDS in other trade agreements: TPP makes it absolutely clear that governments can regulate in the public interest (including with regard to health, safety and the environment); TPP includes the ability to dismiss frivolous claims quickly and award fees against the claimant to deter such suits; sham corporations will be prevented from accessing the investment protections; and arbitration proceedings under TPP will be open to the public and allow for inputs from non-parties.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] argues that \"the ISDS provisions in the TPP are a significant improvement over those in previous agreements\".<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE notes that the ISDS mechanism in the TPP respects environmental, health, and safety regulation; ensures the transparency of dispute proceedings; and eliminates [[forum shopping]].<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE asserts that some of the innovations in the ISDS provisions of TPP \"are generally disliked by the US business community.\"<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE claims that ISDS provisions are necessary, as they boost investment: \"empirical evidence has shown that treaties including these provisions have a positive effect on foreign direct investment (FDI) flows between signatory countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/blogs/trade-investment-policy-watch/what-do-data-say-about-relationship-between-investor-state|title=What Do the Data Say about the Relationship between Investor-State Dispute Settlement Provisions and FDI? {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> PIIE challenges the claim that ISDS \"arbitrators lack integrity\", noting that arbitrators take an oath of impartiality and both sides of a case choose arbitrators.<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE agrees \"that secrecy has gone too far\" in many ISDS cases, but notes that \"TPP negotiators heeded this criticism\" and opened up ISDS cases to greater transparency.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nAccording to the [[International Bar Association|International Bar Association (IBA)]], states have won a higher percentage of ISDS cases than investors, and that around one-third of all cases end in settlement.<ref name=\":27\" /> Claimant investors, when successful, recover on average less than half of the amounts claimed.<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that \"only 8 per cent of ISDS proceedings are commenced by very large multinational corporations.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA challenges the notion that ISDS is biased against developing countries, noting that there is \"no correlation between the success rates of claims against states and their income levels or development status.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that ISDS is necessary even in countries with sophisticated domestic legal systems because those domestic courts rule according to domestic laws, not international law.<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that \"increasingly, awards require the losing party to pay arbitration costs and legal fees to the winning party\", which deters investors from initiating unmeritorious cases.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\n=== Labour standards ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP imposes \"binding and fully enforceable obligations\" on signatories to \"protect the freedom to form unions and bargain collectively\" and \"eliminate exploitative child labor and forced labor protect against employment discrimination\".<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#protecting-workers|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#protecting-workers|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The obligations include \"laws on acceptable conditions of work related to minimum wages, hours of work, and occupational safety and health.\"<ref name=\":21\" /> The USTR insists that if countries like Malaysia and Vietnam do not enforce provisions relating to forced labor, human trafficking and collective bargaining, they will cease to get the economic benefits of the TPP agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership/frequently-asked-questions-on-the-trans-pacific-partnership-eddc8d87ac73#.7j4pdoi5g|title=Will TPP promote higher labor standards?|last=Representative|first=U. S. Trade|date=5 November 2015|website=Medium|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629204511/https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership/frequently-asked-questions-on-the-trans-pacific-partnership-eddc8d87ac73#.7j4pdoi5g|archivedate=29 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] asserts that \"the TPP includes more protections of labor rights than any previous US free trade agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/newsroom/short-videos/labor-standards-tpp|title=Labor Standards in the TPP {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, [[Human Rights Watch]] said that the TPP side agreements with Vietnam, Malaysia, and Brunei \"are a unique and significant step in efforts to protect labor rights in trade agreements\" but noted that enforcement of these rules remains to be seen: \"gauging compliance will require subjective assessments by the US that may take years to carry out and face obstacles arising from foreign policy objectives, commercial interests, and other political considerations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2016/01/12/qa-trans-pacific-partnership#4|title=Q&A: The Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=12 January 2016|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDartmouth economics Professor Emily J. Blanchard argues that while the TPP has been roundly criticized on the political left, progressives should actually be supportive of the TPP: \"The TPP\u2019s promise of a new progressive rule book \u2013 one that includes enforceable agreements against child labor and workplace discrimination, measures to punish illegal logging and trade in protected species, and protections against consumer fraud \u2013 would mark a substantial step forward in the progressive policy agenda on the global stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-progressives-should-rescue-the-tpp-trade-deal-60304|title=Why progressives should rescue the TPP trade deal|last=Blanchard|first=Emily J.|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, U.S. congressman [[Sander Levin]] argued that it is difficult to enforce trade deals, as he questioned Vietnam's willingness to meet the labour standards of TPP.<ref name=\"TG21May2015SLOTPP\">[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/may/21/trans-pacific-partnership-obama-trade-deal-asia-workers Trans-Pacific Partnership won't improve workers' rights in Asia, critics warn] S. Greenhouse, The Guardian, 21 May 2015</ref> A report by U.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] said that there was a huge gap between the labor standards of past US free trade agreements and the actual enforcement of those provisions.<ref name=\"TG21May2015SLOTPP\" /> However, PIIE analysts note that research shows that the presence of \"sticks\" (a possible suspension of trade benefits) and \"carrots\" (technical assistance) in trade deals increase the likelihood that labor obligations in trade deals have a positive effect; there are both sticks and carrots present in TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/piie-briefings/assessing-trans-pacific-partnership-volume-2-innovations-trading-rules|title=Assessing the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Volume 2: Innovations in Trading Rules {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Regulatory cooperation ===\nEven though the TPP has yet to be passed, the agreement has already introduced forms of regulatory cooperation for agriculture beyond that found in the WTO.<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/08/30/the-sky-fell-on-the-u-s-poultry-industry-last-year-but-nafta-and-the-tpp-helped-protect-u-s-exports/|title=The sky fell on the U.S. poultry industry last year. But NAFTA and the TPP helped protect U.S. exports.|website=Washington Post|access-date=30 August 2016}}</ref> This means that regulators in different TPP signatories have been engaging with each other and building trust.<ref name=\":31\" /> Chad P. Bown, senior fellow at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, argues that this regulatory cooperation meant that the US poultry industry was not as hard-hit by the [[2015 United States H5N2 outbreak|2015 bird flu outbreak]], as regulators in TPP countries cooperated and continued to accept US exports of poultry.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n== Economic impact ==\nThe [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]], the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], the [[World Bank]] and the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada found that the final agreement would, if ratified, lead to net positive economic outcomes for all signatories, while a [[Heterodox economics|heterodox]] analysis by two [[Tufts University]] economists found that the agreement would adversely affect the signatories.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" />\n\n=== Effects on economic equality ===\nIn 2013, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel]] Memorial prize-winning economist [[Joseph Stiglitz]] warned that, based on leaked drafts of the TPP, it \"serves the interests of the wealthiest.\"<ref name=\"NYT-20140315\">{{cite news|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/15/on-the-wrong-side-of-globalization|title=On the Wrong Side of Globalization|last=Stiglitz|first=Joseph E.|date=15 March 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Joseph Stiglitz|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/secrecy-surrounds-transpacific-partnership-talks-20131208-2yzea.html|title=Secrecy surrounds Trans-Pacific Partnership talks|date=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> Organised labour in the U.S. argued, during the negotiations, that the trade deal would largely benefit corporations at the expense of workers in the manufacturing and service industries.<ref>[https://www.msnbc.com/the-ed-show/watch/fighting-tpp-to-protect-workers-rights-87825475756 \"Fighting TPP to protect workers' rights\"]. ''[[The Ed Show]]''. 11 December 2013. Retrieved 17 December 2013.</ref> The [[Economic Policy Institute]] and the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] have argued that the TPP could result in job losses and declining wages.<ref>[http://www.epi.org/publication/trade-pacts-korus-trans-pacific-partnership/ \"No Jobs from Trade Pacts: The Trans-Pacific Partnership Could Be Much Worse than the Over-Hyped Korea Deal\"]. [[Economic Policy Institute]]. 18 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.cepr.net/index.php/publications/reports/net-effect-of-the-tpp-on-us-wages \"Gains from Trade? The Net Effect of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement on U.S. Wages\"]. [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]. September 2013</ref>\n\nEconomists Peter A. Petri and Michael G. Plummer challenge the view that TPP will primarily benefit the wealthy. Their analysis finds that \"the gains from TPP appear to be fairly distributed\u2014labour will gain relative to capital, and cost reductions will favour low-income households. Some workers will need to change jobs, but they constitute a small fraction of normal job churn in any given year, and the national benefits argue for generous compensation for their adjustment costs. The agreement will also benefit workers in TPP's poorest member countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voxeu.org/article/economics-tpp-winners-and-losers|title=Economics of the Trans-Pacific Partnership: Distributional impact|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref> Research by Harvard economist Robert Z. Lawrence finds that the \"percentage gains for labor income from the TPP will be slightly greater than the gains to capital income. Households in all quintiles will benefit by similar percentages, but once differences in spending shares are taken into account, the percentage gains to poor and middle-class households will be slightly larger than the gains to households at the top.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/adjustment-and-income-distribution-impacts-trans-pacific-partnership|title=Adjustment and Income Distribution Impacts of the Trans-Pacific Partnership {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/04/why-the-tpp-has-benefits-for-workers-that-far-outweigh-its-costs/|title=Why the TPP has benefits for workers that far outweighs its costs|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> An opinion piece by Ed Gerwin in the Wall Street Journal argues that the TPP agreement benefits small businesses in the US.<ref name=\"WSJ11272015\" />\n\nEconomists [[David Autor]], David Dorn and [[Gordon Hanson|Gordon H. Hanson]], who have extensively studied US labor markets adjustments to [[China shock|trade competition shocks caused by China]],<ref>{{cite journal |first=David H. |last=Autor |first2=David |last2=Dorn |first3=Gordon H. |last3=Hanson |year=2016 |title=The China Shock: Learning from Labor Market Adjustment to Large Changes in Trade |journal=Annual Review of Economics |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=205\u2013240 |doi=10.1146/annurev-economics-080315-015041 |url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w21906.pdf }}</ref> support TPP.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/03/12/why-obamas-key-trade-deal-with-asia-would-actually-be-good-for-american-workers/|title=Why Obama's key trade deal with Asia would actually be good for American workers|website=Washington Post|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> They argue that TPP \"would promote trade in knowledge-intensive services in which U.S. companies exert a strong comparative advantage\", note that \"killing the TPP would do little to bring factory work back to America\" and argue that it would pressure China to raise regulatory rules and standards to those of TPP members.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nAccording to the [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]], the TPP will have positive effects on the U.S. economy as a whole, with unskilled labor reaping 25% of the gains, skilled workers 41% and business owners 34%.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/business/economy/why-dropping-the-trans-pacific-partnership-may-be-a-bad-idea.html|title=Why Dropping the Trans-Pacific Partnership May Be a Bad Idea|last=Porter|first=Eduardo|date=26 July 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Macroeconomics===\n==== World Bank report ====\n[[World Bank]] found that if ratified by signatories, the TPP \"agreement could raise GDP in member countries by an average of 1.1 percent by 2030. It could also increase member countries' trade by 11 percent by 2030, and represent a boost to regional trade growth, which had slowed to about 5 percent, on average, during 2010-14 from about 10 percent during 1990-07.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf|title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=World Bank|access-date=}}</ref> The World Bank finds that the agreement will raise real wages in all signatories: \"In the United States, for example, changes in real wages are expected to be small as unskilled and skilled wages increase by 0.4 and 0.6 percent, respectively, by 2030. In contrast, in Vietnam, TPP could increase the real wages of unskilled workers by more than 14 percent by 2030, as production intensive in unskilled labor (e.g. textiles) shifts to Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== U.S. International Trade Commission estimate ====\nThe [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]] estimates that \"TPP would have positive effects, albeit small as a percentage of the overall size of the U.S. economy\".<ref name=\":2\"/> There will be 128,000 more full-time jobs.<ref name=\":25\" /> By 2032, U.S. annual real income would increase by 0.23%, real GDP would be $42.7 billion or 0.15% higher, employment would be 0.07% higher, US exports would increase 1%, and imports would increase 1.1%.<ref name=\":2\"/> The report added, \"TPP would generally establish trade-related disciplines that strengthen and harmonize regulations, increase certainty, and decrease trade costs for firms that trade and invest in the TPP region.\"<ref name=\":2\"/> Vietnam is often seen as the biggest beneficiary of TPP.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-08/more-shoes-and-shrimp-less-china-reliance-for-vietnam-in-tpp|title=The Biggest Winner From TPP Trade Deal May Be Vietnam|last=svwriter|first=John Boudreau|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/03/why-vietnam-loves-the-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Why Vietnam Loves the Trans-Pacific Partnership|last=Diplomat|first=Dien Luong, The|website=The Diplomat|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Michael J.|last2=Goodman|first2=Matthew P.|date=2 October 2015|title=After TPP: the Geopolitics of Asia and the Pacific|journal=The Washington Quarterly|volume=38|issue=4|pages=19\u201334|doi=10.1080/0163660X.2015.1125827|issn=0163-660X}}</ref> The U.S. International Trade Commission identifies the following US industries as net beneficiaries of TPP: Passenger cars; Apparel, Dairy production; Retailers and Wholesalers; and Business services; and as net losers: Auto parts; Textiles; Soybean production; Transportation and tourism; and Chemicals and drugs.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2016/05/19/ten-winning-and-losing-industries-from-the-pacific-trade-deal/|title=Ten Winning and Losing Industries from the Pacific Trade Deal|last=Mauldin|first=William|website=WSJ|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada report ====\nAccording to a report by the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada, ratification of TPP would increase Canada's GDP by $4.3 billion by 2040.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/not-joining-tpp-will-cost-canada-billions-in-economic-growth-report/article31809986/|title=Not joining TPP will cost Canada billions in economic growth: report|access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref> This is primarily due to the preferential access it would receive to markets in the Asia-Pacific rim.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\" />  According to the report, ratification by the other TPP signatories but a failure by Canada to ratify the agreement would lead Canada to face estimated GDP losses of $5.3 billion by 2040.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\" />\n\n==== Peterson Institute for International Economics report ====\nEconomists Peter A. Petri and Michael G. Plummer of the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] project that the TPP would increase incomes in the U.S. by $131 billion annually, or 0.5 percent of GDP.  Exports from the U.S. would increase by $357 billion annually, or 9.1 percent, as a result of the agreement.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|last1=Hufbauer|first1=Gary Clyde|title=Column: Why the Trans-Pacific Partnership isn't a bum deal|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/making-sense/column-why-the-trans-pacific-partnership-isnt-a-bum-deal/|publisher=PBS|date=5 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>  However, two [[Tufts University]] economists argue that the research by Petri relies on unrealistic assumptions such as full employment: lost jobs will be immediately replaced in other industrial sectors.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\">[http://www.ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/wp/16-01Capaldo-IzurietaTPP.pdf Trading Down:Unemployment, Inequality and Other Risks of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement] J. Capaldo and A. Izurieta, Global Development and Environment Institute, Working Paper No. 16\u20131 Jan (2016)</ref> According to Harvard economist [[Dani Rodrik]], \"Petri and Plummer assume that labor markets are sufficiently flexible that job losses in adversely affected parts of the economy are necessarily offset by job gains elsewhere. Unemployment is ruled out from the start \u2013 a built-in outcome of the model that TPP proponents often fudge.\"<ref name=\":3\"/> Rodrik notes that \"the Petri-Plummer model is squarely rooted in decades of academic trade modeling, which makes a sharp distinction between microeconomic effects (shaping resource allocation across sectors) and macroeconomic effects (related to overall levels of demand and employment). In this tradition, trade liberalization is a microeconomic \"shock\" that affects the composition of employment, but not its overall level.\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n==== Tufts University report ====\n[[Tufts University]] researchers project the TPP would have a negative impact on employment: 450,000 US jobs, 75,000 Japanese jobs, 58,000 Canadian jobs and 5,000 New Zealand jobs would be lost by 2025.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" /> According to the report, 771,000 jobs would be lost in total and positive economic effects would be negligible for participating countries.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" /><ref name=nytimes01Feb2016JC>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/business/international/economists-sharply-split-over-trade-deal-effects.html Economists Sharply Split Over Trade Deal Effects] J. Calmes, The New York Times, 1 February 2016</ref>\n\nHarvard economist [[Robert Z. Lawrence]] says that the model used by the Tufts researchers \"is simply not suited for credibly predicting the effects of the TPP\" and argues that the model used by Petri and Plummer is superior.<ref name=\":0\"/> Lawrence argues that the model used by the Tufts researchers \"does not have the granularity that allows it to estimate variables such as exports, imports, foreign direct investment, and changes in industrial structure. As a result, its predictions ignore the benefits to the TPP economies that occur through increased specialization, the realization of scale economies, and improved consumer choice.\"<ref name=\":0\"/> Lawrence also notes that the model used by the Tufts researchers finds that the TPP will cause GDP to fall by 5.24% in non-TPP developing countries, such as China, India, and Indonesia, which Lawrence is highly skeptical of: \"It is not believable that a trade agreement of this magnitude could cause the rest of the world to plummet into recession.\"<ref name=\":0\"/> Harvard economist [[Dani Rodrik]], a well-known skeptic of globalization, says that the Tufts researchers do \"a poor job of explaining how their model works, and the particulars of their simulation are somewhat murky... the Capaldo framework lacks sectoral and country detail; its behavioral assumptions remain opaque; and its extreme Keynesian assumptions sit uneasily with its medium-term perspective.\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n[[Fredrik Erixon]] and Matthias Bauer of the [[ECIPE|European Centre for International Political Economy (ECIPE)]] write that the Tufts analysis has such serious flaws \"that its results should neither be regarded reliable nor realistic.\"<ref name=\":30\"/> They write that Tufts model is \"by and large a demand-driven model that does not make efforts to capture the supply-side effects of trade, which are the effects that are proven to be the core positive effects of trade liberalisation. Equally problematic, the model is not designed to assess the effect on trade from trade agreements \u2013 in fact, the model is profoundly ill suited for such an exercise. No trade economist, regardless what school of thought he or she comes from, has ever used this model to make estimates of trade. The reason is simple: if a model cannot predict the effects on the flows and profile of trade as a consequence of trade liberalisation, it is of no use at all.\"<ref name=\":30\"/> They add, \"In Capaldo\u2019s analysis, structural change and the emergence of new industries do not play a role at all. Capaldo implicitly assumes that an economy with its labour and capital does not respond and adjust to new circumstances. New competition only leads to new unemployment. In addition, the impact of lower barriers on international commerce on product and process innovation is neglected. Finally, Capaldo does not account for the impact of competition on the cost of production and final consumer prices.\"<ref name=\":30\"/>\n\nAccording to the Congressional Research Service, \"The Tufts study has drawn particular criticism as an unconventional framework for analyzing trade agreements, whereas Computable General Equilibrium (CGE) models, such as that used in the Peterson study are standard in trade policy analysis.\"<ref name=\":8\"/> Fabio Ghironi, Professor in Economics at the [[University of Washington]], describes the models used by the World Bank and the Peterson Institute in more favorable terms than the Tufts analysis.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Effects on the European Union ===\nThe EU is trying to form trade agreements with each country that is part of the TPP: since 2013, there have been talks of a free trade agreement between the EU and Japan, and in 2015 the EU presented its new strategy to improve trade in the Asia-Pacific entitled \"Trade for All.\"<ref name=\"European Parliamentary Research Service\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/582028/EPRS_BRI(2016)582028_EN.pdf|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Potential regional and global impacts|author= Krisztina Binder|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberalization ===\nAccording to an analysis by the Cato Institute of the chapters of the TPP, 15 chapters have a liberalizing impact, 5 have a protectionist impact, and 2 have a neutral impact.<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/publications/working-paper/should-free-traders-support-trans-pacific-partnership-assessment-americas|title=Should Free Traders Support the Trans- Pacific Partnership? An Assessment of America's Largest Preferential Trade Agreement|date=12 September 2016|access-date=13 September 2016}}</ref> Considered as a whole, the terms of the TPP are net liberalizing.<ref name=\":34\" />\n\nThere have been conflicting arguments on whether or not the TPP aims to increase the liberalization of trade. For arguments that propose that the TPP succeeds at liberalizing trade among the participating nations, there is a question of whether or not this causes a positive or a negative net change. Some scholars argue that participatory members of the TPP believe that such membership is a utilitarian and practical method toward new trade liberalization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Meredith|year=2011|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership: New Paradigm or Wolf in Sheep's Clothing?|ssrn=1908411|journal=Boston College International & Comparative Law Review|volume=34|pages=|via=}}</ref> Scholars Peter Petri and Michael Plummer describe the TPP as a \"dynamic process - and example of competitive liberalization,\" and this liberalization described can result in a new type of governance for the Asia-Pacific, as well as transnational trade.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Petri|first=Peter|last2=Plummer|first2=Michael|year=2012|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership and Asia-Pacific Integration: Policy Implications|url=|journal=Peterson Institute for International Economics Policy Brief|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to analyst and economist B.R. Williams, the United States has a large role in the reduction of trade barriers and increased U.S. investment. Williams explains that the U.S. aims to create a \"broader platform for trade liberalization, particularly throughout the Asia-Pacific region.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Williams|first=B.R.|year=2013|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) countries: Comparative trade and economic analysis|url=|journal=Washington, D.C.: Congressional Research Service|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Scholars C. Li and J. Whalley explore a numerical approach in explaining the liberalizing effects of the TPP. Li and Whalley uses a quantitative equilibrium simulation to explore the effects of the TPP on the liberalization of trade and new markets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=C|last2=Whalley|first2=J|year=2014|title=China and the Trans-Pacific Partnership: A Numerical Simulation Assessment of the Effects Involved|url=|journal=World Economics|volume=37|issue=2|pages=169\u2013192|doi=10.1111/twec.12123}}</ref>\n\n== Geopolitics ==\nTPP increases the likelihood that Japan will undertake economic reforms to revive its economy, which coupled with potential South-Korean accession to the TPP, might have an economic impact on China. By making the Chinese economy less competitive and Chinese leadership less likely to write the rules of trade in East and Southeast Asia, the Chinese regime will be under great internal and external pressure to liberalize its economy.<ref name=\":6\"/> Japan's prime minister, [[Shinz\u014d Abe|Shinzo Abe]], believes that future Chinese accession to TPP would have a major pacifying impact on the Asia-Pacific region.<ref name=\":7\"/> U.S. Trade Representative [[Michael Froman]] has said that a failure to ratify TPP would give China the opportunity to boost its exports and set labor and environmental standards in the fast-growing Asia Pacific region through the [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trade-idUSKCN1090QZ |title=Killing TPP would hand China 'keys to the castle': U.S. trade representative |date=29 July 2016 |newspaper=Reuters |access-date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nSouth Korea did not participate in TPP \"largely out of a concern to maintain balance in its economic relations with China and the United States\" but has shown greater interest in joining TPP after Japan, its biggest economic competitor, decided to participate.<ref name=\":9\" /> Also, the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, and Taiwan have reportedly been considering and implementing various domestic reforms to improve their prospects for eventually joining.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nSince formal TPP negotiations began in 2010, China's attitude towards TPP has:\n\n<blockquote>swung from disdain to suspicion to cautious embrace... Conclusion of a TPP agreement in early October has sparked a lively debate in Beijing, with the weight of elite opinion seeming to tilt toward eventual membership; for example, the head of the Chinese-sponsored Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB), Jin Liqun, announced his support during a speech in Washington shortly after the TPP deal was announced.<ref name=\":9\" /></blockquote>\n\nThe TPP may give renewed impetus to trade negotiations among China, Japan, and Korea, and increase the likelihood of [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP) which could provide a possible pathway to a [[free trade area]] of the Asia-Pacific.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nIn January 2016, the [[National Association of Manufacturers]] announced its support for TPP, saying \"without such an agreement, the United States would be ceding economic leadership to other global powers, letting them set the rules of economic engagement in the region\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/policy/finance/264631-manufacturers-endorse-tpp |title=Big Endorsement for Obama Trade Deal |newspaper=The Hill |last1=Needham |first1=Vicki |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 study by [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] political scientists Todd Allee and Andrew Lugg suggests that if the TPP becomes standard legal text, it will shape future trade cooperation and agreements.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nAn October 2016 survey of [[international relations]] scholars showed that the overwhelming majority supported the TPP.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trip.wm.edu/charts/#/bargraph/42/6771 |title=TRIP Data Viewer |website=trip.wm.edu |access-date=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== United States considerations ===\nThe original TPP was thought by some to likely bring China's neighbours closer to the United States and reduce their dependence on Chinese trade.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/10/07/china-tpp-trans-pacific-partnership-obama-us-trade-xi/ |title=What Will the TPP Mean for China? |website=Foreign Policy |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/world/asia/trans-pacific-partnership-china-australia.html |title=U.S. Allies See Trans-Pacific Partnership as a Check on China |last=Perlez |first=Jane |date=6 October 2015|newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://belfercenter.hks.harvard.edu/publication/26627/trade_is_a_national_security_imperative.html |title=Trade Is a National Security Imperative - Harvard - Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs |website=belfercenter.hks.harvard.edu |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/foreign-policy/asia/geopolitical-necessity-trade/ |title=The Geopolitical Necessity of Trade |last=Boot |first=Max |date= |website= |access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news |url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/the-death-tpp-the-best-thing-ever-happened-china-19232?page=show |title=The Death of TPP: The Best Thing That Ever Happened to China |last=Magnusson |first=Earl Anthony Wayne, Oliver |newspaper=The National Interest |language=en |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\"foreignpolicy.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/05/03/this-isnt-realpolitik-this-is-amateur-hour/|title=This Isn't Realpolitik. This Is Amateur Hour. |website=Foreign Policy|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/11/06/trump-will-be-haunted-by-the-ghost-of-tpp-in-asia/ |title=Trump Will Be Haunted by the Ghost of TPP |website=Foreign Policy |access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref> If ratified, the TPP would have strengthened American influence on future rules for the global economy. US Secretary of Defense [[Ash Carter]] claimed the passage of the TPP to be as valuable to the United States as the creation of another aircraft carrier.<ref name=\":9\" /> President Obama has argued \"if we don't pass this agreement\u2014if America doesn't write those rules\u2014then countries like China will\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/06/business/international/trans-pacific-trade-deal-tpp-vietnam-labor-rights.html |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Text Released, Waving Green Flag for Debate |last=Calmes |first=Jackie |date=5 November 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> According to the Congressional Research Service, \"many Asian policymakers\u2014correctly or not\u2014could interpret a failure of TPP in the United States as a symbol of declining U.S. interest in the region and inability to assert leadership... failure to conclude TPP could, in effect, allow China to shape regional rules of commerce and diplomacy through its own trade and investment initiatives, potentially creating regional rules and norms less beneficial for U.S. interests.\"<ref name=\":8\"/> [[Michael Green (political expert)|Michael J. Green]] and Matthew P. Goodman argue that \"history will be unforgiving if TPP fails... If Congress rejects TPP, trying to negotiate a similar arrangement in Asia would reopen demands on the United States\u2014and in the meantime, would likely give impetus to alternative arrangements like RCEP that exclude the United States. Momentum behind the U.S.-led international order would shift to momentum against it. Future generations of historians will take note of U.S. leadership at this moment.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Dan Ikenson, director of Cato's Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies, argued in July 2016 that the \"failure of Congress to ratify the Trans-Pacific Partnership this year would do more to subvert U.S. regional and global interests than anything China is capable of doing.\"<ref name=\":29\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/the-trans-pacific-partnership-is-essential-to-regional-peace |title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership Is Essential to Regional Peace and Global Prosperity |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> [[Stephen Walt|Stephen M. Walt]], professor of international relations at Harvard University, writing after the Trump Administration abandoned the TPP, described the TPP as \"a key institution that would have bound a number of Asian countries more tightly to the United States\".<ref name=\"foreignpolicy.com\"/>\n\n=== Non-TPP party opinions ===\nOn 30 January 2015 [[Philip Hammond]], the former [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom]], described the Trans-Pacific Partnership and the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership as \"potentially important liberalising steps forward\".<ref>Hammond, P., [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/foreign-secretarys-speech-on-the-uk-in-asia-pacific \"Foreign Secretary's speech on the UK in Asia Pacific\"] Foreign & Commonwealth Office, UK, 30 January 2015, accessed 8 October 2015</ref>\n\nThe [[European Centre for International Political Economy]] (ECIPE), a think tank on European policies, predicted in 2012 that the TPP would be a \"deadly threat to European exporters of agricultural products in TPP countries\".<ref>Messerlin, Patrick, [http://www.ecipe.org/media/publication_pdfs/Messerlin_TPP-EU_EN05212.pdf The TPP and the EU policy in East Asia], ECIPE Policy Brief, no.11/2012, European Centre for International Political Economy, {{ISSN|1653-8994}}.</ref>\n\nECIPE has said in 2014 that TPP \"will be the first 'competing' [[economic integration]] that is large enough to have a considerable negative impact on Europe. In the long-term, the negative effects will come from dynamic impact, e.g. on investment, productivity and competitiveness\".<ref name=ecipe14>Matthias Bauer, Fredrik Erixon, Martina Ferracane and Hosuk Lee-Makiyama [http://www.ecipe.org/app/uploads/2014/12/PB09_1.pdf TRANS-PACIFIC PARTNERSHIP: A challenge to Europe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315115352/http://www.ecipe.org/app/uploads/2014/12/PB09_1.pdf |date=15 March 2016 }} ECIPE Policy Briefs, No.9/2014, page 1-13, European Centre for International Political Economy, {{ISSN|1653-8994}}</ref>\n[[Pascal Lamy]] called the TPP \"the last of big old-style trade agreements\".<ref name=ecipe14/>{{rp|2}}\n\nRussian Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev]] has been critical of TPP, saying that \"the WTO is being encroached upon\" and this might lead to the \"destruction of world trade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/business/20160802/1043873347/wto-tpp-ttip-russia.html|title=Russian Prime Minister Medvedev Says TPP, TTIP 'Encroaching on WTO'|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com|access-date=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism{{anchor|Protests}} ==\nNobel Memorial Prize-winning economist [[Paul Krugman]] has said that \"there isn't a compelling case for this deal, from either a global or a national point of view.\"<ref name=\"NYT-20140227\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/opinion/krugman-no-big-deal.html|title=No Big Deal|last=Krugman|first=Paul|date=27 February 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Paul Krugman|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, [[United Nations]]' human rights expert [[Alfred de Zayas]] argued that the TPP was fundamentally flawed and was based on an outdated model of trade pacts, and that governments should not sign or ratify the TPP.<ref name=RT02022016>[https://www.rt.com/usa/331051-tpp-un-human-rights/ TPP 'fundamentally flawed,' should be resisted - UN human rights expert] RT, 2 February 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=17006 UN expert urges Pacific Rim countries not to sign the TPP without committing to human rights and development] OHCHR, 2 February 2016</ref> According to de Zayas, the international human rights regime imposes binding legal obligations on countries, including the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] and the [[International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights]], and trade must be done under the human rights regime. Under the ISDS in the TPP, investors can sue a government, while a government cannot sue investors. De Zayas argued that this asymmetry made the system unfair. He added that international law, including accountability and transparency, must prevail over trade pacts.<ref name=RT02022016 />\n\n=== Currency manipulation ===\nSome critics and even supporters of the TPP wanted the deal to contain measures that would crack down on nations who engage in alleged [[currency manipulation]], notably China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/chinas-impact-looms-large-u-s-debates-trade-deals/|title=China's impact looms large as U.S. debates its own trade deals|language=en-US|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> However, [[Daniel W. Drezner|Daniel Drezner]], professor of international politics at Tufts University, has argued that the trade deal was never likely to include restrictions on currency manipulation, as it would have restricted U.S. monetary policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/10/08/is-hillary-clinton-right-about-the-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Is Hillary Clinton right about the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|website=Washington Post|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> Harvard economist [[Jeffrey Frankel]] has argued that the inclusion of currency manipulation language in TPP would be a mistake.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=http://econbrowser.com/archives/2015/06/the-top-ten-reasons-why-trade-agreements-should-not-cover-currency-manipulation|title=\"The Top Ten Reasons Why Trade Agreements Should Not Cover Currency Manipulation\" {{!}} Econbrowser|website=econbrowser.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> Frankel noted that currency manipulation would be hard to enforce (in part because it is impossible to tell whether a currency is overvalued or undervalued); \"currency manipulation\" can often be legitimate; China, often alleged to be a major currency manipulator, is not party to the TPP; currency manipulation accusations are often meritless; and because it would restrict U.S. monetary policy.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Length and complexity ===\n[[Donald Trump]] has criticized the TPP agreement for being too long and complicated, saying, \"[i]t\u2019s 5,600 pages long, so complex that nobody\u2019s read it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-is-upset-1447374770|title=Donald Trump Is Upset|date=13 November 2015|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] has charged that the \"TPP is much more than a \u2018free trade\u2019 agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://feelthebern.org/bernie-sanders-on-trade/|title=Bernie Sanders on Trade|last=FeelTheBern.org|language=en-US|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Georgetown University]] Professor Marc L. Busch and [[McGill University]] Professor Krzysztof J. Pelc note that modern trade deals are long and complex because they often tackle [[non-tariff barriers to trade]], such as different standards and regulations, in addition to [[tariff]]s. Due to steadily decreasing tariff barriers since WWII, countries have become increasingly likely to enact trade barriers in the form of non-tariff barriers. National firms often lobby their own governments to enact regulations that are designed to keep out foreign firms. The TPP addresses many of these \"disguised restrictions on trade\" by, for instance, \"basing these measures on agreed-upon science; making the process of formulating regulations more transparent; and giving foreign exporters opportunities to offer substantive input in the formulation of these measures.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/08/02/yes-the-tpp-agreement-is-over-5000-pages-long-heres-why-thats-a-good-thing/|title=Yes, the TPP agreement is over 5,000 pages long. Here's why that's a good thing.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Secrecy of negotiations ===\nAs with many trade agreements, until being finalized, negotiations for the TPP were conducted with significant secrecy. Drafts of the agreement were kept classified during negotiations, and access to the working text was significantly restricted even for government officials and business representatives involved in the talks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/secrecy-eroding-support-for-trade-pact-critics-say-117581|title=Extreme secrecy eroding support for Obama's trade pact|publisher=Politico|author=Edward-Isaac Dovere|date=4 May 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Despite this, some sections of TPP drafts were leaked to the public by [[WikiLeaks]], which published an intellectual property chapter draft in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |title=Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) |url=https://wikileaks.org/tpp/ |accessdate=13 November 2013 |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date=13 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/nov/13/wikileaks-trans-pacific-partnership-chapter-secret |title=WikiLeaks publishes secret draft chapter of Trans-Pacific Partnership |first=Steven |last=Musil |work=The Guardian (UK) |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> an environmental chapter draft in 2014,<ref>{{cite press release |title=Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) \u2013 Environment Chapter |url=https://wikileaks.org/tpp-enviro/pressrelease.html |accessdate=11 January 2014 |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date=14 January 2014}}</ref> and the final intellectual property chapter in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Release \u2013 Updated Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) \u2013 IP Chapter (second publication) |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/tpp-ip2/pressrelease/ |date= 26 October 2014 |work=[[WikiLeaks]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, critics such as Public Citizen's [[Global Trade Watch]], a consumer advocacy group, called for more open negotiations in regard to the agreement. U.S. Trade Representative Ron Kirk responded that he believes the Office of the United States Trade Representative (USTR) conducted \"the most engaged and transparent process as we possibly could\", but that \"some measure of discretion and confidentiality\" are needed \"to preserve negotiating strength and to encourage our partners to be willing to put issues on the table they may not otherwise.\"<ref name=\"reuters_1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/14/us-usa-trade-kirk-idUSBRE84C0AQ20120514?feedType=RSS&feedName=everything&virtualBrandChannel=11563|title=Some secrecy needed in trade talks: Ron Kirk|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=13 May 2012|last=Palmer|first=Doug}}</ref> He dismissed the \"tension\" as natural and noted that when the [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]] drafts were released, negotiators were subsequently unable to reach a final agreement.<ref name=\"reuters_1\" />\n\nOn 23 May 2012, U.S. Senator [[Ron Wyden]], Democrat of Oregon, introduced {{USBill|112|s|3225}}, which would have required the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative to disclose its TPP documents to all members of Congress.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/s3225| title=S. 3225 (112th)| accessdate=30 May 2012| author=112th Congress (2012)| date=23 May 2012| work=Legislation| publisher=GovTrack.us| quote=A bill to require the United States Trade Representative to provide documents relating to trade negotiations to Members of Congress and their staff upon request, and for other purposes.}}</ref> Had it passed, Wyden said that the bill would increase Congressional access to information about USTR activity.<ref name=\"Wyden20120523\">{{USCongRec|2012|S3517|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael R. Wessel]], former commissioner on the U.S. Trade Deficit Review Commission claimed in May 2015 that \"cleared advisors\" like himself were \"prohibited from sharing publicly the criticisms we\u2019ve lodged about specific proposals and approaches\". He claimed that only portions of the text had been provided, \"to be read under the watchful eye of a USTR official\", that access on secure government-run website did not contain the most-up-to-date information, and that for cleared advisors to get that information, he had \"to travel to certain government facilities and sign in to read the materials\" and \"even then, the administration determines what we can and cannot review and, often, they provide carefully edited summaries rather than the actual underlying text, which is critical to really understanding the consequences of the agreement.\"<ref>Michael Wessel [http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/05/tpp-elizabeth-warren-labor-118068#ixzz3o1rz9me4 I've Read Obama's Trade Deal. Elizabeth Warren is Right to be Concerned.] Politico.com 19 May 2015, accessed 8 October 2015</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, U.S. Senator [[Rand Paul]], Republican of Kentucky, opposed the bill to [[Fast track (trade)|fast-track]] the congressional ratification of the TPP on the basis of the trade agreement's secrecy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rand Paul demands White House release trade deal text immediately|last=Shabad|first=Rebecca|date=6 June 2015|work=The Hill|URL=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/244220-rand-paul-demands-white-house-release-trade-deal-text-immediately}}</ref>\n\n=== Industry influence ===\nU.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]], Democrat of Massachusetts, has alleged that corporations and industry exert disproportionate influence on U.S. trade negotiators.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/07/18/warrens-claim-that-advisory-committees-formed-during-drafting-of-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Warren's claim that advisory committees 'formed' during drafting of Trans-Pacific Partnership|website=Washington Post|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> She asserted in July 2016 that 85% of seats on U.S. trade advisory committees were held by \"senior corporation executives or industry lobbyists\", and that the members of the committees \"whisper in the ear\" of negotiators.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nMichelle Ye Hee Lee, a fact-checker for ''The Washington Post'', wrote that Warren used \"misleading language\" in describing the TPP. While Warren implied that \"28 trade advisory committees were formed\" specifically to influence the TPP, the advisory committees were actually created as part of the [[Trade Act of 1974]]; only the membership of the trade committees had changed during the Obama administration and the early phases of the TPP. Regarding Warren's claim that trade advisers secretly \"whisper in the ear of our trade negotiators\", Lee wrote: \"while the direct meetings take place in private, committees still have to submit written reports to Congress and provide written recommendations and advice that are made public.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Furthermore, Lee wrote, \"it is true that industry representatives make up a large number of the total membership, but it is worth noting that there is a labor committee in the second tier, labor representatives in the first tier and that the industry groups have a narrow focus (to give technical advice).\"<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nIn response to criticisms about transparency and the large representation from industry representatives, USTR announced it would create a Public Interest Trade Advisory Committee.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Non-compete clause ===\n[[Dean Baker]] argued that Article 18.78, under which countries should ensure that they protect [[trade secrets]] and impose criminal procedures for violators, could be used to enforce [[non-compete agreement]]s.<ref name=\":16\" /> Baker points out that [[California]]'s success can partly be attributed to the fact that the state did not allow for the enforcement of non-compete agreements, making it easy for tech workers to quit their jobs and start to work for another company.<ref name=\":16\">[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/dean-baker/will-the-trans-pacific-pa_b_9878794.html Will the Trans-Pacific Partnership Turn Silicon Valley Into Detroit?] D. Baker, The Huffington Post, 9 May 2016</ref>\n\n=== Criticisms from politicians and activists ===\nIn 2014, linguist and political activist [[Noam Chomsky]] warned that the TPP is \"designed to carry forward the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]] project to maximize profit and domination, and to set the working people in the world in competition with one another so as to lower wages to increase insecurity.\"<ref>Zach Carter and Ryan Grim (13 January 2014). [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/13/noam-chomsky-obama-trans-pacific-partnership_n_4577495.html?ref=topbar \"Noam Chomsky: Obama Trade Deal A 'Neoliberal Assault' To Further Corporate 'Domination'\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''. Retrieved 13 January 2014.</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-[[Vermont|VT]]) argues that trade agreements like the TPP \"have ended up devastating working families and enriching large corporations.\"<ref>[https://www.msnbc.com/the-ed-show/watch/preventing-tpp-essential-to-all-u-s-workers-118892611809 \"Preventing TPP essential to all U.S. workers\"]. ''[[The Ed Show]]'', 16 January 2014. Retrieved 23 January 2014.</ref> Professor [[Robert Reich]] contends that the TPP is a \"Trojan horse in a global [[race to the bottom]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/economy/video-robert-reich-explains-worst-trade-deal-youve-never-heard|title=Robert Reich takes on the Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=29 January 2015|website=MoveOn.org on YouTube|format=Video upload|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/robert-reich-largest-most-disastrous-trade-deal-youve-never-heard|title=Robert Reich: The Largest, Most Disastrous Trade Deal You've Never Heard Of|date=6 January 2015|website=Alternet|publisher=Alternet|author1=Robert Reich|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://billmoyers.com/2015/05/27/stop-calling-tpp-trade-agreement-isnt/|title=Stop Calling the TPP a Trade Agreement \u2013 It Isn't.|date=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==<!--Please respect alphabetical order-->\n{{div col}}\n* [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]]\n** [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP - ASEAN plus 6)\n* [[Combating Online Infringement and Counterfeits Act]] (COICA)\n* [[Counterfeit]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[Fast track (trade)|Trade Promotional Authority]]\n* [[Foreign trade of the United States]]\n* [[Free trade]]\n* [[Free Trade Area]]\n* [[Generic drug]]\n* [[Non-tariff barriers to trade]]\n* [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]]\n* [[Protect IP Act]] (PIPA)\n* [[Stop Online Piracy Act]] (SOPA)\n* [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDG)\n* [[Tariff]]\n* [[Trade in Services Agreement]] (TISA)\n* [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]]\n* [[United States-Mexico-Canada Agreement (USMCA)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement}}\n{{Commons category}}{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [http://tpp.mfat.govt.nz/text Agreement online text in full] ([http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/TPP-text/TPP_All-Chapters.zip zip file]), from the depositary\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/11/05/we-made-president-obamas-big-tpp-trade-deal-searchable/?postshare=5371446749920151 Searchable link to text]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151118232341/https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership Fully highlightable, annotatable, and shareable text] on the [[Medium (publishing platform)]].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151010083924/https://ustr.gov/tpp/ U.S. TPP site]\n* {{Citation\n| last = Greer | first = Evan | date = 5 November 2015\n| title = Final TPP text confirms worst fears: shadowy agreement poses a grave threat to the Internet and freedom of expression\n| publisher = Fight for the Future\n| url = http://tumblr.fightforthefuture.org/post/132605875893/final-tpp-text-confirms-worst-fears-shadowy\n| accessdate = 11 December 2015}}\n* {{Citation\n| last = Malcolm\n| first = Jeremy\n| date = 9 December 2015\n| title = The Final Leaked TPP Text Is All That We Feared\n| publisher = Electronic Frontier Foundation\n| url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/10/final-leaked-tpp-text-all-we-feared\n| accessdate = 16 December 2015 }}\n* {{Citation\n| last = Sutton\n| first = Maira\n| date = 8 December 2015\n| title = How the TPP Will Affect You and Your Digital Rights\n| publisher = Electronic Frontier Foundation\n| url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/12/how-tpp-will-affect-you-and-your-digital-rights\n| accessdate = 16 December 2015 }}\n* Ian F. Fergusson, Bruce Vaughn [https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R40502.pdf The Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement] \u2013 Congressional Research Service report for Congress. 21 pages, 12 December 2011 (PDF).\n* Sit Tsui, Erebus Wong, Lau Kin Chi and Wen Tiejun, [http://monthlyreview.org/2016/12/01/the-rhetoric-and-reality-of-the-trans-pacific-partnership/ \"The Rhetoric and Reality of the Trans-Pacific Partnership \u2013 A View from China\"] (December 2016), ''[[Monthly Review]]''\n*Clyde Prestowitz, ''[https://prospect.org/article/why-losing-tpp-wont-hurt-us-asia Why Losing TPP Won't Hurt the U.S. in Asia''], (July, 2015), The American Prospect  \n\n\n{{Foreign relations of Chile}}\n{{Economy of Malaysia}}\n{{Free trade agreements of New Zealand}}\n{{Free trade agreements of the United States}}\n{{Foreign relations of Vietnam}}\n{{Trump executive actions}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Trade blocs]]\n[[Category:114th United States Congress]]\n[[Category:Proposed free trade agreements]]\n[[Category:Free trade agreements of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Trans-Pacific Partnership]]\n[[Category:Treaties concluded in 2016]]\n[[Category:Treaties not entered into force]]\n[[Category:Free trade agreements of Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 proposed trade agreement between several Pacific Rim countries}}\n{{about|the defunct proposed trade agreement|its 11 nation successor|Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox treaty\n| name = Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| long_name =\n| image =[[File:Leaders of TPP member states.jpg|frameless|upright=1.15]]\n| caption =Leaders from 10 of the 12 prospective member states at a TPP summit in 2010\n| type = [[Trade agreement]]\n| date_drafted ={{start date and age|2015|10|05|df=yes}}<ref name=BBC51015>{{cite news |title=Trans-Pacific free trade deal agreed creating vast partnership |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-34444799 |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 October 2015 |accessdate=5 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=12 Pacific countries seal huge free trade deal |url= https://news.yahoo.com/12-pacific-countries-seal-huge-free-trade-deal-130306553.html |first=Paul |last=Handley |date=5 October 2015 |agency=AFP |work=Yahoo! News |accessdate=7 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Financial Times |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/d4a31d08-6b4c-11e5-8171-ba1968cf791a.html |title=US and 11 nations seal Pacific trade deal |quote=the TPP must still be signed formally by the leader of each country and ratified by their parliaments}}{{paywall}}</ref>\n| date_signed = {{start date and age|2016|02|04|df=yes}}\n| location_signed = [[Auckland]], [[New Zealand]]\n| date_sealed =\n| date_effective = Not in force\n| condition_effective = Ratification by all original signatories, or (2 years after signature) ratification by at least 6 states corresponding to 85% of GDP of original signatories<ref name=Diplomat>{{cite news | newspaper=The Diplomat |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/10/heres-what-needs-to-happen-in-order-for-the-trans-pacific-partnership-to-become-binding/ |title=Here's What Needs to Happen in Order for the Trans-Pacific Partnership to Become Binding}}</ref>\n| signatories =\n* 11\n* {{flag|Australia}}\n* {{flag|Brunei}}\n* {{flag|Canada}}\n* {{flag|Chile}}\n* {{flag|Japan}}\n* {{flag|Malaysia}}\n* {{flag|Mexico}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n* {{flag|Peru}}\n* {{flag|Singapore}}\n* {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| parties =\n| ratifiers =\n* 2\n* {{flag|Japan}}\n* {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| depositor =New Zealand\n| languages = [[English language|English]] (prevailing in the case of conflict or divergence), [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]], [[Japanese language|Japanese]], [[French language|French]]\n| wikisource =Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| date_expiration =\n}}\n\nThe  '''Trans-Pacific Partnership''' ('''TPP'''), also called the '''Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement''', was a proposed [[trade agreement]] between Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Singapore, Vietnam, and the United States signed on 4 February 2016, which was not ratified as required and did not come into effect. After the newly elected US president [[Donald Trump]] withdrew the US signature from TPP in January 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2017/01/23/news/economy/tpp-trump-china/ |title=Trump's decision to kill TPP leaves door open for China|last=Riley|first=Charles|date=23 January 2017|work=CNN|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> the agreement could not enter into force. The remaining countries negotiated a new trade agreement called [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]], which incorporates most of the provisions of the TPP and which entered into force on 30 December 2018.\n\nThe TPP began as an expansion of the [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]] (TPSEP or P4) signed by Brunei, Chile, New Zealand and Singapore in 2005. Beginning in 2008, additional countries joined the discussion for a broader agreement: Australia, Canada, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, Peru, the United States, and Vietnam, bringing the negotiating countries to twelve. In January 2017, the United States withdrew from the agreement.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|author=Trump, Donald J.|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/documents/2017/01/25/2017-01845/withdrawal-of-the-united-states-from-the-trans--pacific-partnership-negotiations-and-agreement|title=Withdrawal of the United States From the Trans- Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement|date=25 January 2017|publisher=[[Federal Register]]}}</ref> The other 11 TPP countries agreed in May 2017 to revive it<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/20/tpp-nations-agree-to-pursue-trade-deal-without-us.html |title=TPP nations agree to pursue trade deal without US |last=Shaffer |first=Sri Jegarajah, Craig Dale, Leslie |date=2017-05-21 |work=[[CNBC]] |access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/saving-the-trans-pacific-partnership-what-are-the-tpps-prospects-after-the-us |title=Saving the Trans-Pacific Partnership: What are the TPP's prospects after the US withdrawal? |last=hermesauto |date=2017-05-21 |work=The Straits Times |access-date=2017-05-21}}</ref> and reached agreement in January 2018. In March 2018, the 11 countries signed the revised version of the agreement, called [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/tpp-11-countries-sign-trade-agreement-as-trump-implements-tariffs.html |title=Global trade just had a 'one step forward, one step back' day |last=Ming |first=Cheang |date=2018-03-09 |work=[[CNBC]] |access-date=2018-03-10}}</ref> After ratification by six of them (Australia, Canada, Japan, Mexico, New Zealand and Singapore), the agreement came into force for those countries on 30 December 2018.\n\nThe original TPP contained measures to lower both [[Non-tariff barriers to trade|non-tariff]] and tariff [[Trade barriers|barriers to trade]],<ref name=\"GuardianAU2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/oct/06/australia-and-the-trans-pacific-partnership-what-we-do-and-dont-know |title=Australia and the Trans-Pacific Partnership: what we do and don't know |date=6 October 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> and establish an [[investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) mechanism.<ref name=\"ustr100620152\">{{cite web |url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/press-releases/2015/october/summary-trans-pacific-partnership |title=Summary of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement |date=4 October 2015 |publisher=USTR |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/cards/trans-pacific-partnethership/what-is-the-trans-pacific-partnership |title=What is the Trans-Pacific Partnership? |date= |publisher=Vox |accessdate=2 July 2015}}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref> The [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]],<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usitc.gov/publications/332/pub4607.pdf |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement: Likely Impact on the U.S. Economy and on Specific Industry Sectors |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=United States International Trade Commission |access-date=}}</ref> the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], the [[World Bank]] and the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada found the final agreement would, if ratified, lead to net positive economic outcomes for all signatories, while an analysis using an alternative methodology by two [[Tufts University]] economists found the agreement would adversely affect the signatories.{{refn|group=\"Note\"|The Tufts University working paper used the [https://www.un.org/development/desa/dpad/publication/united-nations-global-policy-model/ United Nations Global Policy Model] to evaluate TPP; sources for the Tufts paper:<ref name=\":110\">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160212030617/http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2016-02-12 |title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership |publisher=World Bank  }}</ref><ref name=\":122\">{{cite news |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/making-sense/column-why-the-trans-pacific-partnership-isnt-a-bum-deal/ |title=Why the Trans-Pacific Partnership isn't a bum deal |date=5 February 2016 |publisher=[[PBS]] |last1=Hufbauer |first1=Gary Clyde |accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"TUJC16Jan20162\">[http://www.ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/wp/16-01Capaldo-IzurietaTPP.pdf Trading Down:Unemployment, Inequality and Other Risks of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement] J. Capaldo and A. Izurieta, Global Development and Environment Institute, Working Paper No. 16\u201301 Jan (2016)</ref><ref name=\":32\">{{cite news |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2931351/trans-pacific-partnership-would-boost-gdp-by-4-3-billion-study/ |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership would boost GDP by $4.3 billion: study |author=Staff writers |access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.project-syndicate.org/commentary/tpp-debate-economic-benefits-by-dani-rodrik-2016-02?barrier=true |title=The Trade Numbers Game |last=Rodrik |first=Dani |date=10 February 2016 |website=Project Syndicate |access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=https://piie.com/blogs/trade-investment-policy-watch/studies-tpp-which-credible |title=Studies of TPP: Which Is Credible? {{!}} PIIE |website=piie.com |access-date=22 May 2016|date=30 January 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\":30\">{{cite web |url=http://ecipe.org/publications/splendid-isolation-capaldo-study-ttip/ |title=\"Splendid Isolation\" as Trade Policy: Mercantilism and Crude Keynesianism in \"the Capaldo Study\" of TTIP - ECIPE |access-date=10 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/sgp/crs/row/R44278.pdf |title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP): In Brief |last= |first= |date= |publisher=Congressional Research Service |access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=http://voxeu.org/article/tpp-structural-reform-let-s-evaluate-it-structural-models |title=TPP is a structural reform: Let's evaluate it with structural models |website=VoxEU.org |access-date=3 July 2016|date=3 July 2016 }}</ref>}} Many observers have argued the trade deal would have served a geopolitical purpose, namely to reduce the signatories' dependence on Chinese trade and bring the signatories closer to the United States.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":6\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":26\" />\n\n== Membership ==\n[[File:Trans-Pacific Partnership status.svg|thumb|{{legend|green|Parties}}\n{{legend|lightgreen|Signatories}}\n{{legend|red|Withdrawn signatory}}]]\nTwelve countries participated in negotiations for the TPP: the four parties to the 2005 [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]] and eight additional countries. All twelve signed the TPP on 4 February 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-35480600|title=Trans Pacific Partnership trade deal signed in Auckland|newspaper=BBC News|date=4 February 2016}}</ref> The agreement would have entered into force after ratification by all signatories, if this had occurred within two years. If the agreement had not been ratified by all before 4 February 2018, it would have entered into force after ratification by at least 6 states which together have a GDP of more than 85% of the GDP of all signatories. The withdrawal of the United States from the agreement in January 2017 effectively ended any prospect of the agreement entering into force. In response the remaining parties successfully negotiated a new version of the agreement that lacked the 85% GDP threshold, the [[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership|CPTPP]], which entered into force in December 2018. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status in [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 TPSEP agreement]]\n! Start of TPP<br />Negotiations\n! Signature of TPP\n! Ratification of TPP\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Singapore}}\n| Party (28 May 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{N/A}} \n|-\n| {{flag|Brunei}}\n| Party (28 May 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|New Zealand}}\n| Party (12 July 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{dts|11 May 2017}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Chile}}\n| Party (8 November 2006)\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Australia}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Peru}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Vietnam}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|November 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Malaysia}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|October 2010}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n\n|-\n| {{flag|Mexico}}\n| Non-Party\n| {{dts|October 2012}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Canada}}<ref>{{cite press release |quote=Canada formally joined the TPP on October 8, 2012. |url=http://www.international.gc.ca/media_commerce/comm/news-communiques/2012/12/03a.aspx?lang=eng&view=d |title=Canada Joins Trans-Pacific Partnership Round |date=3 December 2012 |accessdate=13 December 2012 |publisher=Foreign Affairs and International Trade Canada}}</ref>\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|October 2012}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|{{N/A}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Japan}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|May 2013}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n| {{dts|20 January 2017}}\n|}\n\n===Withdrawn member===\nOn 23 January 2017, US President [[Donald Trump]] signed a [[presidential memorandum]] to [[s:Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement|withdraw the United States' signature from the agreement]], making its ratification as it was in February 2016 virtually impossible.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/01/23/politics/trans-pacific-partnership-trade-deal-withdrawal-trumps-first-executive-action-monday-sources-say/|publisher=CNN.com|title=Trump signs order withdrawing from TPP, reinstate 'Mexico City policy' on abortion|date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 TPSEP agreement]]\n! Start of TPP<br />Negotiations\n! Signature of TPP\n!Withdrawn\n|-\n| {{flag|United States}}\n| Non-party\n| {{dts|February 2008}}\n| {{dts|4 February 2016}}\n|23 January 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38721056|title=Trump executive order pulls out of TPP trade deal|date=23 January 2017|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\nOn April 13, 2018, Trump said the United States may rejoin the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-43747211|title=Trump to reconsider TPP trade pact|date=13 April 2018|via=www.bbc.com|work=BBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/finance/donald-trump-considers-major-tpp-backflip-considers-rejoining-the-trans-pacific-partnership/news-story/75cb5a67d7e069e9af2869282758a962|title=Trump mulls major TPP backflip|website=news.com.au|date=12 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-04-13/donald-trump-reportedly-exploring-rejoining-tpp-trade-deal-talks/9652202|title=Australian farmers shocked but cautious about news Trump wants 'another look' at the TPP|date=13 April 2018|website=abc.net.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/04/13/elizabeth-warren-bernie-sanders-slam-trumps-move-on-tpp-trade-deal.html|title='A ridiculous reversal': Top Democrats who sided with Trump on trade slam TPP move|first=Jacob|last=Pramuk|date=13 April 2018|website=cnbc.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Potential members ===\n[[APEC]] members may accede to the TPP, as may any other jurisdiction to which existing TPP members agree. After an application for membership is received, a commission of parties to the treaty negotiates conditions for accession.\n\nSouth Korea did not participate in the 2006 agreement, but showed interest in entering the TPP,<ref>{{cite news| url= https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE6AD05L20101114|title= South Korea mulling U.S.-led TPP trade initiative: report |date= 13 November 2010|accessdate= 15 November 2010|agency= Reuters|first= Yoko|last= Nishikawa}}</ref> and was invited to the TPP negotiating rounds in December 2010 by the U.S. after the successful conclusion of its [[Free trade agreement between the United States of America and the Republic of Korea]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://english.donga.com/srv/service.php3?bicode=020000&biid=2010121816208|title=US requests Korea's joining of regional FTA|publisher=The Donga-A Ilbo|date=18 December 2010}}</ref> South Korea already had bilateral trade agreements with some TPP members, but areas such as vehicle manufacturing and agriculture still needed to be agreed upon, making further multilateral TPP negotiations somewhat complicated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.hani.co.kr/arti/english_edition/e_international/605796.html|title=Seoul appears set to join Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations|newspaper=[[The Hankyoreh]]|date=4 October 2013|accessdate=6 October 2013}}</ref> South Korea may join the TPP as part of a second wave of expansion for the trade agreement.<ref name=afifield>{{cite news|last1=Fifield|first1=Anna|title=South Korea asks to join Pacific trade deal. Washington says not so fast.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/south-korea-asks-to-join-pacific-trade-deal-washington-says-not-so-fast/2015/04/15/85d7396a-e39e-11e4-ae0f-f8c46aa8c3a4_story.html|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=Washington Post|date=15 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther countries and regions that are interested in TPP membership include Taiwan,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://focustaiwan.tw/ShowNews/WebNews_Detail.aspx?Type=aALL&ID=201011100039|title=Taiwan aims to join Trans-Pacific Partnership: minister |date=10 November 2010|accessdate=13 November 2010}}</ref> the Philippines,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gov.ph/2010/09/24/speech-of-president-aquino-at-the-council-on-foreign-relations-new-york-city/|title=Speech of President Aquino at the Council on Foreign Relations, New York City |date=23 September 2010 |accessdate=2 November 2010}}</ref> and [[Colombia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tppdigest.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=145:colombia-hopes-to-join-tpp-negotiations&catid=1:latest-news|title=Colombia Hopes To Join TPP Negotiations|date=19 March 2010|accessdate=22 January 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215104815/http://tppdigest.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=145:colombia-hopes-to-join-tpp-negotiations&catid=1:latest-news|archivedate=15 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> as of 2010; [[Thailand]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.voxy.co.nz/politics/thailands-quest-join-tppa-will-strengthen-opposition/5/141000 |title=Thailand's quest to join the TPPA 'will strengthen opposition' |accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref> and [[Laos]]<ref name=\"canonigs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canon-igs.org/en/column/macroeconomics/20120710_1414.html|title=Current Status of the TPP Negotiations|publisher=Canon Institute for Global Studies|date=10 July 2012|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> as of 2012; and [[Indonesia]],<ref>{{cite news|title=US-ASEAN businessmen lobby Indonesia on TPP|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2013/06/25/us-asean-businessmen-lobby-indonesia-tpp.html|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|date=25 June 2013}}</ref> [[Cambodia]],<ref name=Cambodia>{{cite news|last=Theara|first=Khoun|title='No Rush' For Cambodia on Trans-Pacific Trade Agreement, Experts Say|url=http://www.voacambodia.com/content/no-rush-for-cambodia-on-trans-pacific-trade-agreement-experts-say-cambodia/1794961.html|accessdate=12 December 2013|newspaper=Voice of America Khmer|date=22 November 2013}}</ref> [[Bangladesh]],<ref name=Dhaka>{{cite news|last=Sobhan|first=Md Abus|title=Trans Pacific Partnership the way forward| url=http://www.dhakatribune.com/op-ed/2013/sep/15/trans-pacific-partnership-way-forward| accessdate=19 September 2013|newspaper=Dhaka Tribune|date=15 September 2013}}</ref> and [[India]]<ref name=India>{{cite news|last=Kumar|first=Arun|title='India's admission to TPP would be an economic coup'|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/india-s-admission-to-tpp-would-be-an-economic-coup-113080200419_1.html|accessdate=19 September 2013|newspaper=Business Standard|date=2 August 2013}}</ref> as of 2013. According to law professor Edmund Sim in 2013, many of these countries would need to change their [[protectionism|protectionist]] trade policies in order to join the TPP.<ref name=hookway>{{cite news|last1=Hookway|first1=James|last2=Brereton-Fukui|first2=Natasha|title=Trade Is Also Key to Influence in East Asia|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indonesiarealtime/2013/06/28/trade-is-also-key-to-influence-in-east-asia/|accessdate=14 May 2015|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=28 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe largest economy in the [[Pacific Rim]] not involved in the negotiations is [[China]]. According to the [[Brookings Institution]] in 2013, the most fundamental challenge for the TPP project regarding China was that \"it may not constitute a powerful enough enticement to propel China to sign on to these new standards on trade and investment. China so far has reacted by accelerating its own trade initiatives in Asia.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mireya|first1=Solis|title=The Containment Fallacy: China and the TPP|url=http://www.brookings.edu/blogs/up-front/posts/2013/05/24-china-transpacific-partnership-solis|website=Brookings Institution|accessdate=26 June 2014|date=30 November 2001}}</ref> In 2013, it was thought China might still be interested in joining the TPP eventually.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Needham|first1=Vicki|title=China's interest grows in joining an Asia-Pacific trade deal|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/on-the-money/1005-trade/322789-chinas-interest-grows-in-joining-an-asia-pacific-trade-deal|work=TheHill.com|date=17 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920192532/http://thehill.com/blogs/on-the-money/1005-trade/322789-chinas-interest-grows-in-joining-an-asia-pacific-trade-deal|archivedate=20 September 2013}}</ref>  An academic analysis has shown that while the TPP would be more successful if China participated in it, the benefits to China are intangible.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Devadason|first1=Evelyn S.|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP): the Chinese perspective|journal=[[Journal of Contemporary China]]|date=17 January 2014|volume=23|issue=87|pages=462\u2013479|doi=10.1080/10670564.2013.843890}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2015, Indonesian President [[Joko Widodo]] declared Indonesia's intention to join the TPP.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\">\n{{cite news\n|author= Agence France-Presse in Washington\n|url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/27/indonesia-will-join-trans-pacific-partnership-jokowi-tells-obama\n|title= Indonesia will join Trans-Pacific Partnership, Jokowi tells Obama &#124; World news\n|newspaper= The Guardian |date= 27 October 2015 |accessdate= 18 November 2015\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Sri Lanka]] has announced interest of joining the TPP and is currently studying its feasibility.<ref>{{Cite news\n| url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/colombo-contemplating-joining-transpacific-partnership-samaraweera/article8285976.ece\n| title = Colombo contemplating joining Trans-Pacific Partnership: Samaraweera\n| date = 26 February 2016\n| newspaper = The Hindu\n| language = en-IN\n| issn = 0971-751X\n| access-date = 27 February 2016\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2015/11/16/business/govt-pushing-gsp-tpp-membership-dr-harsha\n| title = Govt pushing for GSP+, TPP membership - Dr. Harsha {{!}} Daily News\n| work = dailynews.lk\n| access-date = 27 February 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Status [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|2005 agreement]]\n! Status TPP\n! Announced Interest\n|-\n| {{flag|Colombia}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|January 2010}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Philippines}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|September 2010}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Thailand}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|November 2012}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Republic of China}} (Taiwan)\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|September 2013}}\n|-\n| {{flag|South Korea}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest\n| {{dts|November 2013}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Indonesia}}\n| Non-party\n| Declared Intent to Join<ref name=\"theguardian.com\" />\n| {{dts|October 2015}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Sri Lanka}}\n| Non-party\n| Announced Interest<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.dailynews.lk/?q=2015/11/16/business/govt-pushing-gsp-tpp-membership-dr-harsha\n| title = Govt pushing for GSP+, TPP membership - Dr. Harsha {{!}} Daily News\n| work = dailynews.lk\n| access-date = 27 February 2016}}</ref>\n| {{dts|November 2015}}\n|}\n\n== History ==\n=== Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement ===\n{{main|Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement}}\n\nBrunei, Chile, Singapore and New Zealand are parties to the Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement (TPSEP), which was signed in 2005, and entered into force in 2006. The original TPSEP agreement contains an accession clause and affirms the members' \"commitment to encourage the accession to this Agreement by other economies\".<ref name=\"mfat.govt.nz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Trade-and-Economic-Relations/2-Trade-Relationships-and-Agreements/Trans-Pacific/0-history.php|title=History of the Trans-Pacific SEP Agreement P4|work=mfat.govt.nz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210151458/http://mfat.govt.nz/Trade-and-Economic-Relations/2-Trade-Relationships-and-Agreements/Trans-Pacific/0-history.php|archivedate=10 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf |title=TRANS-PACIFIC STRATEGIC ECONOMIC PARTNERSHIP AGREEMENT |work=mfat.govt.nz |accessdate=5 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514005708/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf |archivedate=14 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It is a comprehensive agreement, affecting trade in goods, rules of origin, trade remedies, [[Agreement on the Application of Sanitary and Phytosanitary Measures|sanitary and phytosanitary measures]], technical barriers to trade, trade in services, intellectual property, government procurement and competition policy. Among other things, it called for a 90-percent reduction of all [[tariff]]s between member countries by 1 January 2006, and reduction of all trade tariffs to zero by the year 2015.<ref name=\"TPP2005\">{{cite web|url= http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf|title= Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement|publisher= NZ Ministry of Foreign Affairs & Trade|year= 2005 |accessdate= 28 January 2012|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150514005708/http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/main-agreement.pdf|archivedate= 14 May 2015|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAlthough original and negotiating parties are members of the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC), TPSEP is not an APEC initiative. However, the TPP is considered{{by whom|date=April 2019}} to be a pathfinder for the proposed [[Free Trade Area of the Asia Pacific]] (FTAAP), an APEC initiative.\n\n=== Original negotiations ===\n{{main|Trans-Pacific Partnership negotiations}}\n\nIn January 2008, the U.S. entered talks with the Pacific 4 (P4) members regarding [[trade liberalisation]] in financial services.<ref name=\"NZH\">{{cite news| url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/3/story.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10491556|title= First step to wider free trade|work= The New Zealand Herald |accessdate= 9 February 2008|first= Chris|last= Daniels|date= 10 February 2008}}</ref> This led to 19 formal negotiation rounds and a subsequent series of additional meetings, such as Chief Negotiators Meetings and Ministers Meetings, and resulted in the agreement announced on 5 October 2015.\n\n=== Ratification of the original agreement ===\nThe original agreement was ratified by Japan and New Zealand.\n\nJapan's main competition in the region is China, these two nations holding polar views on how South-East Asia's economy should develop. Prior to TPP, Japan tried to achieve dominance by establishing the Asian Monetary Fund (AMF), which the U.S blocked.  By 2011 Japan managed to establish a cooperative agreement with China and Korea called the \"PRC\u2013Japan\u2013Republic of Korea Free trade agreement\", also known as the CJK FTA, which did not include the U.S.  Japan's intention with this was to use the People's Republic of China card in order to shift TPP negotiations away from China towards Japan's agendas with support of the United States.<ref name=\"ADB working paper series on regional economic integration\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adb.org/sites/default/files/publication/152753/reiwp-146.pdf|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership versus Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership: Control of Membership and Agenda setting|author=Shintaro Hamanaka|date=January 2014}}</ref> Ratification in Japan required political reforms that shifted some authority from the agriculture ministry to the prime minister.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ishiguro |first1=Kaoru |title=TPP negotiations and political economy reforms in Japan\u2019s executive policy making: a two-level game analysis |journal=International Relations of the Asia-Pacific |date=20 June 2016 |volume=17 |issue=2 |pages=171-201 |doi=https://doi.org/10.1093/irap/lcw010}}</ref>\nOn 9 December 2016, [[resolution (law)|resolution]] of participation was made in the [[House of Councillors (Japan)|House of Councillors]], and notified completion of domestic procedures for ratification to the depositary of the treaty (New Zealand) as the first ratified country on 20 January 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mofa.go.jp/press/release/press4e_001443.html|title=Notification of Completion of Domestic Procedures for the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Agreement|accessdate=22 January 2017|date=20 January 2017|publisher =[[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Japan)]]}}</ref>\n\nNew Zealand ratified the TPP on May 11, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/92466121/government-ratifies-tpp-as-bill-english-heads-to-japan-for-trade-talks|title=Government ratifies TPP as Bill English heads to Japan for trade talks|website=Stuff|access-date=2017-05-11}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Jacinda Ardern]] will seek to renegotiate the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) agreement in Vietnam in time to allow the government to ban foreign speculators from buying existing New Zealand homes. She said \"Our view is that it will be possible to balance our desire to make sure that we provide housing that's affordable, by easing demand and banning foreign speculators from buying existing homes, while meeting our trade goals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/political/342124/ardern-to-push-for-tpp-changes|title=Ardern to push for TPP changes|website=Radio New Zealand|access-date=2017-10-30|date=21 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== United States withdrawal ===\n[[File:Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement.pdf|thumb|Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement (2017)]]\n\nDuring a speech on the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential campaign]], [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] nominee [[Donald Trump]] vowed to withdraw the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership if elected. He argued that the agreement would \"undermine\" the U.S. economy and its independence.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/28/donald-trump-vows-to-cancel-trans-pacific-partners/|title=Donald Trump vows to cancel Trans-Pacific Partnership as president, puts NAFTA on notice|work=[[The Washington Times]]|access-date=15 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"atlantic-wonthelp\">{{cite web|title=TPP's Death Won't Help the American Middle Class|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2016/11/tpps-death-wont-help-the-american-middle-class/507683/|website=The Atlantic|accessdate=22 January 2017|date=15 November 2016}}</ref> On 21 November 2016, in a video message, Trump introduced an economic strategy of \"putting America first\", stating that he would negotiate \"fair, bilateral trade deals that bring jobs and industry back onto American shores.\" As part of this plan, Trump confirmed his intent for the United States to withdraw from the Trans-Pacific Partnership on his first day in office.<ref name=\"bbc-trumpvideo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38059623|title=Trump: US to quit TPP trade deal on first day in office|date=21 November 2016|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shear|first1=Michael D.|last2=Davis|first2=Julie Hirschfeld|title=Trump, on YouTube, Pledges to Create Jobs|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/21/us/politics/donald-trump-presidency.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=22 November 2016|date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"gandm-100days\">{{cite web|title=Trump vows to withdraw from TPP deal, silent on NAFTA|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/trump-says-he-will-withdraw-from-tpp-deal-on-first-day-in-office/article32970902/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=22 January 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170119030112/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/trump-says-he-will-withdraw-from-tpp-deal-on-first-day-in-office/article32970902/|archivedate=19 January 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> McConnell affirmed that the TPP would not be considered during the lame-duck session of Congress preceding the inauguration of Trump.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/12/business/economy/donald-trump-trade-tpp-trans-pacific-partnership.html|title=What Is Lost by Burying the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|last=Calmes|first=Jackie|date=11 November 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=15 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump signed a [[Presidential memorandum]]<ref group=\"Note\">The official title of the document is: Presidential Memorandum Regarding Withdrawal of the United States from the Trans-Pacific Partnership Negotiations and Agreement [https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2017/01/23/presidential-memorandum-regarding-withdrawal-united-states-trans-pacific]</ref> to withdraw the U.S. from the TPP on 23 January 2017.<ref name=\"bbc-exexutiveorder\">{{cite web|title=Trump executive order pulls out of TPP trade deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-38721056|website=BBC News|accessdate=23 January 2017 | quote = Mr Trump's executive order on TPP is seen as mainly symbolic since the deal was never ratified by a divided US Congress.}}</ref> U.S. Senator [[John McCain]] criticized the withdrawal, saying \"it will send a troubling signal of American disengagement in the Asia-Pacific region at a time we can least afford it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/china-eyes-opportunity-as-us-pulls-out-of-transpacific-partnership-20170123-gtxbi1.html|title=China eyes opportunity as US pulls out of Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=24 January 2017|work=Bloomberg / Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> U.S. Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] applauded the move, saying \"For the last 30 years, we have had a series of trade deals[...] which have cost us millions of decent-paying jobs and caused a \u2018race to the bottom\u2019 which has lowered wages for American workers.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/sanders-mccain-trump-trans-pacific-partnership-2017-1|title=Reaction to Trump's withdrawal from TPP doesn't fit cleanly along party lines|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== United States public opinion ===\nIn a 2018 study conducted on general foreign trade, researchers have found that a sizable majority of U.S. adults view foreign trade as conducive to U.S. growth rather than a foreign threat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.gallup.com/poll/228317/positive-attitudes-toward-foreign-trade-stay-high.aspx|title=In U.S., Positive Attitudes Toward Foreign Trade Stay High|last=Inc.|first=Gallup|work=Gallup.com|access-date=2018-04-23|language=en-us}}</ref>  In an international context, Americans generally are among the least likely to support the Trans-Pacific Partnership and a clear partisan divide exists among the U.S. public in supporting the trade deal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/06/23/americans-favor-tpp-but-less-than-other-countries-do/|title=Americans favor TPP, but less than those in other countries do|date=2015-06-23|work=Pew Research Center|access-date=2018-04-02|language=en-US}}</ref></p>\n\nPresident Donald Trump has expressed opposition to the TPP as a tenet of his 2016 election platform, which contributed to his popularity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Blendon|first=Robert J.|date=April 2017|title=Public Opinion and Trump's Jobs and Trade Policies|journal=Challenge|volume=60|issue=3|pages=228\u2013244|doi=10.1080/05775132.2017.1308763}}</ref>\n\nCritics complained that while Trump has worked to contain the economic and geostrategic influence of China, withdrawing from the TPP reduced the effectiveness of a treaty that was designed to do exactly that.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/2019/09/23/arc-trump-administration-bends-toward-stupidity/ The arc of the Trump administration bends toward stupidity ]</ref>\n\n=== New negotiations and CPTPP ===\n{{main|Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership}} \nTPP's future was uncertain after the United States withdrew. Several signatories, however, signaled their intention to rework TPP without US participation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trump-asia-idUSKBN15800V|title=After U.S. exit, Asian nations try to save TPP trade deal|date=2017-01-24|newspaper=Reuters|access-date=2017-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the remaining eleven countries agreed on a revised TPP, now renamed the \"[[Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership]]\" (CPTPP). CPTPP is substantially the same as TPP, but omits 20 provisions that had been added to TPP at US insistence and that are now no longer binding.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/world/6-things-to-know-about-the-trans-pacific-trade-pact-cptpp|title=6 things to know about the trans-Pacific trade pact CPTPP |last=hermesauto|date=2018-01-23|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2018-01-23|language=en}}</ref> These provisions primarily relate to investment, [[government procurement]] and [[intellectual property]].<ref>{{cite web|title= TPP11: Unpacking the Suspended Provisions|url= http://www.asiantradecentre.org/talkingtrade//tpp11-unpacking-the-suspended-provisions|website= Asian Trade Centre|accessdate= 23 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe United Kingdom held informal talks to join the renewed negotiations after [[Brexit]] and has expressed an interest in joining CPTPP.<ref>\n{{Cite web |url= https://www.ft.com/content/73943036-efa9-11e7-b220-857e26d1aca4\n|title= UK looks to join Pacific trade group after Brexit |last= |first= |date= |website= Financial Times |access-date= 2018-01-02}}</ref>\n\n== Contents ==\nA version of the text of the agreement \"subject to legal review\" was released by prospective member parties on 5 November 2015.<ref>{{Citation\n| date = 5 November 2015\n| title = Text of the Trans-Pacific Partnership\n| publisher = New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade\n| url = http://www.mfat.govt.nz/Treaties-and-International-Law/01-Treaties-for-which-NZ-is-Depositary/0-Trans-Pacific-Partnership.php\n| accessdate = 5 November 2015}}</ref> Portions of drafts of the full agreement were previously leaked to the public.<ref>{{cite web|title = Leaked: What's in Obama's trade deal|url = http://www.politico.com/agenda/story/2015/06/tpp-deal-leaked-pharma-000126|website = The Agenda|accessdate = 5 November 2015}}</ref> Many of the provisions in the leaked documents are modeled on previous trade agreements.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nThe contents of the TPP go far beyond the standards drafted by the [[World Trade Organization]].  The TPP includes a [[Negative list|negative-list]] of all sectors covered for the liberalizing trade, except for those clearly stated.  The TPP includes new regulation for [[E-commerce|online commerce]], treatment of foreign investors, far more comprehensive protection for intellectual property, labor codes, and an agreement for neutrality regarding [[State-owned enterprise|state-owned enterprises]].<ref name=\"Tropical Issue\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf|title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership|publisher=Global Economic Prospect|date=January 2016}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 study by [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] political scientists Todd Allee and Andrew Lugg finds that out of the 74 previous trade agreements that TPP members signed since 1995, the text of the TPP most resembles that from earlier U.S. trade agreements.<ref name=\":24\">{{Cite journal|last=Allee|first=Todd|last2=Lugg|first2=Andrew|date=1 July 2016|title=Who wrote the rules for the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|journal=Research & Politics|language=en|volume=3|issue=3|page=2053168016658919|doi=10.1177/2053168016658919|issn=2053-1680}}</ref> A 2017 study found that the TPP scored high relative to other trade agreements in terms of a government's ability to freely legislate and implement regulations in given public policy domains.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Broude|first=Tomer|last2=Haftel|first2=Yoram Z.|last3=Thompson|first3=Alexander|date=2017-06-01|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership and Regulatory Space: A Comparison of Treaty Texts|journal=Journal of International Economic Law|language=en|volume=20|issue=2|pages=391\u2013417|doi=10.1093/jiel/jgx016|issn=1369-3034}}</ref>\n\n=== Trade barriers ===\nThe agreement cuts over 18,000 tariffs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#made-in-america|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#made-in-america|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Tariffs on all U.S. manufactured goods and almost all U.S. farm products would be eliminated completely, with most eliminations occurring immediately.<ref name=WSJ11272015>{{cite news |author=Ed Gerwin |title=Small Businesses With a Big Stake in the Pacific Trade Deal |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=27 November 2015}}</ref> According to the [[Congressional Research Service]], TPP \"would be the largest U.S. [[Free Trade Agreement|FTA]] by trade flows ($905 billion in U.S. goods and services exports and $980 billion in imports in 2014)\".<ref name=\":8\"/> Including the US, the signatories represent roughly 40% of global GDP, and one-third of world trade.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/business/international/the-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-accord-explained.html|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership Trade Accord Explained|last=Granville|first=Kevin|date=26 July 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the agreement mandates expedited customs procedures for express shipments and prohibits customs duties from being applied to electronic transmissions. It also requires additional privacy, security, and consumer protections for online transactions and encourages the publication of online customs forms. These provisions are expected to be particularly beneficial to small businesses.<ref name=WSJ11272015 />\n\n=== Environmental protection ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the \"TPP includes the most robust enforceable environment commitments of any trade agreement in history\".<ref name=\":20\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#preserving-the-environment|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#preserving-the-environment|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The USTR notes that the TPP requires signatories to fulfill their obligations under the [[CITES|Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES)]] to protect and conserve iconic species.<ref name=\":20\" /> According to the USTR, TPP is the first trade agreement to prohibit harmful fisheries subsidies, such as those that contribute to [[overfishing]].<ref name=\":20\" /> The USTR asserts that TPP signatories are required to \"combat illegal fishing\", \"promote sustainable fisheries management practices\", and \"protect wetlands and important natural areas\", \"combat wildlife trafficking, [[illegal logging]], and illegal fishing\"  and \"protect the marine environment from ship pollution, including by implementing their obligations under [[MARPOL 73/78|MARPOL]] (an international agreement to prevent marine pollution)\".<ref name=\":20\" />\n\nMorin and Baumier of the [[Canada Research Chair in International Political Economy]] (writing for the International Centre for Trade and Sustainable Development) argue that while the TPP contains an impressive number of environmental provisions and a wide range of environmental protection areas, very few of these standards are innovative, most of which being copied from previous US agreements, and that the TPP missed an opportunity to be an original and progressive contribution to the environmental agenda. However, the TPP is innovative in its utilization of a combination of the American and the European approaches in environmental protection. Indeed, in doing so, the TPP became much more detailed and specific than regular US agreements while being legally more enforceable than European agreements.<ref>Morin, Jean-Frederic and Guillaume Baumier, TPP environmental commitments: Combining the US legalistic and the EU sectoral approaches, ICTSD, 2016, http://www.chaire-epi.ulaval.ca/sites/chaire-epi.ulaval.ca/files/publications/tpp_environmental_commitments.pdf</ref>\n\nIn 2013 when TPP was still being negotiated, [[Sierra Club]]'s director of responsible trade, Ilana Solomon, argued that the TPP \"could directly threaten our climate and our environment [including] new rights that would be given to corporations, and new constraints on the fossil fuel industry all have a huge impact on our climate, water, and land.\"<ref>Ibrahim Balkhy (9 December 2013). [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/09/obama-trans-pacific-partnership_n_4414891.html \"Obama's Trans-Pacific Partnership May Undermine Public Health, Environment, Internet All At Once\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref> Upon the release of a draft of the Environment Chapter in January 2014, the [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] and the [[World Wide Fund for Nature]] joined with the Sierra Club in criticizing the TPP.<ref>Howard, Brian Clark (17 January 2014). [http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2014/01/140117-trans-pacific-partnership-free-trade-environment-obama/ 4 Ways Green Groups Say Trans-Pacific Partnership Will Hurt Environment]. ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]''. Retrieved 23 January 2014.</ref> After the announcement of the United Nations [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDGs) on 25 September 2015 and the finalisation of the TPP a week later, critics discussed the interactions between the SDGs and the TPP.  While one critic sees the TPP as providing a mixed bag of benefits and drawbacks to the SDGs,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yaleglobal.yale.edu/content/pacific-trade-deal-needs-harmonize-sustainable-development-goals|title=Pacific Trade Deal Needs To Harmonize With Sustainable Development Goals|date=23 October 2015|publisher=YaleGlobal Online|author=Shuaihua Wallace Cheng|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> another regards the TPP as being incompatible with the SDGs, highlighting that if the development provisions clash with any other aspect of the TPP, the other aspect takes priority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership-poses-a-grave-threat-to-sustainable-development-50398|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership poses a grave threat to sustainable development|date=|publisher=[[The Conversation Australia]]|author=Matthew Rimmer|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref> The [[Friends of the Earth]] have spoken out against the TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foe.org.au/articles/2015-10-02/briefing-tpp-and-sustainable-development-goals|title=Briefing on the TPP and Sustainable Development Goals &#124; Friends of the Earth Australia|date=2 October 2015|publisher=Friends of the Earth Australia|author=Cam Walker|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://asiancorrespondent.com/2015/10/tpp-irreconcilable-with-un-sustainable-development-goals-say-critics/|title=TPP irreconcilable with UN sustainable development goals, say critics|date=6 October 2015|publisher=[[Asian Correspondent]]|author=Rowena Dela Rosa Yoon|accessdate=18 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[White House Office|White House]] has cited supportive statements from the [http://www.worldwildlife.org/press-releases/wwf-statement-on-the-close-of-the-trans-pacific-partnership-negotiations World Wildlife Fund], the [[The Nature Conservancy|Nature Conservancy]], the [[The Humane Society of the United States|Humane Society]], the [[Wildlife Conservation Society]], [[Defenders of Wildlife]], [[International Fund for Animal Welfare]], [[World Animal Protection]] and other environmental groups in favor of the TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/03/31/what-theyre-saying-environmental-advocates-point-trans-pacific-partnership-historic-|title=What They're Saying: Environmental Advocates Point to the Trans-Pacific Partnership as a Historic Opportunity to Protect Our Oceans, Forests, and Wildlife|work=whitehouse.gov|date=31 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/economy/trade|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership|website=The White House|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160715213957/https://www.whitehouse.gov/issues/economy/trade|archivedate=15 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] argues that the TPP is \"the most environmentally friendly trade deal ever negotiated.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/newsroom/short-videos/tpp-and-environment|title=TPP and the Environment {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=20 July 2016|date=22 April 2016}}</ref> In regards to ISDS, PIIE analysts note that there is little evidence of constraints on environmental policies resulting from ISDS litigation.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nA September 2016 report by the [[Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy]] (IATP) predicts that \"as countries take action to protect the climate, conflicts between trade rules and climate goals will escalate\".<ref name=\"lilliston-2016\">\n{{cite book\n | last = Lilliston | first = Ben\n | title = The climate cost of free trade: how the TPP and trade deals undermine the Paris climate agreement\n | date = September 2016\n | publisher = [[Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy]] (IATP)\n | location = Minneapolis, MN, USA\n | url = http://www.iatp.org/files/2016_09_06_ClimateCostFreeTrade.pdf\n | access-date = 25 September 2016\n}}\n</ref>{{rp|1}}  The report goes on to say that trade agreements like the TPP set broad-reaching rules for the economy and government policy, thereby expanding trade, often in extractive sectors, and protecting corporations and financial firms from future measures to stabilize the climate.<ref name=\"lilliston-2016\"/>\n\n=== Good governance ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], signatories are required to join the [[United Nations Convention Against Corruption]] (UNCAC); criminalize bribery of public officials; have in place a code of conduct for public officials; take measures to decrease conflicts of interest; effectively enforce anti-corruption laws and regulations; and involve private organizations in the fight against corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#strengthening-good-governance|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#strengthening-good-governance|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP prohibits exploitative child labor and forced labor; ensures the right to [[collective bargaining]]; and prohibits employment discrimination.<ref name=\":19\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#standing-up-for-human-rights|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#standing-up-for-human-rights|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The USTR asserts that \"research by the International Labor Organization and the World Trade Organization finds that combining expanded trade opportunities with strong protections for workers can help workers move from informal-sector jobs into formal work in wage-paying, regulated export industries which offer a minimum wage, benefits, and safety programs\".<ref name=\":19\" /> The USTR asserts that \"research also shows that trade improves human rights conditions by fostering pluralistic institutions and increasing open exchanges of information.\"<ref name=\":19\" />\n\n''[[PolitiFact.com|PolitiFact]]'' rates President Obama's claim that due to the Trans-Pacific Partnership \"we've got a country like [[Malaysia]] taking really serious efforts to crack down on [[human trafficking]]\" as \"mostly true\".<ref name=\":28\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/global-news/statements/2016/aug/05/barack-obama/obama-claims-positive-relationship-between-trans-p/|title=Checking an Obama claim on TPP and Malaysian human rights|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref> ''PolitiFact'' notes that Malaysia began to comply with the TPP in June 2015, amending its law to improve the treatment of trafficking victims.<ref name=\":28\" /> Among the changes, Malaysia gave victims better access to government shelters, transitional housing and more victim-friendly restitution procedures.<ref name=\":28\" /> Malaysia has also taken steps to stop human trafficking within the construction industry.<ref name=\":28\" />\n\nIn August 2017, Reuters reported that the [[Government of Vietnam|Vietnamese government]] was intensifying repression of human rights, in part because of the Trump administration's decision to drop the Trans-Pacific Partnership.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-vietnam-arrests-idUSKBN1AI0LF|title=Trump factor weighs as Vietnam intensifies crackdown on dissidents|last=|first=|date=2017|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-08-03}}</ref> Membership of the TPP had previously encouraged Vietnam to show a good human rights record.<ref name=\":35\" />\n\n=== Intellectual property ===\nThe intellectual property section of a leaked draft of the TPP lays out a minimum level of protection parties to the Agreement must grant for [[trademark]]s, [[copyright]], and [[patents]].<ref name=Gold_standard>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/eastwest-center/tpp-the-new-gold-standard_b_9544428.html|title=TPP: The New Gold Standard for Intellectual Property Protection in Trade Agreements?|work=Huffington Post|author=Carlos A. Primo Braga|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Copyright is granted at a length of life of the author plus 70 years,<ref name=Gold_standard /> and requires countries to set criminal penalties for violating copyright protections such as [[Digital Rights Management]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/spotlight-on-digital-rights-as-tpp-text-revealed-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Spotlight on digital rights as full Trans-Pacific Partnership text finally revealed|publisher=Cnet|author=Claire Reilly|date=5 November 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP will spur innovation by requiring signatories to establish strong patentability standard and adopt strong copyright protections.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#promoting-innovation|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#promoting-innovation|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWalter Park, Professor of Economics at [[American University]], argues, based on the existing literature, that the pharmaceutical protections in TPP will potentially enhance unaffiliated licensing in developing countries, lead to tech transfers that contribute to local learning-by-doing, stimulate new drug launches in more countries, expand marketing and distribution networks, and encourage early-stage pharmaceutical innovations.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/events/tpp-pharmaceutical-protections-too-strong-too-weak-or-just-right|title=The TPP and Pharmaceutical Protections: Too Strong, Too Weak, or Just Right?|date=25 May 2016|access-date=17 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of December 2011, some provisions relating to the enforcement of patents and copyrights alleged to be present in the US proposal for the agreement had been criticised as being excessively restrictive, beyond those in the Korea\u2013US trade agreement and [[Anti-Counterfeiting Trade Agreement]] (ACTA).<ref name=\"pijip\">{{cite journal |last=Flynn |first=Sean |last2=Kaminski |first2=Margot E. |last3=Baker |first3=Brook K. |last4=Koo |first4=Jimmy H. |title=Public Interest Analysis of the US TPP Proposal for an IP Chapter |publisher=Program on Information Justice and Intellectual Property |date=6 December 2011 |url=http://digitalcommons.wcl.american.edu/research/21/}}</ref><ref name=efftpp />\n\nThe [[Electronic Frontier Foundation]]<ref name=efftpp /> was highly critical of the leaked draft chapter on intellectual property covering copyright, trademarks, and patents. In the US, they believed this was likely to further entrench controversial aspects of US copyright law (such as the [[Digital Millennium Copyright Act]]) and restrict the ability of Congress to engage in domestic law reform to meet the evolving intellectual property needs of American citizens and the innovative technology sector. Standardization of copyright provisions by other signatories would also require significant changes to other countries' copyright laws. These, according to EFF, include obligations for countries to expand [[copyright term]]s, restrict [[fair use]], adopt criminal sanctions for copyright infringement that is done without a commercial motivation (ex. [[file sharing]] of copyrighted digital media), place greater liability on [[Internet intermediary|internet intermediaries]], escalate protections for [[digital lock]]s and create new threats for journalists and whistleblowers.<ref name=efftpp>{{cite web|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement|url=https://www.eff.org/issues/tpp|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoth the copyright term expansion and the non-complaint provision (i.e., competent authorities may initiate legal action without the need for a formal complaint) previously failed to pass in Japan because they were so controversial.<ref name=effjap /> In early 2015, \"a group of artists, archivists, academics, and activists  ... in Japan [asked] their negotiators to oppose requirements in the TPP that would require their country, and five of the other 11 nations negotiating this secretive agreement, to expand their copyright terms to match the United States' already excessive length of copyright.\"<ref name=effjap>{{cite web|title=Massive Coalition of Japanese Organizations Campaigns Against TPP Copyright Provisions|url=https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/03/massive-coalition-japanese-organizations-campaign-against-tpp-copyright-provisions|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> The [[s:Trans-Pacific Partnership/Chapter 18#Article 18c: Term of Protection for Copyright and Related Rights|final agreement]] nonetheless sets a term of copyright equal to the one that obtains under U.S. law\u2014life of the author plus 70 years.\n\n[[Ken Akamatsu]], creator of Japanese manga series ''[[Love Hina]]'' and ''[[Mahou Sensei Negima!]]'', expressed concern the agreement could decimate the derivative [[d\u014djinshi]] (self-published) works prevalent in Japan. Akamatsu argued that the TPP \"would destroy derivative d\u014djinshi. And as a result, the power of the entire [[manga]] industry would also diminish.\"<ref>[https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2011-10-31/negima-akamatsu-warns-against-changing-japan-copyright-law \"Negima's Akamatsu Warns Against Changing Japan's Copyright Law\"], [[Anime News Network]], 31 October 2011. Retrieved 10 November 2011</ref>\n\n==== Pharmaceuticals ====\nIn May 2015, Nobel Memorial prize winning economist [[Paul Krugman]] expressed concern that the TPP would tighten the patent laws and allow corporations such as big pharmaceutical companies and Hollywood to gain advantages, in terms of increasing rewards, at the cost of consumers, and that people in developing countries would not be able to access the medicines under the TPP regime.<ref name=TNYTPRK22May2015TPPA>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/22/opinion/paul-krugman-trade-and-trust.html \"Trade and Trust\"] Paul Krugman, ''The New York Times'', 22 May 2015</ref> However, Walter Park, Professor of Economics at American University, argues that it is far from clear in economic research that this would necessarily happen: clarifying intellectual property rights on drugs, for some developing countries, has not led to greater prices and less access to drugs.<ref name=\":14\"/> Park also argues, based on the existing literature, that the pharmaceutical protections in TPP will potentially enhance unaffiliated licensing in developing countries, lead to tech transfers that contribute to local learning-by-doing, stimulate new drug launches in more countries, expand marketing and distribution networks, and encourage early stage pharmaceutical innovations.<ref name=\":14\" /> The [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] notes that the TPP \"aligns with the Doha Declaration on TRIPS and Public Health\", which allows developing countries to circumvent [[patent]] rights for better access to [[essential medicines]].<ref name=\":18\"/>\n\nPharmaceutical companies have criticized TPP for having too lenient intellectual property protections.<ref name=\":14\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-05/drugmakers-say-pacific-trade-pact-to-stifle-investment-in-cures|title=Drugmakers Say Pacific Trade Agreement to Stifle Investment|last=DoniBloomfield|first=Anna Edney annaedney Doni Bloomfield|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/10/5/9456757/trans-pacific-partnership-explained|title=The just-completed Trans-Pacific Partnership deal, explained|last=Lee|first=Timothy B.|date=5 October 2015|website=Vox|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kff.org/news-summary/tpps-pharmaceutical-provisions-likely-to-draw-criticism-from-industry-aid-agencies/|title=TPP's Pharmaceutical Provisions Likely To Draw Criticism From Industry, Aid Agencies|language=en-US|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, an editorial in the ''New England Journal of Medicine'' cited concerns by [[M\u00e9decins sans Fronti\u00e8res]] and [[Oxfam]] that a spike in drug prices caused by patent extensions could threaten millions of lives.<ref name=\"Kapczynski\">{{cite journal|date=16 July 2015|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership \u2014 Is It Bad for Your Health?|journal=[[New England Journal of Medicine]]|volume=373|issue=3|pages=201\u2013203|doi=10.1056/NEJMp1506158|pmid=26061752|last1=Kapczynski|first1=Amy}}</ref> Extending \"data exclusivity\" provisions would \"prevent drug regulatory agencies such as the [[Food and Drug Administration]] from registering a generic version of a drug for a certain number of years.\" The article arugues that TPP could theoretically require corporations be paid compensation for any \"lost profits\" found to result from a nation's health regulations.<ref name=\"Kapczynski\" /> The article argues that the provisions in the TPP concerning generic drugs directly target [[Pharmaceutical industry in India|India's pharmaceutical industry]].<ref name=\"Kapczynski\" /> [[Doctors Without Borders]] said in November 2015 that it was \"extremely concerned about the inclusion of dangerous provisions that would dismantle public health safeguards enshrined in international law and restrict access to price-lowering generic medicines for millions of people.\"<ref name=\"doctorswithoutborders_2015_TPP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/statement-msf-official-release-full-text-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-agreement|title=Statement by MSF on the Official Release of the Full Text of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Trade Agreement|date=5 November 2015|work=Doctors Without Borders|accessdate=6 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107112340/http://www.doctorswithoutborders.org/article/statement-msf-official-release-full-text-trans-pacific-partnership-trade-agreement|archive-date=7 November 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"DemNowTPPout\">{{Citation|last=Goodman|first=Amy|title=Full Text of TPP Trade Deal Revealed -- and Critics Say It's Even Worse Than They Thought|date=6 November 2015|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/11/6/full_text_of_tpp_trade_deal|last2=Gonz\u00e1lez|last3=Wallach|first2=Juan|first3=Lori|author-link=Amy Goodman|author2-link=Juan Gonzalez (journalist)|author3-link=Lori Wallach|publisher=Democracy Now|accessdate=6 November 2015}}</ref> The Australian Public Health Association (PHAA) published a media release in February 2014 that highlighted \"the ways in which some of the expected economic gains from the TPPA may be undermined by poor health outcomes, and the economic costs associated with these poor health outcomes.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/WO1402/S00215/protecting-the-health-of-australians-in-the-tppa.htm|title=Protecting the Health of Australians in the TPPA|date=18 February 2014|newspaper=Scoop Independent News|accessdate=18 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nA number of United States Congressional members,<ref name=\"10reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/Ten-Representatives-on-TPP-08022011.pdf|title=Letter from 10 Representatives asking for a meeting to discuss IP policies that could \"undermine public health and access to medicines.\"|date=3 August 2011|publisher=infojustice.org|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> including Senator [[Bernie Sanders]]<ref name=\"sanders letter\">{{cite web|url=http://keionline.org/sites/default/files/Sen_Sanders_letter_to_USTR_TPP_negotiations_12-1-2011.pdf|title=Letter from Senator Sanders to US Trade Representative Ron Kirk|date=1 December 2011|publisher=keionline.org|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> and Representatives [[Sander M. Levin]], [[John Conyers]], [[Jim McDermott]] and the now-retired [[Henry Waxman]], as well as<ref name=\"four reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Four-Democrat-Reps-10192011.pdf|title=Letter from Representatives Levin, Waxman, McDermott and Conyers to US Trade Representative Ron Kirk|date=19 October 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]], [[Charles B. Rangel]], [[Earl Blumenauer]], [[Lloyd Doggett]] and then-congressman [[Pete Stark]],<ref name=\"five reps letter\">{{cite web|url=http://infojustice.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Five-MOCs-September-8-2011.pdf|title=Letter from Reps. Lewis, Stark, Rangel, Blumenauer, and Doggett asking that the May 10th agreement serve as a 'non-negotiable starting point' for access to medicines|date=8 September 2011|accessdate=30 January 2012}}</ref> have expressed concerns about access to medicine. By protecting intellectual property in the form of the TPP mandating patent extensions, access by patients to affordable medicine in the developing world could be hindered, particularly in Vietnam.<ref name=\"10reps letter\" /> Additionally, they worried that the TPP would not be flexible enough to accommodate existing non-discriminatory drug reimbursement programs and the diverse health systems of member countries.<ref name=\"five reps letter\" /> In February 2015, former U.S. Labor Secretary [[Robert Reich]] stated he opposed the TPP because it would delay cheaper generic versions of drugs and because of its provisions for international tribunals that can require corporations be paid \"compensation for any lost profits found to result from a nation's regulations.\"<ref>''[http://www.salon.com/2015/02/05/robert_reich_a_trans_pacific_partnership_would_be_devastating_partner Robert Reich: A Trans-Pacific Partnership Would Be Devastating].'' Salon.com, 5 February 2015</ref>\n\n=== Investor-state arbitration ===\nThe TPP agreement establishes an [[investor-state dispute settlement]] (ISDS) mechanism,<ref>{{cite web |title=TPP Final Text Chapter 9 Investment |url=https://ustr.gov/sites/default/files/TPP-Final-Text-Investment.pdf |accessdate=17 January 2016 }}</ref> which grants investors the right to sue foreign governments for treaty violations. For example, if an investor invests in country \"A\", a member of a trade treaty, and country A breaches that treaty, then the investor may sue country A's government for the breach.<ref>Hernando Otero and Omar Garc\u00eda-Bol\u00edvar, [http://www.nyulawglobal.org/globalex/International_Arbitration_Foreign_Investors_Host_States.htm \"International Arbitration between Foreign Investors and Host States\"] Hauser Global Law School Program. NYU, December 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2014</ref> ISDS is meant to provide investors in foreign countries basic protections from foreign government actions such as \"freedom from discrimination\", \"protection against uncompensated expropriation of property\", \"protection against denial of justice\" and \"right to transfer capital\":<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/fact-sheets/2015/march/investor-state-dispute-settlement-isds|title=FACT SHEET: Investor-State Dispute Settlement (ISDS) {{!}} United States Trade Representative|website=ustr.gov|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":15\" />\n* Freedom from discrimination: An assurance that those doing business abroad will face a level playing field and will not be treated less favorably than local investors or competitors from other countries.\n* Protection against uncompensated seizure of property: An assurance that property of investors won't be seized by the government without just compensation.\n* Protection against denial of justice: An assurance that investors will not be denied justice in criminal, civil, or administrative adjudicatory proceedings.\n* Right to transfer capital: An assurance that investors will be able to move capital relating to their investments freely, subject to safeguards to provide government flexibility, including to respond to financial crises and ensure the integrity and stability of the financial system.\nISDS cannot overturn local laws (unlike the [[World Trade Organization]]) which violate trade agreements,<ref name=\":23\">{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/piie-briefings/assessing-trans-pacific-partnership-volume-1-market-access-and-sectoral|title=Assessing the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Volume 1: Market Access and Sectoral Issues {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":27\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ibanet.org/Document/Default.aspx?DocumentUid=f30e1893-08fb-4c8e-93bd-eac8442faf5e|title=Investor-state dispute settlement: the importance of an informed, fact-based debate|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=International Bar Association|access-date=}}</ref> but can grant monetary damages to investors adversely affected by such laws.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/jun/10/obscure-legal-system-lets-corportations-sue-states-ttip-icsid|title=The obscure legal system that lets corporations sue countries|newspaper=The Guardian|author= Claire Provost and Matt Kennard|date=10 June 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> As pointed out by the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], ISDS requires specific treaty violations, and does not allow corporations to sue solely over \"lost profits\".<ref name=\":15\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/about-us/policy-offices/press-office/blog/2015/march/isds-important-questions-and-answers|title=ISDS: Important Questions and Answers {{!}} United States Trade Representative|website=ustr.gov|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe TPP specifically excludes tobacco industries from the ISDS process.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/trade/tpp-tobacco-exception-proves-new-rule-trade/p37509|title=TPP Tobacco Exception Proves the New Rule in Trade|website=Council on Foreign Relations|access-date=17 June 2016}}</ref> The carve-out came as a response to concerns about ISDS cases against anti-smoking laws, including [[Philip Morris v. Uruguay]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newsweek.com/war-tobacco-makes-it-tpp-free-trade-deal-426206|title=The War on Tobacco Makes It Into the TPP Free Trade Deal|magazine=Newsweek|author= Thomas J. Bollyky |date=13 February 2016|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> The exemption of tobacco from ISDS is a first for an international trade agreement.<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nOn the basis of leaks, economists [[Joseph Stiglitz]] and Adam S. Hersh criticized the ISDS provisions of the TPP for interfering with the ability of governments to prevent public harm, alleging that if asbestos been discovered today, governments would have been unable to impose regulations without creating grounds for an ISDS suit.<ref name=StiglitzOct5>{{Citation |last=Stiglitz |first=Joseph |last2=Hersh |first2=Adam S. |author-link=Joseph Stiglitz |date=5 October 2015 |title=Opinion: The Trans-Pacific Partnership charade: TPP isn't about 'free' trade at all |publisher=MarketWatch |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/the-trans-pacific-partnership-charade-tpp-isnt-about-free-trade-at-all-2015-10-05\n|accessdate=28 October 2015}}</ref> Stiglitz also claimed that the TPP would give oil companies the right to sue governments for efforts to reduce carbon emissions and [[global warming]].<ref name=StiglitzOct27>{{Citation\n|last=Goodman |first=Amy |last2=Stiglitz |first2=Joseph |author-link=Amy Goodman\n|author-link2=Joseph Stiglitz |date=27 October 2015 |title=Joseph Stiglitz: Under TPP, Polluters Could Sue U.S. for Setting Carbon Emissions Limits |url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/10/27/joseph_stiglitz_under_tpp_polluters_could|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, Columbia professor [[Jeffrey Sachs]] concluded that the ISDS system of the TPP grants huge power to investors, and damages the judicial systems of all the member countries. He alleges that [[ISDS]] has been already used by corporations to upset governments so as to weaken the regulations that have negative effects on their profits.<ref name=THP11Nov2015JSOTPP>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/jeffrey-sachs/tpp-flawed-vote-congress_b_8534286.html Why the TPP Is Too Flawed for a 'Yes' Vote in Congress] J. Sachs, ''The Huffington Post'', 11 November 2015</ref> In February 2016, Lise Johnson and Lisa Sachs of the Columbia Center on Sustainable Investment and [[Jeffrey Sachs]] of the Earth Institute allege that foreign corporations can sue a national government in international arbitration over a government's actions if the measures (including those for public health, national security, environment, food and drug, and responses to economic crises) have a negative effect on their profits and economic interests.<ref name=\"cnn190216LJ\">[http://edition.cnn.com/2016/02/19/opinions/tpp-threatens-sustainable-development-sachs/ The real danger in TPP] L. Johnson, L. Sachs and J. Sachs, CNN, 19 February 2016</ref> [[Lori Wallach]] of Public Citizen's [[Global Trade Watch]] raised similar concerns while TPP was being negotiated.<ref name=\"nation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenation.com/article/168627/nafta-steroids#|title=NAFTA on Steroids|date=16 July 2012|last1=Wallach|first1=Lori|work=The Nation|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2016 op-ed against the TPP, Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] used the example of a French company suing Egypt because Egypt raised its minimum wage as an argument against the ISDS provisions of the TPP.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/kill-the-dispute-settlement-language-in-the-trans-pacific-partnership/2015/02/25/ec7705a2-bd1e-11e4-b274-e5209a3bc9a9_story.html|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership clause everyone should oppose|last=Warren|first=Elizabeth|date=25 February 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref> The Washington Post editorial board has however challenged this characterization of the case, noting that \"[[Veolia]] of France, a waste management company, invoked ISDS to enforce a contract with the government of [[Alexandria|Alexandria, Egypt]], that it says required compensation if costs increased; the company maintains that the wage increases triggered this provision. Incidentally, Veolia was working with Alexandria on a [[World Bank]]-supported project to reduce greenhouse gases, not some corporate plot to exploit the people. The case \u2014 which would result, at most, in a monetary award to Veolia, not the overthrow of the minimum wage \u2014 remains in litigation.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/dont-buy-the-trade-deal-alarmism/2015/03/11/41575fee-c1d5-11e4-9271-610273846239_story.html|title=Don't buy the trade deal alarmism|last=Board|first=Editorial|date=11 March 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|access-date=1 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]] challenges the notion that ISDS challenges \"the sovereign ability of governments impose any measure they wish to protect labor rights, the environment, or other issues of public welfare\".<ref name=\":15\" /> The [[International Bar Association|International Bar Association (IBA)]] mirrors these sentiments, noting that \"while investment treaties limit states\u2019 ability to inflict arbitrary or discriminatory treatment, they do not limit (and, in fact, expressly safeguard) a state's sovereign right to regulate in the public interest in a fair, reasonable and non-discriminatory manner.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> The [[White House Office|White House]] notes that investment protections are a component of more than 3,000 trade agreements, the vast majority of which have some form of neutral arbitration.<ref name=\":17\">{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/blog/2015/02/26/investor-state-dispute-settlement-isds-questions-and-answers|title=Investor-State Dispute Settlement (ISDS) Questions and Answers|date=26 February 2015|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> The United States is party to at least 50 such agreements, has only faced 13 ISDS cases and never lost an ISDS case.<ref name=\":17\" /> The White House asserts that the ISDS components of the TPP are an upgrade and improvement on ISDS in other trade agreements: TPP makes it absolutely clear that governments can regulate in the public interest (including with regard to health, safety and the environment); TPP includes the ability to dismiss frivolous claims quickly and award fees against the claimant to deter such suits; sham corporations will be prevented from accessing the investment protections; and arbitration proceedings under TPP will be open to the public and allow for inputs from non-parties.<ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] argues that \"the ISDS provisions in the TPP are a significant improvement over those in previous agreements\".<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE notes that the ISDS mechanism in the TPP respects environmental, health, and safety regulation; ensures the transparency of dispute proceedings; and eliminates [[forum shopping]].<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE asserts that some of the innovations in the ISDS provisions of TPP \"are generally disliked by the US business community.\"<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE claims that ISDS provisions are necessary, as they boost investment: \"empirical evidence has shown that treaties including these provisions have a positive effect on foreign direct investment (FDI) flows between signatory countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/blogs/trade-investment-policy-watch/what-do-data-say-about-relationship-between-investor-state|title=What Do the Data Say about the Relationship between Investor-State Dispute Settlement Provisions and FDI? {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> PIIE challenges the claim that ISDS \"arbitrators lack integrity\", noting that arbitrators take an oath of impartiality and both sides of a case choose arbitrators.<ref name=\":23\" /> PIIE agrees \"that secrecy has gone too far\" in many ISDS cases, but notes that \"TPP negotiators heeded this criticism\" and opened up ISDS cases to greater transparency.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nAccording to the [[International Bar Association|International Bar Association (IBA)]], states have won a higher percentage of ISDS cases than investors, and that around one-third of all cases end in settlement.<ref name=\":27\" /> Claimant investors, when successful, recover on average less than half of the amounts claimed.<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that \"only 8 per cent of ISDS proceedings are commenced by very large multinational corporations.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA challenges the notion that ISDS is biased against developing countries, noting that there is \"no correlation between the success rates of claims against states and their income levels or development status.\"<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that ISDS is necessary even in countries with sophisticated domestic legal systems because those domestic courts rule according to domestic laws, not international law.<ref name=\":27\" /> IBA notes that \"increasingly, awards require the losing party to pay arbitration costs and legal fees to the winning party\", which deters investors from initiating unmeritorious cases.<ref name=\":27\" />\n\n=== Labour standards ===\nAccording to the [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]], the TPP imposes \"binding and fully enforceable obligations\" on signatories to \"protect the freedom to form unions and bargain collectively\" and \"eliminate exploitative child labor and forced labor protect against employment discrimination\".<ref name=\":21\">{{cite web|url=https://ustr.gov/tpp/#protecting-workers|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|website=The Trans-Pacific Partnership @ USTR.gov|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727215845/https://ustr.gov/tpp/#protecting-workers|archivedate=27 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The obligations include \"laws on acceptable conditions of work related to minimum wages, hours of work, and occupational safety and health.\"<ref name=\":21\" /> The USTR insists that if countries like Malaysia and Vietnam do not enforce provisions relating to forced labor, human trafficking and collective bargaining, they will cease to get the economic benefits of the TPP agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership/frequently-asked-questions-on-the-trans-pacific-partnership-eddc8d87ac73#.7j4pdoi5g|title=Will TPP promote higher labor standards?|last=Representative|first=U. S. Trade|date=5 November 2015|website=Medium|access-date=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629204511/https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership/frequently-asked-questions-on-the-trans-pacific-partnership-eddc8d87ac73#.7j4pdoi5g|archivedate=29 June 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] asserts that \"the TPP includes more protections of labor rights than any previous US free trade agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/newsroom/short-videos/labor-standards-tpp|title=Labor Standards in the TPP {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> In January 2016, [[Human Rights Watch]] said that the TPP side agreements with Vietnam, Malaysia, and Brunei \"are a unique and significant step in efforts to protect labor rights in trade agreements\" but noted that enforcement of these rules remains to be seen: \"gauging compliance will require subjective assessments by the US that may take years to carry out and face obstacles arising from foreign policy objectives, commercial interests, and other political considerations.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2016/01/12/qa-trans-pacific-partnership#4|title=Q&A: The Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=12 January 2016|website=Human Rights Watch|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDartmouth economics Professor Emily J. Blanchard argues that while the TPP has been roundly criticized on the political left, progressives should actually be supportive of the TPP: \"The TPP\u2019s promise of a new progressive rule book \u2013 one that includes enforceable agreements against child labor and workplace discrimination, measures to punish illegal logging and trade in protected species, and protections against consumer fraud \u2013 would mark a substantial step forward in the progressive policy agenda on the global stage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theconversation.com/why-progressives-should-rescue-the-tpp-trade-deal-60304|title=Why progressives should rescue the TPP trade deal|last=Blanchard|first=Emily J.|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, U.S. congressman [[Sander Levin]] argued that it is difficult to enforce trade deals, as he questioned Vietnam's willingness to meet the labour standards of TPP.<ref name=\"TG21May2015SLOTPP\">[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/may/21/trans-pacific-partnership-obama-trade-deal-asia-workers Trans-Pacific Partnership won't improve workers' rights in Asia, critics warn] S. Greenhouse, The Guardian, 21 May 2015</ref> A report by U.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] said that there was a huge gap between the labor standards of past US free trade agreements and the actual enforcement of those provisions.<ref name=\"TG21May2015SLOTPP\" /> However, PIIE analysts note that research shows that the presence of \"sticks\" (a possible suspension of trade benefits) and \"carrots\" (technical assistance) in trade deals increase the likelihood that labor obligations in trade deals have a positive effect; there are both sticks and carrots present in TPP.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/piie-briefings/assessing-trans-pacific-partnership-volume-2-innovations-trading-rules|title=Assessing the Trans-Pacific Partnership, Volume 2: Innovations in Trading Rules {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Regulatory cooperation ===\nEven though the TPP has yet to be passed, the agreement has already introduced forms of regulatory cooperation for agriculture beyond that found in the WTO.<ref name=\":31\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/08/30/the-sky-fell-on-the-u-s-poultry-industry-last-year-but-nafta-and-the-tpp-helped-protect-u-s-exports/|title=The sky fell on the U.S. poultry industry last year. But NAFTA and the TPP helped protect U.S. exports.|website=Washington Post|access-date=30 August 2016}}</ref> This means that regulators in different TPP signatories have been engaging with each other and building trust.<ref name=\":31\" /> Chad P. Bown, senior fellow at the Peterson Institute for International Economics, argues that this regulatory cooperation meant that the US poultry industry was not as hard-hit by the [[2015 United States H5N2 outbreak|2015 bird flu outbreak]], as regulators in TPP countries cooperated and continued to accept US exports of poultry.<ref name=\":31\" />\n\n== Economic impact ==\nThe [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]], the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]], the [[World Bank]] and the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada found that the final agreement would, if ratified, lead to net positive economic outcomes for all signatories, while a [[Heterodox economics|heterodox]] analysis by two [[Tufts University]] economists found that the agreement would adversely affect the signatories.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" />\n\n=== Effects on economic equality ===\nIn 2013, [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences|Nobel]] Memorial prize-winning economist [[Joseph Stiglitz]] warned that, based on leaked drafts of the TPP, it \"serves the interests of the wealthiest.\"<ref name=\"NYT-20140315\">{{cite news|url=http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/15/on-the-wrong-side-of-globalization|title=On the Wrong Side of Globalization|last=Stiglitz|first=Joseph E.|date=15 March 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Joseph Stiglitz|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/secrecy-surrounds-transpacific-partnership-talks-20131208-2yzea.html|title=Secrecy surrounds Trans-Pacific Partnership talks|date=9 December 2013|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=9 December 2013}}</ref> Organised labour in the U.S. argued, during the negotiations, that the trade deal would largely benefit corporations at the expense of workers in the manufacturing and service industries.<ref>[https://www.msnbc.com/the-ed-show/watch/fighting-tpp-to-protect-workers-rights-87825475756 \"Fighting TPP to protect workers' rights\"]. ''[[The Ed Show]]''. 11 December 2013. Retrieved 17 December 2013.</ref> The [[Economic Policy Institute]] and the [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]] have argued that the TPP could result in job losses and declining wages.<ref>[http://www.epi.org/publication/trade-pacts-korus-trans-pacific-partnership/ \"No Jobs from Trade Pacts: The Trans-Pacific Partnership Could Be Much Worse than the Over-Hyped Korea Deal\"]. [[Economic Policy Institute]]. 18 July 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.cepr.net/index.php/publications/reports/net-effect-of-the-tpp-on-us-wages \"Gains from Trade? The Net Effect of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement on U.S. Wages\"]. [[Center for Economic and Policy Research]]. September 2013</ref>\n\nEconomists Peter A. Petri and Michael G. Plummer challenge the view that TPP will primarily benefit the wealthy. Their analysis finds that \"the gains from TPP appear to be fairly distributed\u2014labour will gain relative to capital, and cost reductions will favour low-income households. Some workers will need to change jobs, but they constitute a small fraction of normal job churn in any given year, and the national benefits argue for generous compensation for their adjustment costs. The agreement will also benefit workers in TPP's poorest member countries.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voxeu.org/article/economics-tpp-winners-and-losers|title=Economics of the Trans-Pacific Partnership: Distributional impact|website=VoxEU.org|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref> Research by Harvard economist Robert Z. Lawrence finds that the \"percentage gains for labor income from the TPP will be slightly greater than the gains to capital income. Households in all quintiles will benefit by similar percentages, but once differences in spending shares are taken into account, the percentage gains to poor and middle-class households will be slightly larger than the gains to households at the top.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://piie.com/publications/working-papers/adjustment-and-income-distribution-impacts-trans-pacific-partnership|title=Adjustment and Income Distribution Impacts of the Trans-Pacific Partnership {{!}} PIIE|website=piie.com|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2016/04/why-the-tpp-has-benefits-for-workers-that-far-outweigh-its-costs/|title=Why the TPP has benefits for workers that far outweighs its costs|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> An opinion piece by Ed Gerwin in the Wall Street Journal argues that the TPP agreement benefits small businesses in the US.<ref name=\"WSJ11272015\" />\n\nEconomists [[David Autor]], David Dorn and [[Gordon Hanson|Gordon H. Hanson]], who have extensively studied US labor markets adjustments to [[China shock|trade competition shocks caused by China]],<ref>{{cite journal |first=David H. |last=Autor |first2=David |last2=Dorn |first3=Gordon H. |last3=Hanson |year=2016 |title=The China Shock: Learning from Labor Market Adjustment to Large Changes in Trade |journal=Annual Review of Economics |volume=8 |issue=1 |pages=205\u2013240 |doi=10.1146/annurev-economics-080315-015041 |url=http://www.nber.org/papers/w21906.pdf }}</ref> support TPP.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/03/12/why-obamas-key-trade-deal-with-asia-would-actually-be-good-for-american-workers/|title=Why Obama's key trade deal with Asia would actually be good for American workers|website=Washington Post|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> They argue that TPP \"would promote trade in knowledge-intensive services in which U.S. companies exert a strong comparative advantage\", note that \"killing the TPP would do little to bring factory work back to America\" and argue that it would pressure China to raise regulatory rules and standards to those of TPP members.<ref name=\":10\" />\n\nAccording to the [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]], the TPP will have positive effects on the U.S. economy as a whole, with unskilled labor reaping 25% of the gains, skilled workers 41% and business owners 34%.<ref name=\":25\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/27/business/economy/why-dropping-the-trans-pacific-partnership-may-be-a-bad-idea.html|title=Why Dropping the Trans-Pacific Partnership May Be a Bad Idea|last=Porter|first=Eduardo|date=26 July 2016|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Macroeconomics===\n==== World Bank report ====\n[[World Bank]] found that if ratified by signatories, the TPP \"agreement could raise GDP in member countries by an average of 1.1 percent by 2030. It could also increase member countries' trade by 11 percent by 2030, and represent a boost to regional trade growth, which had slowed to about 5 percent, on average, during 2010-14 from about 10 percent during 1990-07.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/content/dam/Worldbank/GEP/GEP2016a/Global-Economic-Prospects-January-2016-Implications-Trans-Pacific-Partnership-Agreement.pdf|title=Potential Macroeconomic Implications of the Trans-Pacific Partnership|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=World Bank|access-date=}}</ref> The World Bank finds that the agreement will raise real wages in all signatories: \"In the United States, for example, changes in real wages are expected to be small as unskilled and skilled wages increase by 0.4 and 0.6 percent, respectively, by 2030. In contrast, in Vietnam, TPP could increase the real wages of unskilled workers by more than 14 percent by 2030, as production intensive in unskilled labor (e.g. textiles) shifts to Vietnam.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==== U.S. International Trade Commission estimate ====\nThe [[United States International Trade Commission|U.S. International Trade Commission]] estimates that \"TPP would have positive effects, albeit small as a percentage of the overall size of the U.S. economy\".<ref name=\":2\"/> There will be 128,000 more full-time jobs.<ref name=\":25\" /> By 2032, U.S. annual real income would increase by 0.23%, real GDP would be $42.7 billion or 0.15% higher, employment would be 0.07% higher, US exports would increase 1%, and imports would increase 1.1%.<ref name=\":2\"/> The report added, \"TPP would generally establish trade-related disciplines that strengthen and harmonize regulations, increase certainty, and decrease trade costs for firms that trade and invest in the TPP region.\"<ref name=\":2\"/> Vietnam is often seen as the biggest beneficiary of TPP.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-08/more-shoes-and-shrimp-less-china-reliance-for-vietnam-in-tpp|title=The Biggest Winner From TPP Trade Deal May Be Vietnam|last=svwriter|first=John Boudreau|website=Bloomberg.com|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|url=http://thediplomat.com/2016/03/why-vietnam-loves-the-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Why Vietnam Loves the Trans-Pacific Partnership|last=Diplomat|first=Dien Luong, The|website=The Diplomat|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Green|first=Michael J.|last2=Goodman|first2=Matthew P.|date=2 October 2015|title=After TPP: the Geopolitics of Asia and the Pacific|journal=The Washington Quarterly|volume=38|issue=4|pages=19\u201334|doi=10.1080/0163660X.2015.1125827|issn=0163-660X}}</ref> The U.S. International Trade Commission identifies the following US industries as net beneficiaries of TPP: Passenger cars; Apparel, Dairy production; Retailers and Wholesalers; and Business services; and as net losers: Auto parts; Textiles; Soybean production; Transportation and tourism; and Chemicals and drugs.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/economics/2016/05/19/ten-winning-and-losing-industries-from-the-pacific-trade-deal/|title=Ten Winning and Losing Industries from the Pacific Trade Deal|last=Mauldin|first=William|website=WSJ|access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada report ====\nAccording to a report by the Office of the Chief Economist at Global Affairs Canada, ratification of TPP would increase Canada's GDP by $4.3 billion by 2040.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/not-joining-tpp-will-cost-canada-billions-in-economic-growth-report/article31809986/|title=Not joining TPP will cost Canada billions in economic growth: report|access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref> This is primarily due to the preferential access it would receive to markets in the Asia-Pacific rim.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\" />  According to the report, ratification by the other TPP signatories but a failure by Canada to ratify the agreement would lead Canada to face estimated GDP losses of $5.3 billion by 2040.<ref name=\":32\"/><ref name=\":33\" />\n\n==== Peterson Institute for International Economics report ====\nEconomists Peter A. Petri and Michael G. Plummer of the [[Peterson Institute for International Economics]] project that the TPP would increase incomes in the U.S. by $131 billion annually, or 0.5 percent of GDP.  Exports from the U.S. would increase by $357 billion annually, or 9.1 percent, as a result of the agreement.<ref name=\":12\">{{cite news|last1=Hufbauer|first1=Gary Clyde|title=Column: Why the Trans-Pacific Partnership isn't a bum deal|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/making-sense/column-why-the-trans-pacific-partnership-isnt-a-bum-deal/|publisher=PBS|date=5 February 2016|accessdate=7 February 2016}}</ref>  However, two [[Tufts University]] economists argue that the research by Petri relies on unrealistic assumptions such as full employment: lost jobs will be immediately replaced in other industrial sectors.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\">[http://www.ase.tufts.edu/gdae/Pubs/wp/16-01Capaldo-IzurietaTPP.pdf Trading Down:Unemployment, Inequality and Other Risks of the Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement] J. Capaldo and A. Izurieta, Global Development and Environment Institute, Working Paper No. 16\u20131 Jan (2016)</ref> According to Harvard economist [[Dani Rodrik]], \"Petri and Plummer assume that labor markets are sufficiently flexible that job losses in adversely affected parts of the economy are necessarily offset by job gains elsewhere. Unemployment is ruled out from the start \u2013 a built-in outcome of the model that TPP proponents often fudge.\"<ref name=\":3\"/> Rodrik notes that \"the Petri-Plummer model is squarely rooted in decades of academic trade modeling, which makes a sharp distinction between microeconomic effects (shaping resource allocation across sectors) and macroeconomic effects (related to overall levels of demand and employment). In this tradition, trade liberalization is a microeconomic \"shock\" that affects the composition of employment, but not its overall level.\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n==== Tufts University report ====\n[[Tufts University]] researchers project the TPP would have a negative impact on employment: 450,000 US jobs, 75,000 Japanese jobs, 58,000 Canadian jobs and 5,000 New Zealand jobs would be lost by 2025.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" /> According to the report, 771,000 jobs would be lost in total and positive economic effects would be negligible for participating countries.<ref name=\"TUJC16Jan2016\" /><ref name=nytimes01Feb2016JC>[https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/02/business/international/economists-sharply-split-over-trade-deal-effects.html Economists Sharply Split Over Trade Deal Effects] J. Calmes, The New York Times, 1 February 2016</ref>\n\nHarvard economist [[Robert Z. Lawrence]] says that the model used by the Tufts researchers \"is simply not suited for credibly predicting the effects of the TPP\" and argues that the model used by Petri and Plummer is superior.<ref name=\":0\"/> Lawrence argues that the model used by the Tufts researchers \"does not have the granularity that allows it to estimate variables such as exports, imports, foreign direct investment, and changes in industrial structure. As a result, its predictions ignore the benefits to the TPP economies that occur through increased specialization, the realization of scale economies, and improved consumer choice.\"<ref name=\":0\"/> Lawrence also notes that the model used by the Tufts researchers finds that the TPP will cause GDP to fall by 5.24% in non-TPP developing countries, such as China, India, and Indonesia, which Lawrence is highly skeptical of: \"It is not believable that a trade agreement of this magnitude could cause the rest of the world to plummet into recession.\"<ref name=\":0\"/> Harvard economist [[Dani Rodrik]], a well-known skeptic of globalization, says that the Tufts researchers do \"a poor job of explaining how their model works, and the particulars of their simulation are somewhat murky... the Capaldo framework lacks sectoral and country detail; its behavioral assumptions remain opaque; and its extreme Keynesian assumptions sit uneasily with its medium-term perspective.\"<ref name=\":3\"/>\n\n[[Fredrik Erixon]] and Matthias Bauer of the [[ECIPE|European Centre for International Political Economy (ECIPE)]] write that the Tufts analysis has such serious flaws \"that its results should neither be regarded reliable nor realistic.\"<ref name=\":30\"/> They write that Tufts model is \"by and large a demand-driven model that does not make efforts to capture the supply-side effects of trade, which are the effects that are proven to be the core positive effects of trade liberalisation. Equally problematic, the model is not designed to assess the effect on trade from trade agreements \u2013 in fact, the model is profoundly ill suited for such an exercise. No trade economist, regardless what school of thought he or she comes from, has ever used this model to make estimates of trade. The reason is simple: if a model cannot predict the effects on the flows and profile of trade as a consequence of trade liberalisation, it is of no use at all.\"<ref name=\":30\"/> They add, \"In Capaldo\u2019s analysis, structural change and the emergence of new industries do not play a role at all. Capaldo implicitly assumes that an economy with its labour and capital does not respond and adjust to new circumstances. New competition only leads to new unemployment. In addition, the impact of lower barriers on international commerce on product and process innovation is neglected. Finally, Capaldo does not account for the impact of competition on the cost of production and final consumer prices.\"<ref name=\":30\"/>\n\nAccording to the Congressional Research Service, \"The Tufts study has drawn particular criticism as an unconventional framework for analyzing trade agreements, whereas Computable General Equilibrium (CGE) models, such as that used in the Peterson study are standard in trade policy analysis.\"<ref name=\":8\"/> Fabio Ghironi, Professor in Economics at the [[University of Washington]], describes the models used by the World Bank and the Peterson Institute in more favorable terms than the Tufts analysis.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Effects on the European Union ===\nThe EU is trying to form trade agreements with each country that is part of the TPP: since 2013, there have been talks of a free trade agreement between the EU and Japan, and in 2015 the EU presented its new strategy to improve trade in the Asia-Pacific entitled \"Trade for All.\"<ref name=\"European Parliamentary Research Service\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/RegData/etudes/BRIE/2016/582028/EPRS_BRI(2016)582028_EN.pdf|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) Potential regional and global impacts|author= Krisztina Binder|date=May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberalization ===\nAccording to an analysis by the Cato Institute of the chapters of the TPP, 15 chapters have a liberalizing impact, 5 have a protectionist impact, and 2 have a neutral impact.<ref name=\":34\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cato.org/publications/working-paper/should-free-traders-support-trans-pacific-partnership-assessment-americas|title=Should Free Traders Support the Trans- Pacific Partnership? An Assessment of America's Largest Preferential Trade Agreement|date=12 September 2016|access-date=13 September 2016}}</ref> Considered as a whole, the terms of the TPP are net liberalizing.<ref name=\":34\" />\n\nThere have been conflicting arguments on whether or not the TPP aims to increase the liberalization of trade. For arguments that propose that the TPP succeeds at liberalizing trade among the participating nations, there is a question of whether or not this causes a positive or a negative net change. Some scholars argue that participatory members of the TPP believe that such membership is a utilitarian and practical method toward new trade liberalization.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Meredith|year=2011|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership: New Paradigm or Wolf in Sheep's Clothing?|ssrn=1908411|journal=Boston College International & Comparative Law Review|volume=34|pages=|via=}}</ref> Scholars Peter Petri and Michael Plummer describe the TPP as a \"dynamic process - and example of competitive liberalization,\" and this liberalization described can result in a new type of governance for the Asia-Pacific, as well as transnational trade.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Petri|first=Peter|last2=Plummer|first2=Michael|year=2012|title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership and Asia-Pacific Integration: Policy Implications|url=|journal=Peterson Institute for International Economics Policy Brief|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to analyst and economist B.R. Williams, the United States has a large role in the reduction of trade barriers and increased U.S. investment. Williams explains that the U.S. aims to create a \"broader platform for trade liberalization, particularly throughout the Asia-Pacific region.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Williams|first=B.R.|year=2013|title=Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) countries: Comparative trade and economic analysis|url=|journal=Washington, D.C.: Congressional Research Service|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> Scholars C. Li and J. Whalley explore a numerical approach in explaining the liberalizing effects of the TPP. Li and Whalley uses a quantitative equilibrium simulation to explore the effects of the TPP on the liberalization of trade and new markets.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Li|first=C|last2=Whalley|first2=J|year=2014|title=China and the Trans-Pacific Partnership: A Numerical Simulation Assessment of the Effects Involved|url=|journal=World Economics|volume=37|issue=2|pages=169\u2013192|doi=10.1111/twec.12123}}</ref>\n\n== Geopolitics ==\nTPP increases the likelihood that Japan will undertake economic reforms to revive its economy, which coupled with potential South-Korean accession to the TPP, might have an economic impact on China. By making the Chinese economy less competitive and Chinese leadership less likely to write the rules of trade in East and Southeast Asia, the Chinese regime will be under great internal and external pressure to liberalize its economy.<ref name=\":6\"/> Japan's prime minister, [[Shinz\u014d Abe|Shinzo Abe]], believes that future Chinese accession to TPP would have a major pacifying impact on the Asia-Pacific region.<ref name=\":7\"/> U.S. Trade Representative [[Michael Froman]] has said that a failure to ratify TPP would give China the opportunity to boost its exports and set labor and environmental standards in the fast-growing Asia Pacific region through the [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP).<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-trade-idUSKCN1090QZ |title=Killing TPP would hand China 'keys to the castle': U.S. trade representative |date=29 July 2016 |newspaper=Reuters |access-date=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nSouth Korea did not participate in TPP \"largely out of a concern to maintain balance in its economic relations with China and the United States\" but has shown greater interest in joining TPP after Japan, its biggest economic competitor, decided to participate.<ref name=\":9\" /> Also, the Philippines, Indonesia, Thailand, and Taiwan have reportedly been considering and implementing various domestic reforms to improve their prospects for eventually joining.<ref name=\":29\" />\n\nSince formal TPP negotiations began in 2010, China's attitude towards TPP has:\n\n<blockquote>swung from disdain to suspicion to cautious embrace... Conclusion of a TPP agreement in early October has sparked a lively debate in Beijing, with the weight of elite opinion seeming to tilt toward eventual membership; for example, the head of the Chinese-sponsored Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB), Jin Liqun, announced his support during a speech in Washington shortly after the TPP deal was announced.<ref name=\":9\" /></blockquote>\n\nThe TPP may give renewed impetus to trade negotiations among China, Japan, and Korea, and increase the likelihood of [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP) which could provide a possible pathway to a [[free trade area]] of the Asia-Pacific.<ref name=\":9\" />\n\nIn January 2016, the [[National Association of Manufacturers]] announced its support for TPP, saying \"without such an agreement, the United States would be ceding economic leadership to other global powers, letting them set the rules of economic engagement in the region\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://thehill.com/policy/finance/264631-manufacturers-endorse-tpp |title=Big Endorsement for Obama Trade Deal |newspaper=The Hill |last1=Needham |first1=Vicki |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nA 2016 study by [[University of Maryland, College Park|University of Maryland]] political scientists Todd Allee and Andrew Lugg suggests that if the TPP becomes standard legal text, it will shape future trade cooperation and agreements.<ref name=\":24\" />\n\nAn October 2016 survey of [[international relations]] scholars showed that the overwhelming majority supported the TPP.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trip.wm.edu/charts/#/bargraph/42/6771 |title=TRIP Data Viewer |website=trip.wm.edu |access-date=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== United States considerations ===\nThe original TPP was thought by some to likely bring China's neighbours closer to the United States and reduce their dependence on Chinese trade.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/10/07/china-tpp-trans-pacific-partnership-obama-us-trade-xi/ |title=What Will the TPP Mean for China? |website=Foreign Policy |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/07/world/asia/trans-pacific-partnership-china-australia.html |title=U.S. Allies See Trans-Pacific Partnership as a Check on China |last=Perlez |first=Jane |date=6 October 2015|newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://belfercenter.hks.harvard.edu/publication/26627/trade_is_a_national_security_imperative.html |title=Trade Is a National Security Imperative - Harvard - Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs |website=belfercenter.hks.harvard.edu |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.commentarymagazine.com/foreign-policy/asia/geopolitical-necessity-trade/ |title=The Geopolitical Necessity of Trade |last=Boot |first=Max |date= |website= |access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":26\">{{Cite news |url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/the-death-tpp-the-best-thing-ever-happened-china-19232?page=show |title=The Death of TPP: The Best Thing That Ever Happened to China |last=Magnusson |first=Earl Anthony Wayne, Oliver |newspaper=The National Interest |language=en |access-date=2017-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\"foreignpolicy.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/05/03/this-isnt-realpolitik-this-is-amateur-hour/|title=This Isn't Realpolitik. This Is Amateur Hour. |website=Foreign Policy|access-date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2017/11/06/trump-will-be-haunted-by-the-ghost-of-tpp-in-asia/ |title=Trump Will Be Haunted by the Ghost of TPP |website=Foreign Policy |access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref> If ratified, the TPP would have strengthened American influence on future rules for the global economy. US Secretary of Defense [[Ash Carter]] claimed the passage of the TPP to be as valuable to the United States as the creation of another aircraft carrier.<ref name=\":9\" /> President Obama has argued \"if we don't pass this agreement\u2014if America doesn't write those rules\u2014then countries like China will\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/06/business/international/trans-pacific-trade-deal-tpp-vietnam-labor-rights.html |title=Trans-Pacific Partnership Text Released, Waving Green Flag for Debate |last=Calmes |first=Jackie |date=5 November 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times |issn=0362-4331 |access-date=24 May 2016}}</ref> According to the Congressional Research Service, \"many Asian policymakers\u2014correctly or not\u2014could interpret a failure of TPP in the United States as a symbol of declining U.S. interest in the region and inability to assert leadership... failure to conclude TPP could, in effect, allow China to shape regional rules of commerce and diplomacy through its own trade and investment initiatives, potentially creating regional rules and norms less beneficial for U.S. interests.\"<ref name=\":8\"/> [[Michael Green (political expert)|Michael J. Green]] and Matthew P. Goodman argue that \"history will be unforgiving if TPP fails... If Congress rejects TPP, trying to negotiate a similar arrangement in Asia would reopen demands on the United States\u2014and in the meantime, would likely give impetus to alternative arrangements like RCEP that exclude the United States. Momentum behind the U.S.-led international order would shift to momentum against it. Future generations of historians will take note of U.S. leadership at this moment.\"<ref name=\":9\" /> Dan Ikenson, director of Cato's Herbert A. Stiefel Center for Trade Policy Studies, argued in July 2016 that the \"failure of Congress to ratify the Trans-Pacific Partnership this year would do more to subvert U.S. regional and global interests than anything China is capable of doing.\"<ref name=\":29\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/the-trans-pacific-partnership-is-essential-to-regional-peace |title=The Trans-Pacific Partnership Is Essential to Regional Peace and Global Prosperity |date=14 July 2016 |access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> [[Stephen Walt|Stephen M. Walt]], professor of international relations at Harvard University, writing after the Trump Administration abandoned the TPP, described the TPP as \"a key institution that would have bound a number of Asian countries more tightly to the United States\".<ref name=\"foreignpolicy.com\"/>\n\n=== Non-TPP party opinions ===\nOn 30 January 2015 [[Philip Hammond]], the former [[Foreign Secretary of the United Kingdom]], described the Trans-Pacific Partnership and the Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership as \"potentially important liberalising steps forward\".<ref>Hammond, P., [https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/foreign-secretarys-speech-on-the-uk-in-asia-pacific \"Foreign Secretary's speech on the UK in Asia Pacific\"] Foreign & Commonwealth Office, UK, 30 January 2015, accessed 8 October 2015</ref>\n\nThe [[European Centre for International Political Economy]] (ECIPE), a think tank on European policies, predicted in 2012 that the TPP would be a \"deadly threat to European exporters of agricultural products in TPP countries\".<ref>Messerlin, Patrick, [http://www.ecipe.org/media/publication_pdfs/Messerlin_TPP-EU_EN05212.pdf The TPP and the EU policy in East Asia], ECIPE Policy Brief, no.11/2012, European Centre for International Political Economy, {{ISSN|1653-8994}}.</ref>\n\nECIPE has said in 2014 that TPP \"will be the first 'competing' [[economic integration]] that is large enough to have a considerable negative impact on Europe. In the long-term, the negative effects will come from dynamic impact, e.g. on investment, productivity and competitiveness\".<ref name=ecipe14>Matthias Bauer, Fredrik Erixon, Martina Ferracane and Hosuk Lee-Makiyama [http://www.ecipe.org/app/uploads/2014/12/PB09_1.pdf TRANS-PACIFIC PARTNERSHIP: A challenge to Europe] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315115352/http://www.ecipe.org/app/uploads/2014/12/PB09_1.pdf |date=15 March 2016 }} ECIPE Policy Briefs, No.9/2014, page 1-13, European Centre for International Political Economy, {{ISSN|1653-8994}}</ref>\n[[Pascal Lamy]] called the TPP \"the last of big old-style trade agreements\".<ref name=ecipe14/>{{rp|2}}\n\nRussian Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev]] has been critical of TPP, saying that \"the WTO is being encroached upon\" and this might lead to the \"destruction of world trade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sputniknews.com/business/20160802/1043873347/wto-tpp-ttip-russia.html|title=Russian Prime Minister Medvedev Says TPP, TTIP 'Encroaching on WTO'|last=Sputnik|website=sputniknews.com|access-date=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism{{anchor|Protests}} ==\nNobel Memorial Prize-winning economist [[Paul Krugman]] has said that \"there isn't a compelling case for this deal, from either a global or a national point of view.\"<ref name=\"NYT-20140227\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/28/opinion/krugman-no-big-deal.html|title=No Big Deal|last=Krugman|first=Paul|date=27 February 2014|work=[[The New York Times]]|authorlink=Paul Krugman|accessdate=28 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2016, [[United Nations]]' human rights expert [[Alfred de Zayas]] argued that the TPP was fundamentally flawed and was based on an outdated model of trade pacts, and that governments should not sign or ratify the TPP.<ref name=RT02022016>[https://www.rt.com/usa/331051-tpp-un-human-rights/ TPP 'fundamentally flawed,' should be resisted - UN human rights expert] RT, 2 February 2016</ref><ref>[http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/DisplayNews.aspx?NewsID=17006 UN expert urges Pacific Rim countries not to sign the TPP without committing to human rights and development] OHCHR, 2 February 2016</ref> According to de Zayas, the international human rights regime imposes binding legal obligations on countries, including the [[International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights]] and the [[International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights]], and trade must be done under the human rights regime. Under the ISDS in the TPP, investors can sue a government, while a government cannot sue investors. De Zayas argued that this asymmetry made the system unfair. He added that international law, including accountability and transparency, must prevail over trade pacts.<ref name=RT02022016 />\n\n=== Currency manipulation ===\nSome critics and even supporters of the TPP wanted the deal to contain measures that would crack down on nations who engage in alleged [[currency manipulation]], notably China.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/chinas-impact-looms-large-u-s-debates-trade-deals/|title=China's impact looms large as U.S. debates its own trade deals|language=en-US|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> However, [[Daniel W. Drezner|Daniel Drezner]], professor of international politics at Tufts University, has argued that the trade deal was never likely to include restrictions on currency manipulation, as it would have restricted U.S. monetary policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/10/08/is-hillary-clinton-right-about-the-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Is Hillary Clinton right about the Trans-Pacific Partnership?|website=Washington Post|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> Harvard economist [[Jeffrey Frankel]] has argued that the inclusion of currency manipulation language in TPP would be a mistake.<ref name=\":22\">{{cite web|url=http://econbrowser.com/archives/2015/06/the-top-ten-reasons-why-trade-agreements-should-not-cover-currency-manipulation|title=\"The Top Ten Reasons Why Trade Agreements Should Not Cover Currency Manipulation\" {{!}} Econbrowser|website=econbrowser.com|access-date=22 July 2016}}</ref> Frankel noted that currency manipulation would be hard to enforce (in part because it is impossible to tell whether a currency is overvalued or undervalued); \"currency manipulation\" can often be legitimate; China, often alleged to be a major currency manipulator, is not party to the TPP; currency manipulation accusations are often meritless; and because it would restrict U.S. monetary policy.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\n=== Length and complexity ===\n[[Donald Trump]] has criticized the TPP agreement for being too long and complicated, saying, \"[i]t\u2019s 5,600 pages long, so complex that nobody\u2019s read it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-is-upset-1447374770|title=Donald Trump Is Upset|date=13 November 2015|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] has charged that the \"TPP is much more than a \u2018free trade\u2019 agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://feelthebern.org/bernie-sanders-on-trade/|title=Bernie Sanders on Trade|last=FeelTheBern.org|language=en-US|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHowever, [[Georgetown University]] Professor Marc L. Busch and [[McGill University]] Professor Krzysztof J. Pelc note that modern trade deals are long and complex because they often tackle [[non-tariff barriers to trade]], such as different standards and regulations, in addition to [[tariff]]s. Due to steadily decreasing tariff barriers since WWII, countries have become increasingly likely to enact trade barriers in the form of non-tariff barriers. National firms often lobby their own governments to enact regulations that are designed to keep out foreign firms. The TPP addresses many of these \"disguised restrictions on trade\" by, for instance, \"basing these measures on agreed-upon science; making the process of formulating regulations more transparent; and giving foreign exporters opportunities to offer substantive input in the formulation of these measures.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2016/08/02/yes-the-tpp-agreement-is-over-5000-pages-long-heres-why-thats-a-good-thing/|title=Yes, the TPP agreement is over 5,000 pages long. Here's why that's a good thing.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Secrecy of negotiations ===\nAs with many trade agreements, until being finalized, negotiations for the TPP were conducted with significant secrecy. Drafts of the agreement were kept classified during negotiations, and access to the working text was significantly restricted even for government officials and business representatives involved in the talks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/05/secrecy-eroding-support-for-trade-pact-critics-say-117581|title=Extreme secrecy eroding support for Obama's trade pact|publisher=Politico|author=Edward-Isaac Dovere|date=4 May 2015|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Despite this, some sections of TPP drafts were leaked to the public by [[WikiLeaks]], which published an intellectual property chapter draft in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |title=Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) |url=https://wikileaks.org/tpp/ |accessdate=13 November 2013 |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date=13 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/nov/13/wikileaks-trans-pacific-partnership-chapter-secret |title=WikiLeaks publishes secret draft chapter of Trans-Pacific Partnership |first=Steven |last=Musil |work=The Guardian (UK) |date=12 November 2013 |accessdate=15 November 2013}}</ref> an environmental chapter draft in 2014,<ref>{{cite press release |title=Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) \u2013 Environment Chapter |url=https://wikileaks.org/tpp-enviro/pressrelease.html |accessdate=11 January 2014 |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date=14 January 2014}}</ref> and the final intellectual property chapter in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Press Release \u2013 Updated Secret Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement (TPP) \u2013 IP Chapter (second publication) |url=https://www.wikileaks.org/tpp-ip2/pressrelease/ |date= 26 October 2014 |work=[[WikiLeaks]] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, critics such as Public Citizen's [[Global Trade Watch]], a consumer advocacy group, called for more open negotiations in regard to the agreement. U.S. Trade Representative Ron Kirk responded that he believes the Office of the United States Trade Representative (USTR) conducted \"the most engaged and transparent process as we possibly could\", but that \"some measure of discretion and confidentiality\" are needed \"to preserve negotiating strength and to encourage our partners to be willing to put issues on the table they may not otherwise.\"<ref name=\"reuters_1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/14/us-usa-trade-kirk-idUSBRE84C0AQ20120514?feedType=RSS&feedName=everything&virtualBrandChannel=11563|title=Some secrecy needed in trade talks: Ron Kirk|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=13 May 2012|last=Palmer|first=Doug}}</ref> He dismissed the \"tension\" as natural and noted that when the [[Free Trade Area of the Americas]] drafts were released, negotiators were subsequently unable to reach a final agreement.<ref name=\"reuters_1\" />\n\nOn 23 May 2012, U.S. Senator [[Ron Wyden]], Democrat of Oregon, introduced {{USBill|112|s|3225}}, which would have required the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative to disclose its TPP documents to all members of Congress.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/112/s3225| title=S. 3225 (112th)| accessdate=30 May 2012| author=112th Congress (2012)| date=23 May 2012| work=Legislation| publisher=GovTrack.us| quote=A bill to require the United States Trade Representative to provide documents relating to trade negotiations to Members of Congress and their staff upon request, and for other purposes.}}</ref> Had it passed, Wyden said that the bill would increase Congressional access to information about USTR activity.<ref name=\"Wyden20120523\">{{USCongRec|2012|S3517|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Michael R. Wessel]], former commissioner on the U.S. Trade Deficit Review Commission claimed in May 2015 that \"cleared advisors\" like himself were \"prohibited from sharing publicly the criticisms we\u2019ve lodged about specific proposals and approaches\". He claimed that only portions of the text had been provided, \"to be read under the watchful eye of a USTR official\", that access on secure government-run website did not contain the most-up-to-date information, and that for cleared advisors to get that information, he had \"to travel to certain government facilities and sign in to read the materials\" and \"even then, the administration determines what we can and cannot review and, often, they provide carefully edited summaries rather than the actual underlying text, which is critical to really understanding the consequences of the agreement.\"<ref>Michael Wessel [http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2015/05/tpp-elizabeth-warren-labor-118068#ixzz3o1rz9me4 I've Read Obama's Trade Deal. Elizabeth Warren is Right to be Concerned.] Politico.com 19 May 2015, accessed 8 October 2015</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, U.S. Senator [[Rand Paul]], Republican of Kentucky, opposed the bill to [[Fast track (trade)|fast-track]] the congressional ratification of the TPP on the basis of the trade agreement's secrecy.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rand Paul demands White House release trade deal text immediately|last=Shabad|first=Rebecca|date=6 June 2015|work=The Hill|URL=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/244220-rand-paul-demands-white-house-release-trade-deal-text-immediately}}</ref>\n\n=== Industry influence ===\nU.S. Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]], Democrat of Massachusetts, has alleged that corporations and industry exert disproportionate influence on U.S. trade negotiators.<ref name=\":13\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/fact-checker/wp/2016/07/18/warrens-claim-that-advisory-committees-formed-during-drafting-of-trans-pacific-partnership/|title=Warren's claim that advisory committees 'formed' during drafting of Trans-Pacific Partnership|website=Washington Post|access-date=20 July 2016}}</ref> She asserted in July 2016 that 85% of seats on U.S. trade advisory committees were held by \"senior corporation executives or industry lobbyists\", and that the members of the committees \"whisper in the ear\" of negotiators.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nMichelle Ye Hee Lee, a fact-checker for ''The Washington Post'', wrote that Warren used \"misleading language\" in describing the TPP. While Warren implied that \"28 trade advisory committees were formed\" specifically to influence the TPP, the advisory committees were actually created as part of the [[Trade Act of 1974]]; only the membership of the trade committees had changed during the Obama administration and the early phases of the TPP. Regarding Warren's claim that trade advisers secretly \"whisper in the ear of our trade negotiators\", Lee wrote: \"while the direct meetings take place in private, committees still have to submit written reports to Congress and provide written recommendations and advice that are made public.\"<ref name=\":13\" /> Furthermore, Lee wrote, \"it is true that industry representatives make up a large number of the total membership, but it is worth noting that there is a labor committee in the second tier, labor representatives in the first tier and that the industry groups have a narrow focus (to give technical advice).\"<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nIn response to criticisms about transparency and the large representation from industry representatives, USTR announced it would create a Public Interest Trade Advisory Committee.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\n=== Non-compete clause ===\n[[Dean Baker]] argued that Article 18.78, under which countries should ensure that they protect [[trade secrets]] and impose criminal procedures for violators, could be used to enforce [[non-compete agreement]]s.<ref name=\":16\" /> Baker points out that [[California]]'s success can partly be attributed to the fact that the state did not allow for the enforcement of non-compete agreements, making it easy for tech workers to quit their jobs and start to work for another company.<ref name=\":16\">[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/dean-baker/will-the-trans-pacific-pa_b_9878794.html Will the Trans-Pacific Partnership Turn Silicon Valley Into Detroit?] D. Baker, The Huffington Post, 9 May 2016</ref>\n\n=== Criticisms from politicians and activists ===\nIn 2014, linguist and political activist [[Noam Chomsky]] warned that the TPP is \"designed to carry forward the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]] project to maximize profit and domination, and to set the working people in the world in competition with one another so as to lower wages to increase insecurity.\"<ref>Zach Carter and Ryan Grim (13 January 2014). [https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/13/noam-chomsky-obama-trans-pacific-partnership_n_4577495.html?ref=topbar \"Noam Chomsky: Obama Trade Deal A 'Neoliberal Assault' To Further Corporate 'Domination'\"]. ''[[The Huffington Post]]''. Retrieved 13 January 2014.</ref> Senator [[Bernie Sanders]] ([[Independent politician|I]]-[[Vermont|VT]]) argues that trade agreements like the TPP \"have ended up devastating working families and enriching large corporations.\"<ref>[https://www.msnbc.com/the-ed-show/watch/preventing-tpp-essential-to-all-u-s-workers-118892611809 \"Preventing TPP essential to all U.S. workers\"]. ''[[The Ed Show]]'', 16 January 2014. Retrieved 23 January 2014.</ref> Professor [[Robert Reich]] contends that the TPP is a \"Trojan horse in a global [[race to the bottom]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/economy/video-robert-reich-explains-worst-trade-deal-youve-never-heard|title=Robert Reich takes on the Trans-Pacific Partnership|date=29 January 2015|website=MoveOn.org on YouTube|format=Video upload|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternet.org/robert-reich-largest-most-disastrous-trade-deal-youve-never-heard|title=Robert Reich: The Largest, Most Disastrous Trade Deal You've Never Heard Of|date=6 January 2015|website=Alternet|publisher=Alternet|author1=Robert Reich|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://billmoyers.com/2015/05/27/stop-calling-tpp-trade-agreement-isnt/|title=Stop Calling the TPP a Trade Agreement \u2013 It Isn't.|date=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==<!--Please respect alphabetical order-->\n{{div col}}\n* [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]]\n** [[Regional Comprehensive Economic Partnership]] (RCEP - ASEAN plus 6)\n* [[Combating Online Infringement and Counterfeits Act]] (COICA)\n* [[Counterfeit]]\n* [[Digital rights]]\n* [[Fast track (trade)|Trade Promotional Authority]]\n* [[Foreign trade of the United States]]\n* [[Free trade]]\n* [[Free Trade Area]]\n* [[Generic drug]]\n* [[Non-tariff barriers to trade]]\n* [[Office of the United States Trade Representative]]\n* [[Protect IP Act]] (PIPA)\n* [[Stop Online Piracy Act]] (SOPA)\n* [[Sustainable Development Goals]] (SDG)\n* [[Tariff]]\n* [[Trade in Services Agreement]] (TISA)\n* [[Trans-Pacific Strategic Economic Partnership Agreement]]\n* [[United States-Mexico-Canada Agreement (USMCA)]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Trans-Pacific Partnership Agreement}}\n{{Commons category}}{{Library resources box}}\n\n* [http://tpp.mfat.govt.nz/text Agreement online text in full] ([http://www.mfat.govt.nz/downloads/trade-agreement/transpacific/TPP-text/TPP_All-Chapters.zip zip file]), from the depositary\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/11/05/we-made-president-obamas-big-tpp-trade-deal-searchable/?postshare=5371446749920151 Searchable link to text]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151118232341/https://medium.com/the-trans-pacific-partnership Fully highlightable, annotatable, and shareable text] on the [[Medium (publishing platform)]].\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151010083924/https://ustr.gov/tpp/ U.S. TPP site]\n* {{Citation\n| last = Greer | first = Evan | date = 5 November 2015\n| title = Final TPP text confirms worst fears: shadowy agreement poses a grave threat to the Internet and freedom of expression\n| publisher = Fight for the Future\n| url = http://tumblr.fightforthefuture.org/post/132605875893/final-tpp-text-confirms-worst-fears-shadowy\n| accessdate = 11 December 2015}}\n* {{Citation\n| last = Malcolm\n| first = Jeremy\n| date = 9 December 2015\n| title = The Final Leaked TPP Text Is All That We Feared\n| publisher = Electronic Frontier Foundation\n| url = https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2015/10/final-leaked-tpp-text-all-we-feared\n| accessdate = 16 December 2015 }}\n* {{Citation\n| last = Sutton\n| first = Maira\n| date = 8 December 2015\n| title = How the TPP Will Affect You and Your Digital Righ