ulian Winston || Off-Broadway: [[Westside Theatre]], New York City\n|-\n| 2013-14 || ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'' || R.F. Simpson || UK National Tour\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Legends!]]'' || Klemmer || Australian Tour\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[My Fair Lady]]'' || Henry Higgins || Atwood Concert Hall, [[Anchorage, Alaska]]\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' || Nathan Detroit || UK National Tour\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Hangmen (play)|Hangmen]]'' || Albert || Off-Broadway: [[Atlantic Theater Company|Linda Gross Theater]], New York City\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[The Lady Vanishes]]'' || Dr. Hartz || UK National Tour\n|-\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! Notes\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[Accident (1967 film)|Accident]]''\n| Ted\n| Credited as Maxwell Findlater\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Grease 2]]''\n| Michael Carrington\n| \n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Electric Dreams (film)|Electric Dreams]]''\n| Bill\n| \n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[The Boys Next Door (1985 film)|The Boys Next Door]]''\n| Roy Alston\n| \n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[The Supernaturals (film)|The Supernaturals]]''\n| Pvt. Ray Ellis\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1989\n| ''[[Sundown: The Vampire in Retreat]]''\n| Shane\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Mind Games (1989 film)|Mind Games]]''\n| Eric Garrison\n| \n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Fatal Sky]]''\n| George Abbott\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 1992\n| ''[[Exiled in America]]''\n| Joe Moore\n| \n|-\n| ''Animal Instincts''\n| David Cole\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Dance with Death (film)|Dance with Death]]''\n| Shaughnessy\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Waxwork 2]]''\n| Mickey\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 1993\n| ''No Escape No Return''\n| William Robert Sloan\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Gettysburg (1993 film)|Gettysburg]]''\n| Col. [[Strong Vincent]]\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Calendar Girl (1993 film)|Calendar Girl]]''\n| Man in Bathrobe\n|\n|-\n| ''Midnight Witness''\n| Garland\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Alien Intruder]]''\n| Nick Mancuzo\n| \n|-\n| 1995\n| ''[[Empire Records]]''\n| Rex Manning\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1996\n| ''Prey of the Jaguar''\n| Derek Leigh / The Jaguar\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Oblivion 2: Backlash]]''\n| Sweeney\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1997\n| ''[[Divine Lovers]]''\n| Jeff Thompson\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Man Who Knew Too Little]]''\n| British Agent\n| \n|-\n| ''[[The Real Blonde]]''\n| Bob\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1999\n| ''More to Love''\n| Barry Gordon\n| \n|-\n| ''Smut''\n| \n| Unfinished\n|-\n| ''Dazzle''\n| Tom\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2000\n| ''[[Submerged (2000 film)|Submerged]]''\n| Jim Carpenter\n| \n|-\n| ''The Perfect Tenant''\n| Daniel Summer\n| \n|-\n| ''Overnight Sensation''\n| Mark Connor\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2001\n| ''The Hit''\n| Keith\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Facing the Enemy]]''\n| Harlan Moss\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Dragon Storm (film)|Dragon Storm]]''\n| Silas\n| \n|-\n| 2006\n| ''Dog Lover's Symphony''\n| Tom\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2007\n| ''Nightmare City 2035''\n| Alex McDowell\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Cry of the Winged Serpent]]''\n| Griffin\n| \n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Dire Wolf''\n| Sheriff Parker\n| \n|-\n| 2013\n| ''The Right Regrets''\n| Chris Wickham\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Short film\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''The Tormentors''\n| Rob Turner\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Axcellerator''\n| Ray Moritz\n| \n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Those Who Wander]]''\n| Rex\n| Unreleased\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Ryan's Hope]]''\n| Punk\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1983\n| ''Journey's End''\n| Captain Stanhope\n| TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[The Powers of Matthew Star]]''\n| Scotty Ferguson\n| Episode: \"Starr Knight\"\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''The Parade''\n| Jeff\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 1985\u201386\n| ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Miles Colby]]\n| 8 episodes\n|-\n| 1985\u201387\n| ''[[The Colbys]]''\n| 49 episodes\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Hotel (American TV series)|Hotel]]''\n| Alex Morrison\n| Episode: \"Pitfalls\"\n|-\n| 1988\u201391\n| ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''\n| Derek Padley/Roger Travis\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Judith Krantz's Till We Meet Again]]''\n| Alain Marais\n| TV miniseries\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 1990\n| ''[[Counterstrike (1990 TV series)|Counterstrike]]''\n| Van Gelder\n| Episode: \"Regal Connection\"\n|-\n| ''[[Monsters (TV series)|Monsters]]''\n| Timothy Danforth\n| Episode: \"Cellmates\"\n|-\n| ''[[Beverly Hills, 90210]]''\n| Jason Croft\n| Episode: \"Class of Beverly Hills\"\n|-\n| ''Blue Bayou''\n| Phil Serulla\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 1991\n| ''[[Dynasty: The Reunion]]''\n| [[Miles Colby]]\n|[[Miniseries]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n| ''[[Sirens (1993 TV series)|Sirens]]''\n| Maxwell Caulfield\n| Episode: \"Crossing the Line\"\n|-\n| ''[[Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman]]''\n| Andrew Strauss / David Lewis\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1995\u201398\n| ''[[Spider-Man (1994 TV series)|Spider-Man]]''\n| [[Alistair Smythe|Alistair Smythe / Ultimate Spider Slayer]] (voice)\n| 19 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 1996\n| ''[[List of The Rockford Files episodes#CBS TV movies|The Rockford Files: Godfather Knows Best]]''\n| Ian Levin\n| TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[The Lazarus Man]]''\n| [[George Armstrong Custer|General Custer]]\n| Episode: \"The Boy General\"\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[All My Children]]''\n| Pierce Riley\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1998\n| ''[[Love Boat: The Next Wave]]''\n| Armand\n| Episode: \"True Course\"\n|-\n| ''[[Mike Hammer, Private Eye]]''\n| Tony Berelli\n| Episode: \"The Maya Connection\"\n|-\n| ''[[Veronica's Closet]]''\n| Brian\n| Episode: \"Veronica's Bridal Shower\"\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''[[The Nanny]]''\n| Rodney Pembroke\n| Episode: \"The Fran in the Mirror\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2000\n| ''[[Son of the Beach]]''\n| Stevens\n| Episode: \"A Star is Boned\"\n|-\n| ''[[La Femme Nikita (TV series)|La Femme Nikita]]''\n| Helmut Volker\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Missing Pieces (2000 film)|Missing Pieces]]''\n| Stuart\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 2000\u201301\n| ''[[Strip Mall]]''\n| Rafe Barrett\n| 22 episodes\n|-\n| 2003\u201304\n| ''[[Casualty (TV series)|Casualty]]''\n| Jim Brodie\n| 58 episodes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| Jim Brodie\n| Episode: \"Casualty @ Holby City: Part 2\"\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''The Great San Francisco Earthquake''\n| Mayor Schmitz\n| TV movie\n|-\n| 2009\u201310\n| ''[[Emmerdale]]''\n| [[Mark Wylde]]\n| 158 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2013\n| ''[[NCIS (TV series)|NCIS]]''\n| Dr. Madison Fielding\n| Episode: \"Revenge\"\n|-\n| ''[[Modern Family]]''\n| Professor Cooke\n| Episode: \"[[Bad Hair Day (Modern Family)|Bad Hair Day]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[DeVanity]]''\n| Richard DeVanity\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2015\n| ''[[A Prince for Christmas]]''\n| King of Balemont\n| rowspan=\"2\" | TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[I'm Not Ready for Christmas]]''\n| Greydon DuPois\n|-\n| ''[[Castle (TV series)|Castle]]''\n| Sir Ian Rasher\n| Episode: \"The Wrong Stuff\"\n|}\n\n===Audiobooks===\n\n*''[[Anonymous Rex (novel)|Anonymous Rex]]'' by [[Eric Garcia (writer)|Eric Garcia]] (2000)\n*''The Lion of Cormarre and Other Stories: The Collected Stories of [[Arthur C. Clarke]] (1937\u20131949)'' (2001)\n*''Mimus'' by Lilli Thal (2007)\n*''Spud'' by [[John van de Ruit]] (2008)\n*''Sebastian Darke: Prince of Fools'' by [[Philip Caveney]] (2008)\n*''Spud: The Madness Continues'' by [[John van de Ruit]] (2009)\n*''[[The War of the Worlds]]'' by [[H. G. Wells]] (2012)\n\n=== Video games ===\n\n* ''[[James Bond 007: Nightfire]]'' (2002) as [[James Bond (literary character)|James Bond]]\n* [[Eragon (video game)|''Eragon'']] (2006) as Brom\n\n==Discography==\n\n* 1982: \"Charades\" on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack (as Michael Carrington)\n* 1982: \"(Love Will) Turn Back the Hands of Time\" with [[Michelle Pfeiffer]] on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Who's That Guy?\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Reproduction\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"Rock-A-Hula-Luau (Summer is Coming)\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1982: \"We'll Be Together\" with Cast on the ''[[Grease 2 (soundtrack)|Grease 2]]'' soundtrack\n* 1995: \"Say No More (Mon Amore)\" in Alan Moyle's ''[[Empire Records]]'' (as Rex Manning)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\n* [[Theater World Award]] (1979) for his performance in ''Class Enemy'' ([[Players Theatre]], [[West Village]], New York City).<ref name=\"broadway\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0001028}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{iobdb name|14561}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caulfield, Maxwell}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:English expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:English male soap opera actors]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:People with acquired American citizenship]]\n[[Category:People from Belper]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStage credits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maxwell_Caulfield"}
{"title_page": "Kakapo", "text_new": "{{short description|A large flightless nocturnal parrot endemic to New Zealand }}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{engvarB|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Kakapo\n| image = Sirocco full length portrait.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| image_caption = A male named [[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] on [[Maud Island]]\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22685245/0 |title=''Strigops habroptila'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2013 |accessdate=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| status2 = NC\n| status2_system = NZTCS\n| status2_ref = <ref name=\"NZTCS\"/>\n| genus = Strigops\n| parent_authority = [[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1845\n| species = habroptilus\n| authority = [[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1845\n| synonyms = ''Strigops habroptila''\n}}\n\nThe '''kakapo''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|p|o\u028a}} {{respell|KAH|k\u0259|poh}}, {{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|k|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|\u02c8|p|o\u028a}} {{respell|-|POH}}; from {{lang-mi|k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d||night parrot}}), also called '''owl parrot''' (''Strigops habroptilus''), is a species of large, [[Flightless bird|flightless]], [[Nocturnal animal|nocturnal]], ground-dwelling parrot of the super-family [[New Zealand parrot|Strigopoidea]], [[Endemism in birds|endemic]] to [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"Best1984\">{{cite journal|first=H. A. |last=Best| title=The foods of kakapo on Stewart Island as determined from their feeding sign| journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|year=1984| volume=7| pages=71\u201383| url=http://newzealandecology.org/nzje/1599.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt has finely blotched yellow-green plumage, a distinct facial disc, a large grey beak, short legs, large feet, and relatively short wings and tail. A combination of traits make it unique among its kind; it is the world's only flightless [[parrot]], the heaviest parrot, nocturnal, herbivorous, visibly [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]] in body size, has a low [[basal metabolic rate]] and no male parental care, and is the only parrot to have a [[Polygyny in animals|polygynous]] [[Lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system. It is also possibly one of the world's longest-living birds.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\">{{cite journal |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |year=2006 |first1=Ralph G. |last1=Powlesland |first2=Don V. |last2=Merton |authorlink2=Don Merton |first3=John F. |last3=Cockrem| pages=3\u201326 |title=A parrot apart: the natural history of the kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus''), and the context of its conservation management |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_3.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIts anatomy typifies the tendency of bird evolution on oceanic islands, with few predators and abundant food: a generally robust physique at the expense of flight abilities, resulting in reduced wing muscles and a diminished [[Keel (bird)|keel]] on the [[sternum]]. Like many other New Zealand bird species, the kakapo was historically important to  [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the indigenous people of New Zealand, appearing in many of their traditional legends and folklore; however it was also heavily hunted and used as a resource by M\u0101ori, both for its meat as a food source and for its feathers, which were used to make highly valued pieces of clothing. Kakapo were also occasionally kept as pets.\n\nThe kakapo is critically endangered; the total known adult population is {{Number_of_Living_Kakapo}}<!-- see link on talk page for editing this number --> [[List of kakapo|living individuals]], all of which are named and tagged, confined to four small islands off the coast of New Zealand that have been cleared of predators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/26/world/kakapo-conservation-scn-c2e-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Can tech save New Zealand's 'gorgeous, hilarious' parrot?|first=Sarah |last=Lazarus|website=CNN|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> The [[Invasive species in New Zealand|introduction of predators]] such as cats, rats, ferrets, and stoats during British colonisation  almost wiped out the kakapo. Conservation efforts began in the 1890s, but they were not very successful until the implementation of the Kakapo Recovery Programme in 1995.\n\nMost kakapo are kept on two predator-free islands, [[Codfish Island|Codfish / Whenua Hou]] and [[Anchor Island|Anchor]], where they are closely monitored, and [[Little Barrier Island|Little Barrier / Hauturu Island]] is being trialled as a third home for the species.\n\n==Taxonomy, systematics and naming==\n[[File:Kakapo2.jpg|thumb|left|Illustration of a kakapo from the book ''A History of the Birds of New Zealand'' by Walter Lawry Buller, published in 1873.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/kakapo.html |title=New Zealand Birds &#124; Birds &#124; Gallery &#124; Kakapo, ''Strigops habroptilus'' |publisher=Nzbirds.com |date=9 October 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>]]\nThe common English name \"kakapo\" comes from the [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] \"k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d\", from ''k\u0101k\u0101'' (\"parrot\") + ''p\u014d'' (\"night\"); the name is both singular and plural. \"K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d\" is increasingly written in New Zealand English with the [[Macron (diacritic)|macrons]] that indicate long vowels.\n\nThe kakapo was originally described by English [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] [[George Robert Gray]] in 1845 and named ''Strigops habroptilus''.<ref group=lower-alpha>Some sources give the kakapo's Latin name as ''Strigops habroptila'', from the belief that the word ''Strigops'' is feminine, and the species name is required to agree in gender; neither of which is true \u2013 ''Strigops'' is a masculine compound, and ''habroptilus'' is a noun in apposition, not an adjective. ''S. habroptilus'' is the most common form used in the scientific literature.</ref> Its generic name ''Strigops'' is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''strix'', genitive ''strigos'' \"owl\", and ''ops'' \"face\", while its specific [[epithet]] ''habroptilus'' comes from ''habros'' \"soft\", and ''ptilon'' \"feather\".<ref name=\"Liddell1980\">{{Cite book| authorlink1 = Henry George Liddell | last1=Liddell | first1=Henry George | authorlink2=Robert Scott (philologist) | first2=Robert | last2=Scott | year = 1980 | title = A Greek-English Lexicon (Abridged Edition) | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = United Kingdom | isbn =978-0-19-910207-5| title-link=A Greek-English Lexicon }}</ref>\n\nThe bird has so many unusual features that it was initially placed in its own [[tribe (biology)|tribe]], Strigopini. Recent [[phylogenetic]] studies have confirmed the unique position of this genus as well as the closeness to the [[k\u0101k\u0101]] and the [[kea]], both belonging to the New Zealand parrot genus ''Nestor''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Rheindt|first=Frank E.|last2=Christidis|first2=Les|last3=Kuhn|first3=Sylvia|last4=de Kloet|first4=Siwo|last5=Norman|first5=Janette A.|last6=Fidler|first6=Andrew|date=2013|title=The timing of diversification within the most divergent parrot clade|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|language=en|volume=45|issue=2|pages=140\u2013148|doi=10.1111/j.1600-048x.2013.00200.x|issn=0908-8857}}</ref> Together, they are now considered a separate superfamily within the parrots, Strigopoidea, the most basal of all living parrots.<ref name=\"revision\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2012/f/z03205p040f.pdf|author=Joseph, Leo|year=2012|title= A revised nomenclature and classification for family-group taxa of parrots (Psittaciformes)|journal= Zootaxa|volume= 3205|pages= 26\u201340|display-authors=etal|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3205.1.2}}</ref>\n\nWithin the Strigopoidea, the kakapo is placed in its own [[family (biology)|family]], Strigopidae. The common ancestor of the kakapo and the genus ''[[Nestor (genus)|Nestor]]'' became isolated from the remaining parrot species when New Zealand broke off from [[Gondwana]], around 82 million years ago. Around 30&nbsp;million years ago, the kakapo diverged from the genus ''Nestor''.<ref name=\"Wright\">{{cite journal|title=A Multilocus Molecular Phylogeny of the Parrots (Psittaciformes): Support for a Gondwanan Origin during the Cretaceous|journal=Mol Biol Evol|year=2008|first=T. F. |last=Wright|last2=Schirtzinger |first2=E. E. |last3=Matsumoto |first3=T. |last4=Eberhard |first4=J. R. |last5=Graves |first5=G. R. |last6=Sanchez |first6=J. J. |last7=Capelli |first7=S. |last8=Muller |first8=H. |last9=Scharpegge |first9=J. |last10=Chambers |first10=G. K. |last11=Fleischer |first11=R. C.|volume=25|issue=10|pages=2141\u20132156|doi= 10.1093/molbev/msn160|url=|accessdate=|pmid=18653733|pmc=2727385 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarlier ornithologists felt that the kakapo might be related to the [[Pezoporus|ground parrots]] and [[night parrot]] of Australia due to their similar colouration, but this is contradicted by recent studies;<ref>[[Richard Schodde|Schodde, R.]] & [[Ian J. Mason|Mason, I.J.]] (1981). Nocturnal Birds of Australia. Illustrated by Jeremy Boot. Melbourne: Lansdowne Edns 136 pp. 22 pls [35\u201336]</ref> rather, the [[crypsis|cryptic]] colour seems to be [[adaptation]] to terrestrial habits that evolved twice [[convergent evolution|convergently]].<ref name=Leeton>{{cite journal | last1 = Leeton | first1 = P.R.J. | last2 = Christidis | first2 = L. | last3 = Westerman | first3 = M. | last4 = Boles | first4 = W.E. | year = 1994 | title = Molecular phylogenetic relationships of the Night Parrot (''Geopsittacus occidentalis'') and the Ground Parrot (''Pezoporus wallicus'') | url = http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v111n04/p0833-p0843.pdf | journal = [[Auk (journal)|Auk]] | volume = 111 | issue = 4| pages = 833\u2013843 | doi = 10.2307/4088815 | jstor = 4088815 }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus 1-1c.jpg|thumb|A year-old kakapo on [[Codfish Island]].]]\nThe kakapo is a large, rotund parrot. Adults can measure from {{convert|58|to|64|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length, and weight can vary from {{convert|0.95|to|4|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} at maturity.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\">{{Cite book|last=Higgins |first=P. J.| year=1999| title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Volume 4: Parrots to Dollarbird| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=Melbourne| isbn=978-0-19-553071-1|title-link=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cameron |first=M. |year=2012 |title=Parrots: The animal answer guide |url=https://archive.org/details/parrotsanimalans0000came |url-access=registration |publisher=JHU Press}}</ref> Males are larger than females. Twenty-eight males were found to average {{convert|2|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in one study, and 39 males were found to average {{convert|2.06|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in another. In the same studies, 28 females were found to average {{convert|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and 18 females were found to average {{convert|1.28|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, respectively.<ref name=\"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses, 2nd Edition'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4200-6444-5}}.</ref><ref name=\"Merton1984\">{{Cite journal |last1=Merton |first1=D. V. | authorlink1=Don Merton| last2=Morris |first2=R. B. |last3=Atkinson |first3=I. A. |date=1984 |title=Lek behaviour in a parrot: the kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' of New Zealand. |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=126 |issue=3 |pages=277\u2013283 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1984.tb00250.x}}</ref> Kakapo are the heaviest living species of parrot and on average weigh about {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} more than the largest flying parrot, the [[hyacinth macaw]].<ref name = \"CRC\"/>\n\nThe kakapo cannot fly, having relatively short wings for its size and lacking the [[Keel (bird anatomy)|keel]] on the [[sternum]] (breastbone), where the flight muscles of other birds attach.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> It uses its wings for balance and to break its fall when leaping from trees. Unlike many other land birds, the kakapo can accumulate large amounts of body fat.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nThe upper parts of the kakapo have yellowish moss-green feathers barred or mottled with black or dark brownish grey, blending well with native vegetation. Individuals may have strongly varying degrees of mottling and colour tone and intensity \u2013 museum specimens show that some birds had completely yellow colouring. The breast and flank are yellowish-green streaked with yellow. The belly, undertail, neck, and face are predominantly yellowish streaked with pale green and weakly mottled with brownish-grey. Because the feathers do not need the strength and stiffness required for flight, they are exceptionally soft, giving rise to the [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''habroptilus''. The kakapo has a conspicuous facial disc of fine feathers resembling the face of an owl; thus, early European settlers called it the \"owl parrot\". The beak is surrounded by delicate feathers which resemble [[whiskers|vibrissae]] or \"whiskers\"; it is possible kakapo use these to sense the ground as they walk with its head lowered, but there is no evidence for this. The mandible is variable in colour, mostly ivory, with the upper part often bluish-grey. The eyes are dark brown. Kakapo feet are large, scaly, and, as in all parrots, [[dactyly|zygodactyl]] (two toes face forward and two backward). The pronounced claws are particularly useful for climbing. The ends of the tail feathers often become worn from being continually dragged on the ground.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n[[File:K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d head.jpg|thumb|left|The \"whiskers\" around the beak.]]\nFemales are easily distinguished from males as they have a narrower and less domed head, narrower and proportionally longer beak, smaller [[Beak#Cere|cere]] and [[Beak#Nares|nostrils]], more slender and pinkish grey legs and feet, and proportionally longer tail. While their plumage colour is not very different from that of the male, the toning is more subtle, with less yellow and mottling. Nesting females also have a [[brood patch]] of bare skin on the belly.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nThe kakapo's [[Altriciality|altricial]] young are first covered with greyish white down, through which their pink skin can be easily seen. They become fully feathered at approximately 70 days old. Juvenile individuals tend to have duller green colouration, more uniform black barring, and less yellow present in their feathers. They are additionally distinguishable because of their shorter tails, wings, and beaks. At this stage, they have a ring of short feathers surrounding their irises that resemble eyelashes.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" />\n\nLike many other parrots, kakapo have a variety of calls. As well as the ''booms'' (see [[Kakapo#Media|below]] for a recording) and ''chings'' of their mating calls, they will often loudly ''skraark''.<ref name=\"CloseUp\"/>\n\nThe kakapo has a well-developed [[Olfaction|sense of smell]], which complements its nocturnal lifestyle.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\">{{Cite journal\n| last1 = Hagelin | first1 = Julie C.\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2004.00212.x\n| title = Observations on the olfactory ability of the kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'', the critically endangered parrot of New Zealand\n| journal = [[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]]\n| volume = 146\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 161\u2013164\n|date=January 2004\n}}</ref> It can distinguish between odours while foraging, a behaviour reported in only one other parrot species.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\"/> The kakapo has a large olfactory bulb ratio (longest diameter of the olfactory bulb/longest diameter of the brain) indicating that it does, indeed, have a more developed sense of smell than other parrots.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\" /> One of the most striking characteristics of the kakapo is its distinct musty-sweet odour.<ref name=\"CloseUp\">{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/up-close-and-personal/|title=Up Close & Personal|publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> The smell often alerts predators to the presence of kakapo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wildinfo.net/facts/Kakapo.asp?page=/facts/Kakapo.asp|title=Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'')|publisher=Wild Magazine}}</ref>\n\nAs a nocturnal species, the kakapo has adapted its senses to living in darkness. Its [[optic tectum]], [[nucleus rotundus]], and [[Avian pallium|entopallium]] are smaller in relation to its overall brain size than those of diurnal parrots. Its retina shares some qualities with that of other nocturnal birds but also has some qualities typical of diurnal birds, lending to best function around twilight. These modifications allow the kakapo to have enhanced light sensitivity but with poor visual acuity.<ref>{{cite journal\n| last1=Corfield | first1=J. R.\n| last2=Gsell | first2=A. C.\n| last3=Brunton | first3=D.\n| last4=Heesy | first4=C. P.\n| last5=Hall | first5=M. I.\n| last6=Acosta | first6=M. L.\n| last7=Iwaniuk | first7=A. N.\n| year=2011\n| title=Anatomical Specializations for Nocturnality in a Critically Endangered Parrot, the Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'')\n| journal=PLoS ONE\n| volume=6\n| issue=8\n| page=e22945\n| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0022945\n| pmid=21860663\n| pmc=3157909\n}}</ref>\n\n===Internal anatomy===\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus (AM LB299).jpg|thumb|upright|Skeleton]] \nThe skeleton of the kakapo differs from other parrots in several features associated with flightlessness. Firstly, it has the smallest relative wing size of any parrot. Its wing feathers are shorter, more rounded, less asymmetrical, and have fewer distal barbules to lock the feathers together. The sternum is small and has a low, [[vestigial]] keel and a shortened [[spina externa]]. As in other flightless birds and some flighted parrots, the [[furcula]] is not fused but consists of a pair of [[clavicles]] lying in contact with each [[coracoid]]. As in other flightless birds, the angle between the coracoid and sternum is enlarged. The kakapo has a larger pelvis than other parrots. The proximal bones of the leg and arm are disproportionately long and the distal elements are disproportionately short.<ref name=\"Livezey1992\">{{Cite journal\n| last1 = Livezey | first1 = Bradley C.\n| doi = 10.1002/jmor.1052130108\n| pmid = 29865598\n| title = Morphological corollaries and ecological implications of flightlessness in the kakapo (Psittaciformes: ''Strigops habroptilus'')\n| journal = Journal of Morphology\n| volume = 213\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 105\u2013145\n|date=July 1992\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[pectoralis major muscle|pectoral]] musculature of the kakapo is also modified by flightlessness. The [[pectoralis major muscle|pectoralis]] and [[supracoracoideus]] muscles are greatly reduced. The [[propatagialis tendo longus]] has no distinct muscle belly. The [[sternocoracoideus]] is tendinous. There is an extensive [[cucularis capitis clavicularis]] muscle that is associated with the large crop.<ref name=\"Livezey1992\"/>\n\n===Genetics===\nBecause kakapo passed through a [[Population_bottleneck|genetic bottleneck]], in which the world population was reduced to 49 birds, they are extremely inbred and have low genetic diversity. This manifests in lower disease resistance and fertility problems: 40% of kakapo eggs are infertile.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=White|first=Rebekah|date=Sep\u2013Oct 2016|title=Decoding K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d|url=https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/decoding-kakapo/|journal=New Zealand Geographic|volume=141|pages=|via=}}</ref> Beginning in 2015, the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d 125 project aimed to sequence the [[genome]] of all living kakapo, as well as some museum specimens \u2013 the first time an entire species has had its genome sequenced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/science/77878783/kakapo-to-have-genomes-sequenced-in-a-world-first-for-science|title=Kakapo to have genomes sequenced in a world first for science|last=Thomas|first=Rachel|date=14 March 2016|work=Stuff|access-date=5 December 2018}}</ref> The project is a collaboration between [[Duke University]] and the New Zealand Genomics lab in [[Dunedin]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Habitat ==\nBefore the arrival of humans, the kakapo was distributed throughout both main islands of New Zealand. Although it may have inhabited [[Stewart Island]] before human arrival, it has so far not been found in the extensive fossil collections from there.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wood|first=Jamie R.|date=2016|title=Spatial distribution of late Holocene bird bones in the Mason Bay dune system, Stewart Island, New Zealand|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand|language=en|volume=46|issue=2|pages=103\u2013116|doi=10.1080/03036758.2016.1149497|issn=0303-6758}}</ref> Kakapo lived in a variety of habitats, including [[tussock grass|tussocklands]], scrublands and coastal areas. It also inhabited [[forest]]s dominated by [[Podocarpaceae|podocarps]] ([[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]], [[Prumnopitys taxifolia|matai]], [[Dacrycarpus dacrydioides|kahikatea]], [[Podocarpus totara|totara]]), [[Nothofagus|beeches]], [[tawa (tree)|tawa]], and [[Metrosideros umbellata|rata]]. In [[Fiordland]], areas of avalanche and slip debris with regenerating and heavily fruiting vegetation \u2013 such as five finger, [[Aristotelia serrata|wineberry]], [[bush lawyer (plant)|bush lawyer]], [[tutu (plant)|tutu]], [[hebe (plant)|hebes]], and [[coprosma]]s \u2013 became known as \"kakapo gardens\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=P. N.|date=1975|title=Vegetation associated with kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'' Gray) in Sinbad Gully, Fiordland, New Zealand|journal=New Zealand Journal of Botany|volume=14|issue=2|pages=151\u2013159|doi=10.1080/0028825x.1976.10428889}}</ref>\n\nThe kakapo is considered to be a \"habitat generalist\".<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> Though they are now confined to islands free of predation, they were once able to live in nearly any climate present on the islands of New Zealand. They survived dry, hot summers on the North Island as well as cold winter temperatures in the sub-alpine areas of Fiordland. Kakapo seem to have preferred broadleaf or [[Nothofagus solandri var. cliffortioides|mountain beech]] and [[Podocarpus laetus|Hall's t\u014dtara]] forest with mild winters and high rainfall,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lentini|first=Pia E.|last2=Stirnemann|first2=Ingrid A.|last3=Stojanovic|first3=Dejan|last4=Worthy|first4=Trevor H.|last5=Stein|first5=John A.|date=2018|title=Using fossil records to inform reintroduction of the kakapo as a refugee species|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=217|pages=157\u2013165|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2017.10.027|issn=0006-3207}}</ref> but the species was not exclusively forest-dwelling. All kakapo that were transferred to predator-free islands in the last decades have adapted well to any changes in environment and food plants.\n\n==Ecology and behaviour==\n[[File:Kakapohist.svg|thumb|250px|Historic distribution of the kakapo.\n{{legend|#44a844|Maximum distribution since 1840}}\n{{legend|#ced362|Fossil evidence}}]]\nIt seems that the kakapo \u2013 like many of New Zealand's bird species \u2013 has [[evolution|evolved]] to occupy an [[ecological niche]] normally filled by various species of mammal (the only non-marine mammals native to New Zealand are [[List of mammals of New Zealand#Order: Chiroptera (bats)|three species of small bats]]).\n\nThe kakapo is primarily nocturnal; it roosts under cover in trees or on the ground during the day and moves around its territories at night.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/>\n\nThough the kakapo cannot fly, it is an excellent climber, ascending to the crowns of the tallest trees. It can also \"parachute\" \u2013 descending by leaping and spreading its wings. In this way it may travel a few metres at an angle of less than 45 degrees.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> With only 3.3% of its mass made up of pectoral muscle, it is no surprise that the kakapo cannot use its wings to lift its heavy body off the ground. Because of its flightlessness, it has very low metabolic demands in comparison to flighted birds. It is able to survive easily on very little or on very low quality food sources. Unlike most other bird species, the kakapo is entirely herbivorous, feeding on fruits, seeds, leaves, stems, and rhizomes. When foraging, kakapo tend to leave crescent-shaped wads of fiber in the vegetation behind them, called \"browse signs\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHaving lost the ability to fly, it has developed strong legs. [[Animal locomotion|Locomotion]] is often by way of a rapid \"jog-like\" gait by which it can move several kilometres.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/> A female has been observed making two return trips each night during nesting from her nest to a food source up to {{convert|1|km|mi|1|abbr=on}} away<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Powlesland |first1=R.G. |last2=Lloyd |first2=B.D. |last3=Best |first3=H.A. |last4=Merton |first4=D.V. |authorlink4=Don Merton |title=Breeding Biology of the kakapo ''Strigops-Habroptilus'' on Stewart Island, New Zealand |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=134 |issue=4 |pages=361\u2013373 |date=1992 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1992.tb08016.x}}</ref> and the male may walk from its home range to a mating arena up to {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} away during the mating season (October\u2013January).<ref name=\"Best1985\">{{cite book |first1=H.A. |last1=Best |first2=R.G. |last2=Powlesland |year=1985 |title=Kakapo |publisher=John McIndoe and New Zealand Wildlife Service |location=Dunedin}}</ref>\n[[File:Kakapo Trevor feeding on poroporo fruit.jpg|thumb|left|Individual nicknamed Trevor feeding on [[poroporo]] fruits, Maud Island]] \nYoung birds indulge in play fighting, and one bird will often lock the neck of another under its chin.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Judy |last1=Diamond |first2=Daryl |last2=Eason |first3=Clio |last3=Reid |first4=Alan B. |last4=Bond|year=2006|journal=Behaviour |volume=143 |pages=1397\u20131423 |title=Social play in kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') with comparisons to kea (Nestor notabilis) and kaka (Nestor meridionalis) |doi=10.1163/156853906778987551 |issue=11 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1031&context=bioscibehavior}}</ref> The kakapo is curious by nature and has been known to interact with humans. Conservation staff and volunteers have engaged extensively with some kakapo, which have distinct personalities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/behaviour/ |title=Behaviour |accessdate=6 March 2014 |publisher=Kakapo Recovery}}</ref> While they are curious toward humans, kakapo are not social birds.\n\nThe kakapo was a very successful species in pre-human New Zealand, and was well adapted to avoid the birds of prey which were their only predators. As well as the [[New Zealand falcon]], there were two other birds of prey in pre-human New Zealand: [[Haast's eagle]] and [[Eyles' harrier]].<ref name=\"GOG\"/> All these [[Bird of prey|raptors]] soared overhead searching for prey in daylight, and to avoid them the kakapo evolved camouflaged plumage and became nocturnal. When a kakapo feels threatened, it freezes, so that it is more effectively camouflaged in the vegetation its plumage resembles. Kakapo were not entirely safe at night, when the [[laughing owl]] was active, and it is apparent from owl nest deposits on Canterbury limestone cliffs that kakapo were among their prey.<ref name=\"LWOTM\">{{Cite book|title=The Lost world of the Moa: Prehistoric life in New Zealand|last1=Worthy|first1=T. H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=R. N.|publisher=Canterbury University Press|year=2002|location=Christchurch|page=718}}</ref>\n\nKakapo defensive adaptations were no use, however, against the mammalian predators introduced to New Zealand by humans. Birds hunt very differently from mammals, relying on their powerful vision to find prey, and thus they usually hunt by day.<ref name=\"GOG\" /> Mammalian predators, in contrast to birds, often hunt by night, and rely on their sense of smell and hearing to find prey; a common way for humans to hunt kakapo was by releasing trained dogs.<ref>{{cite book |title=The habits of flightless birds of New Zealand: with notes on other flightless New Zealand birds |last=Henry |first=R. |publisher=Government Printer |year=1903 |location=Wellington}}</ref><ref name=\"GOG\" /> The kakapo's adaptations to avoid avian predation have thus been useless against its new enemies, and the reason for its massive decline since the introduction of dogs, cats and [[Mustelidae|mustelids]] (see ''[[Kakapo#Human impact|Conservation: Human impact]]''). \n[[File:051226-kakapo-billbooming.ogg|thumb|The sound of a kakapo booming]]\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Kakapo egg hatching.jpg|thumb|left|Hatching kakapo egg]] \nThe kakapo is the only extant species of flightless parrot in the world,<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> and the only flightless bird that has a [[lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\">{{cite book |title=Collins Field Guide to New Zealand Wildlife |first1=Terrence |last1=Lindsey |first2=Rod |last2=Morris |publisher=HarperCollins New Zealand |year=2000 |isbn=978-1-86950-300-0}}</ref> Males loosely gather in an arena and compete with each other to attract females. Females listen to the males as they display, or \"lek\".<ref name=\"Merton77\">{{cite book |author-link=Don Merton |author=Merton, D.V. |year=1976 |chapter=Conservation of the kakapo: A progress report. |title=Proc. Science in Nat. Parks. |publisher=National Parks Authority |location=Wellington, N.Z. |series=National Parks Series |volume=6 |pages=139\u2013148}}</ref> They choose a mate based on the quality of his display; they are not pursued by the males in any overt way. No pair bond is formed; males and females meet only to mate.\n\nDuring the courting season, males leave their home ranges for hilltops and ridges where they establish their own mating courts. These leks can be up to {{convert|5|km|mi|0}} from a kakapo's usual territory and are an average of {{Convert|50|m|ft|-1}} apart within the lek arena. Males remain in the region of their court throughout the courting season. At the start of the breeding season, males will fight to try to secure the best courts. They confront each other with raised feathers, spread wings, open beaks, raised claws and loud screeching and growling. Fighting may leave birds with injuries or even kill them.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1017/S0959270900001933 |last1=Clout |first1=M. N. |last2=Merton |first2=D. V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |date=1998 |title=Saving the kakapo: The conservation of the world's most peculiar parrot |journal=Bird Conservation International |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013295}}</ref> Mating occurs only approximately every five years, with the ripening of the rimu fruit. In mating years, males making \"booming\" calls for 6\u20138&nbsp;hours every night for more than four months.\n\nEach court consists of one or more saucer-shaped depressions or \"bowls\" dug in the ground by the male, up to {{Convert|10|cm|in|0}} deep and long enough to fit the half-metre length of the bird. The kakapo is one of only a handful of birds in the world which actually constructs its leks.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\"/> Bowls are often created next to rock faces, banks, or tree trunks to help reflect sound:<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> the bowls themselves function as amplifiers to enhance the projection of the males' booming mating calls.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\"/> Each male's bowls are connected by a network of trails or tracks which may extend {{Convert|50|m|ft|-1}} along a ridge or {{Convert|20|m|ft|-1}} in diameter around a hilltop.<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> Males meticulously clear their bowls and tracks of debris. One way researchers check whether bowls are visited at night is to place a few twigs in the bowl; if the male visits overnight, he will pick them up in his beak and toss them away.\n\nTo attract females, males make loud, low-frequency (below 100&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]]) booming calls from their bowls by inflating a [[thorax|thoracic]] sac.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/><ref name=\"Cockrem2002\">{{cite journal |last=Cockrem |first=J. F. |title=Reproductive biology and conservation of the endangered kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') in New Zealand |journal=Avian and Poultry Biology Reviews |date=2002 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=139\u2013144 |doi=10.3184/147020602783698548}}</ref> They start with low grunts, which increase in volume as the sac inflates. After a sequence of about 20 loud booms, the male kakapo emits a high-frequency, metallic \"ching\" sound.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the kakapo: Breeding |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/breeding/ |website=Kakapo Recovery |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref> He stands for a short while before again lowering his head, inflating his chest and starting another sequence of booms. The booms can be heard at least {{Convert|1|km|mi}} away on a still night; wind can carry the sound at least {{Convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> Males boom for an average of eight hours a night; each male may produce thousands of booms in this time. This may continue every night for three or four months during which time the male may lose half his body weight. Each male moves around the bowls in his court so that the booms are sent out in different directions. These booms are also notorious for attracting predators, because of the long range at which they can be heard.\n\nFemales are attracted by the booms of the competing males; they too may need to walk several kilometres from their territories to the arena. Once a female enters the court of one of the males, the male performs a display in which he rocks from side to side and makes clicking noises with his beak.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> He turns his back to the female, spreads his wings in display and walks backwards towards her. He will then attempt copulation for 40 minutes or more.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d: rescued from the brink of extinction |last=Ballance |first=Alison |publisher=Potton and Burton |year=2018 |isbn=9781877517273 |edition=2nd revised |location=Nelson, New Zealand}}</ref> Once the birds have mated, the female returns to her home territory to lay eggs and raise the chicks. The male continues booming in the hope of attracting another female.\n\n[[File:Kakapo chicks.jpg|thumb|Hatchlings]] \nThe female kakapo lays 1\u20134&nbsp;eggs per breeding cycle, with several days between eggs.<ref name=\"Cockrem2002\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> She nests on the ground under the cover of plants or in cavities such as hollow tree trunks. The female incubates the eggs faithfully, but is forced to leave them every night in search of food. Predators are known to eat the eggs, and the embryos inside can also die of cold in the mother's absence. Kakapo eggs usually hatch within 30&nbsp;days,<ref name=\"Easton2006\">{{cite journal |title=Breeding biology of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') on offshore island sanctuaries, 1990\u20132002 |last1=Eason |first1=Daryl K. |last2=Elliott |first2=Graeme P. |last3=Merton |first3=Don V. |authorlink3=Don Merton |last4=Jansen |first4=Paul W. |last5=Harper |first5=Grant A. |last6=Moorhouse |first6=Ron J. |journal=Notornis |volume=54 |issue=1 |date=2006 |pages=27\u201336 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_27.pdf}}</ref> bearing fluffy grey chicks that are quite helpless. After the eggs hatch, the female feeds the chicks for three months, and the chicks remain with the female for some months after [[fledge|fledging]].<ref name=\"Cockrem2002\"/> The young chicks are just as vulnerable to predators as the eggs, and young have been killed by many of the same predators that attack adults. Chicks leave the nest at approximately 10 to 12&nbsp;weeks of age. As they gain greater independence, their mothers may feed the chicks sporadically for up to 6&nbsp;months.\n\nBecause the kakapo is long-lived, with an average life expectancy of 60 (plus or minus 20) years, it tends to have an adolescence before it starts breeding.<ref name=\":2\" /> Males start booming at about 5&nbsp;years of age.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/> It was thought that females reached [[sexual maturity]] at 9 years of age, but four five-year-old females have now been recorded reproducing.<ref name=\"Easton2006\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> The kakapo does not breed every year and has one of the lowest rates of reproduction among birds. Breeding occurs only in years when trees mast (fruit heavily), providing a plentiful food supply. [[Dacrydium cupressinum|Rimu]] mast occurs only every three to five years, so in rimu-dominant forests, such as those on Whenua Hou, kakapo breeding occurs as infrequently.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Nutrient composition of the diet of parent-raised kakapo nestlings |first1=Yvette |last1=Cottam |first2=Don V. |last2=Merton  |authorlink2=Don Merton |first3=Wouter |last3=Hendriks |pages=90\u201399|journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |year=2006 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_90.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAnother aspect of the kakapo's breeding system is that a female can alter the sex ratio of her offspring depending on her condition. A female in good condition produces more male offspring (males have 30%\u201340% more body weight than females<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>). Females produce offspring biased towards the dispersive sex when competition for resources (such as food) is high and towards the non-dispersive sex when food is plentiful. A female kakapo will likely be able to produce eggs even when there are few resources, while a male kakapo will be more capable of perpetuating the species when there are plenty, by mating with several females.<ref name=\"berkeley_kakapo_reproduction\">{{cite web |url=http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/news/060401_kakapo |title=Conserving the kakapo |accessdate=22 March 2008 |date=April 2006 |work=Understanding Evolution |publisher=University of California, Berkeley}}</ref> This supports the [[Trivers\u2013Willard hypothesis]]. The relationship between clutch sex ratio and maternal diet has conservation implications, because a captive population maintained on a high quality diet will produce fewer females and therefore fewer individuals valuable to the recovery of the species.<ref name=\"sutherland-sciencesexkakapo\">{{cite journal |last=Sutherland |first=William J. |title=Conservation biology: Science, sex and the kakapo |journal=Nature |volume=419 |year=2002 |pages=265\u2013266 |doi=10.1038/419265a |pmid=12239554 |issue=6904}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe beak of the kakapo is adapted for grinding food finely. For this reason, the kakapo has a very small [[gizzard]] compared to other birds of their size. It is entirely [[Herbivore|herbivorous]], eating native plants, seeds, fruits, pollen and even the sapwood of trees. A study in 1984 identified 25 plant species as kakapo food.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/> It is particularly fond of the fruit of the [[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]] tree, and will feed on it exclusively during seasons when it is abundant. The kakapo strips out the nutritious parts of the plant out with its beak, leaving a ball of indigestible fibre. These little clumps of plant fibres are a distinctive sign of the presence of the bird.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Gray |first=R. S. |year=1977| title=The kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'', Gray 1847), its food, feeding and habitat in Fiordland and Maud Island| version=MSc thesis| publisher=Massey University, Palmerston North, New Zealand}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Atkinson |first1=I.A.E. |last2=Merton |first2=D.V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |year=2006 |title=Habitat and diet of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') in the Esperance Valley, Fiordland, New Zealand |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=37\u201354 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_37.pdf}}</ref> The kakapo is believed to employ bacteria in the fore-gut to ferment and help digest plant matter.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Lopez-Calleja |first1 = M. Victoria |last2=Bozinovic | first2 = F. |doi=10.4067/S0716-078X2000000300005 |title=Energetics and nutritional ecology of small herbivorous birds |journal=Revista Chilena de Historia Natural |volume=73 |issue=3 |year=2000 |pages=411\u2013420}}</ref>\n\nKakapo diet changes according to the season. The plants eaten most frequently during the year include some species of ''[[Lycopodium ramulosum]]'', ''Lycopodium fastigium'', ''Schizaea fistulosa'', ''Blechnum minus'', ''Blechnum procerum'', ''Cyathodes juniperina'', ''Dracophyllum longifolium'', ''Olearia colensoi'' and ''Thelymitra venosa''. Individual plants of the same species are often treated differently. Kakapo leave conspicuous evidence of their feeding activities, over feeding areas that range between {{Convert|10|\u00d7|10|m|ft|-1}} and {{Convert|50|\u00d7|100|m|ft|-1}} per individual.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/> Kakapo feeding grounds almost always host [[Leptospermum scoparium|manuka]] and yellow silver pine (''[[Lepidothamnus intermedius]]'') scrubs.\n\n==Conservation==\nFossil records indicate that in pre-Polynesian times, the kakapo was New Zealand's third most common bird<ref name=\"GOG\">{{Cite book |title=Ghosts of Gondwana; The history of life in New Zealand |first=George |last=Gibbs |publisher=Craig Potton Publishing |year=2007}}</ref> and it was widespread on all three main islands. However, the kakapo population in New Zealand has declined massively since human settlement of the country, and its conservation status as ranked by the Department of Conservation continues to be \"Nationally Critical\".<ref name=\"NZTCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nztcs.org.nz/#/assessments/31698|title=NZTCS Assessment Details |website=www.nztcs.org.nz |access-date=2019-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122223418/https://nztcs.org.nz/#/assessments/31698 |archive-date=22 January 2019 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 1891, conservation efforts have been made to prevent extinction. The most successful scheme has been the Kakapo Recovery Programme; this was implemented in 1995 and continues.\n\n===Human impact===\n[[File:Naturhistorisches Museum, Kakapo.jpg|thumb| [[Zoological specimen|Specimens]] at the [[Vienna Museum of Natural History]]; thousands of kakapo were collected for museums across the world]]\nThe first factor in the decline of the kakapo was the arrival of humans. [[M\u0101ori mythology|M\u0101ori folklore]] suggests that the kakapo was found throughout the country when the [[Polynesians]] first arrived in [[Aotearoa]] 700 years ago.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> [[Subfossil]] and [[midden]] deposits show that the bird was present throughout the North and South Island before and during early M\u0101ori times.<ref name=\"FGNZB\">{{cite book |first1=Barrie |last1=Heather |first2=Hugh |last2=Robertson |others=illustrated by Derek Onley |title=The Field Guide to the Birds of New Zealand |publisher=Viking |edition=revised |year=2005}}</ref> M\u0101ori hunted the kakapo for food and for their skins and feathers, which were made into [[M\u0101ori traditional textiles|cloaks]].<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> They used the dried heads as ear ornaments.\n\nDue to its inability to fly, strong scent and habit of freezing when threatened, the kakapo was easy prey for the M\u0101ori and their dogs. Its eggs and chicks were also preyed upon by the [[Polynesian rat]] or kiore, which the M\u0101ori brought to New Zealand as a stowaway.<ref name=\"Merton77\"/> Furthermore, the deliberate clearing of vegetation by M\u0101ori reduced the habitable range for kakapo. Although the kakapo was extinct in many parts of the islands by the time Europeans arrived,<ref name=\"Williams1956\">{{cite journal |journal=Notornis |first=G.R. |last=Williams |title=The kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'', Gray): A review and reappraisal of a near-extinct species |volume=7 |issue=2 |year=1956 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_7_2.pdf |pages=29\u201356}}</ref> including the [[Tararua Ranges|Tararua]] and [[Aorangi Range]]s,<ref name=\"FLM\">{{cite book |last=Best |first=Elsdon |authorlink=Elsdon Best |title=Forest Lore of the Maori |url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-BesFore.html |access-date=11 May 2012 |series=Memoirs of the Polynesian Society. '''18'''. Dominion Museum bulletin |volume=14 |year=1977 |origyear=1942 |publisher=E.C. Keating, Government Printer |location=[[Wellington]], New Zealand |oclc=639613989 |pages=170\u2013175 |chapter=Bird Lore: How birds were taken \u2013 K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d (''Strigops habroptilus'') |chapter-url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-BesFore-t1-body-d2-d6-d3.html}}</ref> it was locally abundant in parts of New Zealand, such as the central North Island and forested parts of the South Island.<ref name=\"FGNZB\"/>\n\nAlthough kakapo numbers were reduced by M\u0101ori settlement, they declined much more rapidly after European colonisation.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bergner|first=Laura M. |last2=Dussex |first2=Nicolas |last3=Jamieson |first3=Ian G. |last4=Robertson |first4=Bruce C. |date=2016 |title=European colonization, not Polynesian arrival, impacted population size and genetic diversity in the critically endangered New Zealand k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |journal=Journal of Heredity |language=en |volume=107 |issue=7 |pages=593\u2013602 |doi=10.1093/jhered/esw065 |pmid=27694405 |issn=0022-1503}}</ref> Beginning in the 1840s, [[P\u0101keh\u0101]] settlers [[Deforestation in New Zealand#European settlement|cleared vast tracts of land]] for farming and grazing, further reducing kakapo habitat. They brought more dogs and other mammalian predators, including domestic cats, black rats and [[Stoats in New Zealand|stoats]].<ref name=\"Sutherland2002\">{{cite journal |journal=Nature |title=Conservation biology: Science, sex, and the kakapo |volume=419 |issue=6904 |first=W.J. |last=Sutherland |pages=265\u2013266 |doi=10.1038/419265a |pmid=12239554 |year=2002}}</ref> Europeans knew little of the kakapo until [[George Robert Gray|George Gray]] of the [[British Museum]] described it from a skin in 1845. As the M\u0101ori had done, early European explorers and their dogs ate kakapo. In the late 19th century, the kakapo became well known as a scientific curiosity, and thousands were captured or killed for zoos, museums and collectors. Most captured specimens died within months. From at least the 1870s, collectors knew the kakapo population was declining; their prime concern was to collect as many as possible before the bird became extinct.\n\nIn the 1880s, large numbers of [[Mustelidae|mustelids]] (stoats, ferrets and weasels) were released in New Zealand to reduce rabbit numbers,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Murphy |first1=E. |last2=Dowding |first2=J. | year=1995 |title=Ecology of the stoat in ''Nothofagus'' forest: home range, habitat use and diet at different stages of the beech mast cycle |journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=97\u2013109 |url=http://www.nzes.org.nz/nzje/free_issues/NZJEcol19_2_97.pdf}}</ref> but they also preyed heavily on many native species including the kakapo. Other browsing animals, such as introduced deer, competed with the kakapo for food, and caused the extinction of some of its preferred plant species. The kakapo was reportedly still present near the head of the [[Whanganui River]] as late as 1894, with one of the last records of a kakapo in the North Island being a single bird caught in the [[Kaimanawa Range]]s by Te Kepa Puawheawhe in 1895.<ref name=\"FLM\"/>\n\n===Early protection efforts===\nIn 1891, the New Zealand government set aside [[Resolution Island, New Zealand|Resolution Island]] in Fiordland as a nature reserve. In 1894, the government appointed [[Richard Treacy Henry|Richard Henry]] as caretaker. A keen naturalist, Henry was aware that native birds were declining, and began catching and moving kakapo and [[kiwi]] from the mainland to the predator-free Resolution Island. In six years, he moved more than 200&nbsp;kakapo to Resolution Island. By 1900, however, [[stoat]]s had swum to Resolution Island and colonised it; they wiped out the nascent kakapo population within 6&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"Hill1987\">{{cite book |author1=Hill, S. |author2=Hill, J. |year=1987 |title=Richard Henry of Resolution Island |location=Dunedin |publisher=John McIndoe}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, three kakapo were moved from Resolution Island to the nature reserve of [[Little Barrier Island]] (Hauturu-o-Toi) north-east of [[Auckland]], but [[feral cats]] were present and the kakapo were never seen again. In 1912, three kakapo were moved to another reserve, [[Kapiti Island]], north-west of [[Wellington]]. One of them survived until at least 1936, despite the presence of feral cats for part of the intervening period.<ref name=\"Hill1987\"/>\n\nBy the 1920s, the kakapo was extinct in the [[North Island]] and its range and numbers in the [[South Island]] were declining.<ref name=\"Williams1956\"/> One of its last refuges was rugged Fiordland. There, during the 1930s, it was often seen or heard, and occasionally eaten, by hunters or roadworkers. By the 1940s, reports of kakapo were becoming scarce.\n{{clear}}\n\n===1950\u20131989 conservation efforts===\n[[File:Milford Sound and Sinbad Gully -New Zealand-9Jan2009.jpg|right|thumb|Sinbad Gully in Fiordland, seen between the mountains on the far side of a [[fjord]], was one of the last strongholds of the kakapo on mainland New Zealand.<ref name=LCTSee-2009>{{cite episode |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00mg3qk |title=Last Chance to See |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |series=Last Chance to See |series-link=Last Chance to See (TV series) |airdate=2009-10-04 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nIn the 1950s, the [[New Zealand Wildlife Service]] was established and began making regular expeditions to search for the kakapo, mostly in Fiordland and what is now the [[Kahurangi National Park]] in the northwest of the South Island. Seven Fiordland expeditions between 1951 and 1956 found only a few recent signs. Finally, in 1958 a kakapo was caught and released in the [[Milford Sound]] catchment area in Fiordland. Six more kakapo were captured in 1961; one was released and the other five were transferred to the [[aviary|aviaries]] of the Mount Bruce Bird Reserve near [[Masterton]] in the North Island. Within months, four of the birds had died and the fifth died after about four years. In the next 12&nbsp;years, regular expeditions found few signs of the kakapo, indicating that numbers were continuing to decline. Only one bird was captured in 1967; it died the following year.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Donald |first1=Paul F. |last2=Collar |first2=Nigel J.|last3=Marsden |first3=Stuart J. |last4=Pain |first4=Deborah J. |title=Facing Extinction: The World's Rarest Birds and the Race to Save Them |year=2010 |publisher=T & A D Poyser |location=London |isbn=978-0-7136-7021-9 |p=167}}</ref>\n\nBy the early 1970s, it was uncertain whether the kakapo was still an extant species. At the end of 1974, scientists located several more male kakapo and made the first scientific observations of kakapo booming. These observations led [[Don Merton]] to speculate for the first time that the kakapo had a [[Lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system.<ref name=\"Merton77\"/> From 1974 to 1978 a total of 18&nbsp;kakapo were discovered in Fiordland, but all were males. This raised the possibility that the species would become extinct, because there might be no surviving females. One male bird was captured in the Milford area in 1975, christened \"Richard Henry\", and transferred to [[Maud Island]]. All the birds the Wildlife Service discovered from 1951 to 1976 were in U-shaped [[glaciated valley]]s flanked by almost-vertical cliffs and surrounded by high mountains. Such extreme terrain had slowed colonisation by browsing mammals, leaving islands of virtually unmodified native vegetation. However, even here, stoats were present and by 1976 the kakapo was gone from the valley floors and only a few males survived high on the most inaccessible parts of the cliffs.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nBefore 1977, no expedition had been to [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]] to search for the bird. In 1977, sightings of kakapo were reported on [[Stewart Island]].<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> An expedition to the island found a track and bowl system on its first day; soon after, it located several dozen kakapo. The finding in an 8,000-hectare area of fire-modified [[scrubland]] and forest raised hope that the population would include females. The total population was estimated at 100 to 200&nbsp;birds.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/03014223.1995.9518039 |last1=Powlesland |first1=R.G. |last2=Roberts|first2=A. |last3=Lloyd |first3=B.D. |last4=Merton |first4=D.V. |authorlink4=Don Merton |year=1995 |title=Number, fate and distribution of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') found on Stewart Island, New Zealand, 1979\u201392 |journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=239\u2013248}}</ref>\n\n[[Mustelid]]s have never colonised [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]], but feral cats were present. During a survey, it was apparent that cats killed kakapo at a rate of 56% per year.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Karl |first1=B.J |last2=Best |first2=H.A. |title=Feral cats on Stewart Island: their foods and their effects on kakapo |journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=287\u2013294 |year=1982 |doi=10.1080/03014223.1982.10423857}}</ref> At this rate, the birds could not survive on the island and therefore an intensive cat control was introduced in 1982, after which no cat-killed kakapo were found.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> However, to ensure the survival of the remaining birds, scientists decided later that this population should be transferred to predator-free islands; this operation was carried out between 1982 and 1997.<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\">{{cite journal |first1=B.D. |last1=Lloyd |first2=R.G. |last2=Powlesland |title=The decline of kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' and attempts at conservation by translocation |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=69 |issue=1 |year=1994 |pages=75\u201385 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(94)90330-1}}</ref>\n\n===Kakapo Recovery programme===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Kakapo Translocations 1974\u20131992<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\"/>\n|-\n! Translocated to !! Number of kakapo !! Deaths < 6 months !! Survived as of November 1992\n|-\n| Maud Island (1974\u201381) || 9 (6\u2642, 3\u2640) || 3 (2\u2642, 1\u2640) || 4 (2\u2642, 2\u2640)\n|-\n| Little Barrier Island (1982) || 22 (13\u2642, 9\u2640) || 2 (1\u2642, 1\u2640) || 15\u201319 (10\u201312\u2642, 5\u20137\u2640)\n|-\n| Codfish Island (1987\u201392) || 30 (20\u2642, 10\u2640) || 0 || 20\u201330 (13\u201320\u2642, 7\u201310\u2640)\n|-\n| Maud Island (1989\u201391) || 6 (4\u2642, 2\u2640) || 0 || 5 (3\u2642, 2\u2640)\n|-\n| Mana Island (1992) || 2 (2\u2640) || 1 (1\u2640) || 1 (1\u2640)\n|-\n| '''Total''' || 65 (43\u2642, 22\u2640) || 6 (3\u2642, 3\u2640) || 41\u201355 (27\u201336\u2642, 14\u201319\u2640)\n|-\n| colspan=4 |'''Note:''' \u2642 = males, \u2640 = females.\n|}\n\nIn 1989, a Kakapo Recovery plan was developed, and a Kakapo Recovery programme was established in 1995.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.| year=1989 | title=Kakapo recovery plan 1989\u20131994| publisher=Department of Conservation| location=Wellington}}</ref> The New Zealand [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] replaced the Wildlife Service for this task.\n\nThe first action of the plan was to relocate all the remaining kakapo to suitable islands for them to breed. None of the New Zealand islands were ideal to establish kakapo without [[Island restoration|rehabilitation]] by extensive re-vegetation and the eradication of introduced mammalian predators and competitors. Four islands were finally chosen: [[Maud Island|Maud]], [[Little Barrier Island|Hauturu/Little Barrier]], [[Codfish Island|Codfish]] and [[Mana Island, New Zealand|Mana]].<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\" /> Sixty-five kakapo (43 males, 22 females) were successfully transferred onto the four islands in five translocations.<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\" /> Some islands had to be rehabilitated several times when feral cats, stoats and [[weka]] kept appearing. Little Barrier Island was eventually viewed as unsuitable due to the rugged landscape, the thick forest and the continued presence of rats, and its birds were evacuated in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/little-barrier-island/|title=Little Barrier Island |publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> Along with Mana Island, it was replaced with two new kakapo sanctuaries: [[Chalky Island (New Zealand)|Chalky Island (Te Kakahu)]] and [[Anchor Island]].<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> The entire kakapo population of Codfish Island was temporarily relocated in 1999 to [[Pearl Island (New Zealand)|Pearl Island]] in [[Port Pegasus]] while rats were being eliminated from Codfish.<ref name=\"Whitehead\">{{cite thesis | first = Joanna K. | last = Whitehead | title = Breeding success of adult female kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') on Codfish Island (Whenua Hou): correlations with foraging home ranges and habitat selection | year = 2007 |publisher=Lincoln University |type=MSc thesis | hdl = 10182/640 }}</ref> All kakapo on Pearl and Chalky Islands were moved to Anchor Island in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=57&Itemid=223|title=Updates: June to September 2005 |publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=12 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616192606/http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=57&Itemid=223|archivedate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Supplementary feeding====\nA key part of the Recovery Programme is the supplementary feeding of females. Kakapo breed only once every two to five years, when certain plant species, primarily [[Dacrydium cupressinum|''Dacrydium cupressinum'' (rimu)]], produce protein-rich fruit and seeds. During breeding years when rimu masts supplementary food is provided to kakapo to increase the likelihood of individuals successfully breeding.<ref name=\"Elliott2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Elliott |first1=G.P. |last2=Merton |first2=D.V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |last3=Jansen |first3=P. W. |year=2001 |title=Intensive management of a critically endangered species: the kakapo |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=99 |pages=121\u2013133 |issue=1 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(00)00191-9}}</ref> In 1989, six preferred foods (apples, sweet potatoes, almonds, Brazil nuts, sunflower seeds and walnuts) were supplied ''[[ad libitum]]'' each night to 12&nbsp;feeding stations. Males and females ate the supplied foods, and females nested on Little Barrier Island in the summers of 1989\u20131991 for the first time since 1982, although nesting success was low.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=R.G. |last1=Powlesland |first2=B.D. |last2=Lloyd |title=Use of supplementary feeding to induce breeding in free-living kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' in New Zealand |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=69 |issue=1 |year=1994 |pages=97\u2013106 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(94)90332-8}}</ref>\n\nSupplementary feeding affects the [[sex ratio]] of kakapo offspring, and can be used to increase the number of female chicks by deliberately manipulating maternal condition.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Robertson |first1=B.C. |last2=Elliott |first2=G.P. |last3=Eason |first3=D.K. |last4=Clout |first4=M.N. |last5=Gemmell |first5=N.J. |year=2006 |title=Sex allocation theory aids species conservation |journal=[[Biology Letters]] |pmid=17148369 |pages=229\u2013231 |volume=2 |pmc=1618899 |issue=2 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2005.0430}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> During the winter of 1981, only females lighter than {{convert|1.5|kg|abbr=on}} were given supplementary feeding to avoid raising their body condition, and the sex ratio results in 1982 were close to parity, eliminating the male-biased sex ratios in the unrestricted feeding.\n\nToday commercial parrot food is supplied to all individuals of breeding age on Whenua Hou and Anchor. The amount eaten and individual weights are carefully monitored to ensure that optimum body condition is maintained.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Nest management====\n[[File:Stephen Bragg with kakapo chicks.jpg|thumb|left|Department of Conservation worker with chicks]]Kakapo nests are intensively managed. Before [[Polynesian rat]]s were removed from Whenua Hou, they were a threat to the survival of young kakapo. Of 21 chicks that hatched between 1981 and 1994, nine were either killed by rats or died and were subsequently eaten by rats.<ref name=\"Elliott2001\" /> Nest protection was intensified after 1995 by using [[rat trap|traps]] and poison stations as soon as a nest was detected. A small video camera and [[Infrared|infra-red light source]] would watch the nest continuously, and scare approaching rats with flashing lights and loud popping sounds.\n\nAll kakapo islands are now rat-free, but infrared cameras still allow rangers to remotely monitor the behaviour of females and chicks in nests. Data loggers record when mother kakapo come and go, allowing rangers to pick a time to check on the health of chicks, and also indicate how hard females are having to work to find food. Because mother kakapo often struggle to successfully rear multiple chicks, Kakapo Recovery rangers will move chicks between nests as needed.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nEggs are often removed from nests for incubation to reduce the likelihood of accidents, such as lost eggs or crushing. If chicks become ill, aren\u2019t putting on weight, or there are too many chicks in the nest (and no available nest to move them to) they will be hand-reared by the Kakapo Recovery team.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the 2019 season, eggs were also removed from nests to encourage females to re-nest. By hand-raising the first group of chicks in captivity and encouraging females to lay more eggs, the Kakapo Recovery Team hoped that overall chick production would be increased.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/programmes/kakapo-files/story/2018678725/super-studs-and-hitting-the-reset-button |title=Super-studs & hitting the reset button |website=RNZ |date=17 January 2019 |last=Ballance |first=A. |access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref> By the end of February 2020, the bird's summer breeding season, these efforts led to the production of 80 chicks, \"a record number.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/14/worlds-fattest-parrot-comeback-from-extinction-aoe |title=How the world's fattest parrot came back from the brink |website=The Guardian|date=14 March 2020 |last=Evans|first=Kate |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Monitoring====\nTo monitor the kakapo population continuously, each bird is equipped with a [[radio transmitter]].<ref name=\"Elliott2001\" /> [[List of kakapo|Every known kakapo, barring some young chicks, has been given a name]] by Kakapo Recovery Programme officials, and detailed data is gathered about every individual.<ref name=\":4\" /> GPS transmitters are also being trialled to provide more detailed data about the movement of individual birds and their habitat use.<ref name=\":2\" /> The signals also provide behavioural data, letting rangers gather information about mating and nesting remotely.<ref name=\":4\" /> Every individual kakapo receives an annual health check and has their transmitter replaced.\n\n====Reintroduction====\nThe Kakapo Recovery programme has been successful, with the numbers of kakapo increasing steadily. Adult survival rate and productivity have both improved significantly since the programme's inception. However, the main goal is to establish at least one viable, self-sustaining, unmanaged population of kakapo as a functional component of the [[ecosystem]] in a protected habitat.<ref>{{cite book |title=Kakapo recovery plan 1996\u20132005. Threatened Species Recovery Plan No. 21 .|last=Cresswell|first=M. |publisher=Department of Conservation |year=1996 |location=Wellington}}</ref> To help meet this conservation challenge, [[Resolution Island, New Zealand|Resolution Island]] (20,860&nbsp;ha) in Fiordland has been prepared for kakapo re-introduction with ecological restoration including the eradication of stoats.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/southland/kakapo-overcrowding-may-force-return-island |title=Kakapo overcrowding may force return to island |last=McNeilly |first=Hamish |date=30 July 2011 |work=Otago Daily Times Online News |access-date=2018-12-04 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> Ultimately, the Kakapo Recovery vision for the species is to restore the \"mauri\" (Maori for \"life-force\") of the kakapo by breeding 150&nbsp;adult females.<ref name=\"PFTF\">{{cite web |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/a-plan-for-the-future/ |title=A Plan for the Future 2006\u20132016|publisher=Kakapo Recovery |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127092154/http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/a-plan-for-the-future/ |archive-date=27 January 2018 |access-date=26 December 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Fatal fungal infection====\nIn late April 2019, the first case of the fungal disease ''[[aspergillosis]]'' in New Zealand k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d was discovered. {{As of|2019|06|13|post=,}} almost 20% of the population, or 36 birds, have been flown by helicopter to veterinary hospitals around New Zealand for [[CT scan]] diagnosis and intensive treatment that usually lasted for several months.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Charles |title=World's fattest parrot, the endangered k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d, could be wiped out by fungal infection |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/13/worlds-fattest-parrot-endangered-kakapo-fungal-infection-new-zealand |website=Guardian International |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 June 2019 |quote=The world\u2019s fattest parrot is facing an existential threat in the form of a dangerous fungal infection which has already endangered a fifth of its species.  Seven of New Zealand\u2019s native k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d have died in recent months after falling victim to the respiratory disease aspergillosis. The latest was on Tuesday, where a 100-day-old chick died at the Auckland Zoo.  The nocturnal and flightless parrot ingratiated itself with world after it mated with a zoologist\u2019s head during a BBC documentary. The incident led it to being described as the \u201cparty parrot\u201d and finding a life-long fan in Stephen Fry.}}</ref>\n\n[[Dunedin]]'s Wildlife Hospital has treated 12 birds.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Van Velthooven |first1=Emily |title=Spate of k\u0101k\u0101po deaths 'the devastating outcome of the really great breeding season' |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/spate-k-po-deaths-devastating-outcome-really-great-breeding-season |accessdate=13 June 2019 |publisher=One News Now |quote=While aspergillosis isn\u2019t incurable, time is a defining factor. Dr.&nbsp;Chatterton says the best chance a k\u0101k\u0101po has is an early diagnosis with lots of medication. \"But that\u2019s really challenging with wild birds.\" It\u2019s not just Auckland helping, Massey University's Wild Base Hospital in Palmerston North has taken in six birds for treatment and Dunedin's Wildlife Hospital has taken in a further 12.}}</ref>\n\n==Population timeline==\n[[File:Kakapo-population-size.svg|thumb|upright=2|Cat control in 1982 arrested a sharp decline in kakapo numbers, and they have recently increased under the Kakapo Recovery plan. Red arrows indicate breeding years. Numbers become less precise before 1995, with the 1977 figure perhaps out by 50&nbsp;birds.]]\n\n* 1977: Kakapo rediscovered on [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]]\n* 1989: Most kakapo are removed from Rakiura to Whenua Hou and Hauturu-O-Toi\n* 1995: Kakapo population consists of 51 individuals; beginning of the Kakapo Recovery Programme\n* 1999: Kakapo removed from Hauturu\n* 2002: A significant breeding season led to 24&nbsp;chicks being hatched\n* 2005: 41&nbsp;females and 45&nbsp;males, including four fledglings (3&nbsp;females and 1&nbsp;male); kakapo established on Anchor Island<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" />\n* 2009: The total kakapo population rose to over 100 for the first time since monitoring began.<ref>{{cite news |author=NZPA |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/2251118/Kakapo-population-over-100-mark|title=Kakapo population over 100&nbsp;mark |work=stuff.co.nz |date=11 March 2009}}</ref> Twenty-two of the 34&nbsp;chicks had to be hand-reared because of a shortage of food on Codfish Island.<ref>{{cite news |author=NZPA |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/2328772/Keeping-kakapo-alive|title=Keeping kakapo alive |work=stuff.co.nz |date=11 April 2009}}</ref>\n* December 2010: Death of the oldest known kakapo, \"Richard Henry\", possibly 80 years old.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2011/kakapo-males-boom-on-as-legendary-bird-dies/ |title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d males 'boom' on as legendary bird dies |date=13 January 2011 |website=DOC |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n* 2012: Seven kakapo  transferred to Hauturu, in an attempt to establish a successful breeding programme. Kakapo were last on the island in 1999.<ref name=\"barrier\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/6746273/Kakapo-relocated-to-raise-chicks |title=Kakapo relocated to raise chicks|publisher=stuff.co.nz |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n* March 2014: With the kakapo population having increased to 126, the bird's recovery was used by [[Melbourne]] artist Sayraphim Lothian as a metaphor for the [[February 2011 Christchurch earthquake|recovery of Christchurch]], parallelling the \"indomitable spirit of these two communities and their determination to rebuild\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Kakapo sculptures hidden in Christchurch |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/9834934/Find-a-kakapo-keep-the-love |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140317050015/http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/9834934/Find-a-kakapo-keep-the-love |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 March 2014 |last=Harvie |first=Will |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Journey \u2013 A new work by Sayraphim Lothian with support from Gap Filler |url=http://www.gapfiller.org.nz/journey-a-new-work-by-sayraphim-lothian-with-support-from-gap-filler/ |accessdate=17 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317092202/http://www.gapfiller.org.nz/journey-a-new-work-by-sayraphim-lothian-with-support-from-gap-filler/ |archivedate=17 March 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2016: First breeding on Anchor; a significant breeding season, with 32&nbsp;chicks; kakapo population grows to over 150\n* 2018: After the death of 3&nbsp;birds, the population has been reduced to 149.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://createsend.com/t/i-FE4939184088B7162540EF23F30FEDED |title=News and updates from the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Recovery Team |website=createsend.com |access-date=2018-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822231212/http://createsend.com/t/i-FE4939184088B7162540EF23F30FEDED |archive-date=22 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2019: An abundance of rimu fruit and the introduction of several new technologies (including [[artificial insemination]] and 'smart eggs') helped make 2019 the best breeding season on record, with over 200&nbsp;eggs laid and 72&nbsp;chicks fledged {{As of|2019|07|01|lc=y}}. According to the Kakapo Recovery Team at the New Zealand Department of Conservation, this was the earliest and longest breeding season yet.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/programmes/kakapo-files/story/2018684744/kakapo-rangers |title=Breaking news from one of the world's favourite birds - New Zealand's rare flightless parrot, the k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |website=radionz.co.nz |access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2019/first-new-kakapo-chicks-hatch/ |title=News and updates from the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Recovery Team|website=govt.nz |access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> Population reached 200 juvenile or older birds on 17 Aug 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet | last = Digby | first = Andrew |user=takapodigs |author-link=Andrew Digby|number= 1162835621523664898|date=17 Aug 2019 |title= 200 #kakapo! The population has reached 200 today, with the latest chick (Esperance-3-B-19) becoming a juvenile - when we add birds to the official tally. There are probably more k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d alive now than at any time for \u226570 years. #kakapo2019 #conservation pic: @deidre_vercoe}}</ref>\n\n==In M\u0101ori culture==\nThe kakapo is associated with a rich tradition of M\u0101ori folklore and beliefs. The bird's irregular breeding cycle was understood to be associated with heavy fruiting or \"[[Mast year|masting]]\" events of particular plant species such as the [[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]], which led M\u0101ori to credit the bird with the ability to tell the future.<ref name=\"MBL\">{{cite book |first=Murdoch |last=Riley |title=Maori Bird Lore; An introduction |publisher=Viking Sevenseas NZ LTD. |year=2001}}</ref> Used to substantiate this claim were reported observations of these birds dropping the berries of the [[Elaeocarpus dentatus|hinau]] and [[Tawa (tree)|tawa]] trees (when they were in season) into secluded pools of water to preserve them as a food supply for the summer ahead; in legend this became the origin of the M\u0101ori practice of immersing food in water for the same purpose.<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\n===Use for food and clothing===\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus (AM LB14666-3).jpg|thumb|upright|Feathers]] \nThe meat of kakapo made good eating and was considered by M\u0101ori to be a delicacy<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> and it was hunted for food when it was still widespread.<ref name=\"WS\">{{Cite book |first1=Rod |last1=Morris |first2=Hal |last2=Smith |title=Wild South: Saving New Zealand's endangered birds |publisher=Random House |location=New Zealand |year=1995}}</ref> One source states that its flesh \"resembles [[Lamb and mutton|lamb]] in taste and texture\",<ref name=\"MBL\"/> although European settlers have described the bird as having a \"strong and slightly stringent [sic] flavour\".<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/>\n\nIn breeding years, the loud booming calls of the males at their [[Lek (mating arena)|mating arenas]] made it easy for M\u0101ori hunting parties to track the kakapo down, and it was also hunted while feeding or when dust-bathing in dry weather. The bird was caught, generally at night, using [[Trapping (Animal)#Snares|snares]], pitfall traps, or by groups of domesticated [[Kur\u012b|Polynesian dogs]] which accompanied hunting parties \u2013 sometimes they would use fire sticks of various sorts to dazzle a bird in the darkness, stopping it in their tracks and making the capture easier.<ref name=\"MBL\"/> Cooking was done in a [[h\u0101ngi]] or in gourds of boiling oil.<ref name=\"WS\"/> The flesh of the bird could be preserved in its own fat and stored in containers for later consumption \u2013 hunters of the [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] tribe would pack the flesh in baskets made from the inner bark of [[totara]] tree or in containers constructed from [[kelp]].<ref name=\"KM\">{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/iwi-perspective/ |title=New Zealand Ma\u014dri and the k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |publisher=Kakapo Recovery |year=2015 |accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> Bundles of kakapo tail feathers were attached to the sides of these containers to provide decoration and a way to identify their contents.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\">{{cite journal |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_191.pdf |first=Rob |last=Tipa |title=Short note: Kakapo in M\u0101ori lore |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |pages=193\u2013194 |year=2006 |issue=1}}</ref><ref name=\"KM\"/> Also taken by the M\u0101ori were the bird's eggs, which are described as whitish \"but not pure white\", and about the same size as a [[kerer\u016b]] egg.<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\nAs well as eating the meat of the kakapo, M\u0101ori would use kakapo skins with the feathers still attached or individually weave in kakapo feathers with flax fibre to create cloaks and capes.<ref name=\"WS\"/><ref name=\"KM\"/><ref>{{cite web| title = Kakapo feather cloak | work = Search the collection database | publisher = British Museum | url = https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=497615&partid=1&IdNum=Oc1936,0607.1&orig=/research/search_the_collection_database/museum_no__provenance_search.aspx | accessdate = 1 August 2010}}</ref> Each one required up to 11,000 feathers to make.<ref name=\"WNZB?\"/> Not only were these garments considered very beautiful, they also kept the wearer very warm.<ref name=\"WS\"/><ref name=\"WNZB?\">{{Cite book |first=Andrew |last=Crowe |title=Which New Zealand Bird? |publisher=Penguin |year=2001}}</ref> They were highly valued, and the few still in existence today are considered ''[[taonga]]'' (treasures) \u2013 indeed, the old M\u0101ori adage \"You have a k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d cape and you still complain of the cold\" was used to describe someone who is never satisfied.<ref name=\"WS\"/> Kakapo feathers were also used to decorate the heads of [[taiaha]], but were removed before use in combat.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/><ref name=\"KM\"/><ref name=\"WNZB?\"/>\n\nDespite this, the kakapo was also regarded as an affectionate pet by the M\u0101ori. This was corroborated by European settlers in New Zealand in the 19th century, among them [[George Edward Grey]], who once wrote in a letter to an associate that his pet kakapo's behaviour towards him and his friends was \"more like that of a dog than a bird\".<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\n==In the media==\nThe conservation of the kakapo has made the species well known. Many books and documentaries detailing the plight of the kakapo have been produced in recent years, one of the earliest being ''Two in the Bush'', made by [[Gerald Durrell]] for the [[BBC]] in 1962.<ref name=\"GeraldDurrellBBC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.durrellwildlife.org/index.cfm?a=51 |title=Gerald Durrell's career |publisher=durrellwildlife.org |accessdate = 8 August 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070725220741/http://www.durrellwildlife.org/index.cfm?a=51 |archive-date=25 July 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nA feature-length documentary, ''The Unnatural History of the Kakapo''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elwin.co.nz/kakapo-film/ |title=The Unnatural History of the Kakapo |publisher=Elwin.co.nz |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref> won two major awards at the [[Reel Earth Environmental Film Festival]]. Two of the most significant documentaries, both made by [[NHNZ]], are ''Kakapo \u2013 Night Parrot'' (1982) and ''To Save the Kakapo'' (1997). \n\n[[File:Kakapo Sirocco 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] on Maud Island]]\nThe BBC's Natural History Unit also featured the kakapo, including a sequence with [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]] in ''[[The Life of Birds]]''. It was also one of the endangered animals [[Douglas Adams]] and [[Mark Carwardine]] set out to find for the radio series and book ''[[Last Chance to See]]''. An updated version of the series has been produced for BBC TV, in which [[Stephen Fry]] and Carwardine revisit the animals to see how they are getting on almost 20&nbsp;years later, and in January 2009, they spent time filming the kakapo on Codfish Island.<ref name=LCTSee-2009/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/national/38869/fry-making-kakapo-doco |title=Fry making kakapo doco |last=McNeilly |first=Hamish |date=10 January 2009 |publisher=Otago Daily Times |accessdate=9 January 2009}}</ref> Footage of a kakapo named [[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] attempting to mate with Carwardine's head was viewed by millions worldwide, leading to Sirocco becoming \"spokes-bird\" for New Zealand wildlife conservation in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Starmer-Smith|first=Charles |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/7128042/Parrot-that-tried-to-mate-with-Mark-Carwardine-is-given-a-government-role.html |title=Parrot that tried to mate with Mark Carwardine is given a government role |work=The Telegraph |date=1 February 2010 |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> Sirocco became the inspiration for a popular animated emoji frequently associated with the workflow application Slack. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2017/07/13/cult-of-the-party-parrot-slack-reddit-meme/|title=Cult of the party parrot: How a ridiculous bird became an emoji hero|last=Beckman|first=Brittany Levine|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref> \n\nThe kakapo was featured in the episode \"Strange Islands\" of the documentary series ''[[South Pacific (TV series)|South Pacific]]'', originally aired on 13 June 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1486170 |title=Wild Pacific \u2013 Strange Evolutions |accessdate=29 March 2011 |website=IMDb}}</ref> in the episode \"Worlds Apart\" of the series ''[[The Living Planet]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The Living Planet [episode&nbsp;10] |url=http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/the-living-planet/ |website=Top Documentary Films}}</ref> and in episode&nbsp;3 of the BBC's ''New Zealand Earth's Mythical Islands''.<ref>{{cite media |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07lslq4 |title=New Zealand Earth's Mythical Islands |medium=video |publisher=BBC |location=U.K.}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2019 kakapo awareness campaign, the Kakapo Recovery Programme New Zealand National Partner, [[Meridian Energy]], ran a ''Search for a Saxophonist'' to provide suitable mood music for encouraging mating to coincide with the 2019 kakapo breeding season. The search and footage from the islands where breeding was taking place were featured on the ''One News Breakfast'' programme.<ref>{{cite media |last=One News New Zealand|title=Saxophonist wanted by DOC to get endangered k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d in breeding mood with romantic music 1 NEWS NOW |date=2019-01-28 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsogD557D5I |access-date=2019-06-27 |medium=video |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cats in New Zealand]]\n* [[Conservation in New Zealand]]\n{{Portal bar|Birds|Animals|Biology|New Zealand}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ballance, Alison |title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d: Rescued from the brink of extinction |publisher=Craig Potton Publishing |location=Nelson |orig-year=2010 |edition=2nd |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-877517-27-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Butler |first=David |year=1989 |title=Quest for the kakapo |location=Auckland | publisher=Heinemann Reed |isbn=978-0-7900-0065-7}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Climo |first1=Gideon |last2=Ballance |first2=Alison |year=1997 |title=Hoki: The story of a kakapo |location=Auckland |publisher=Godwit |isbn=978-1-86962-009-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jones |first=Jenny |year=2003 |title=The kakapo |location=Auckland |isbn=978-1-86948-662-4 |publisher=Reed}}\n* {{Cite journal |title=Saving kakapo: An illustrated history |year=2006 |first1=Murray |last1=Williams |first2=Don |last2=Merton |authorlink2=Don Merton |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_i.pdf}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Eulenpapagei oder Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') |editor=Steinig, G\u00fcnther |magazine=Brehms Exotische Vogelwelt |publisher=Safari |location=Berlin |date=Feb 1963 |pages=62\u201371 |quote=Die Darstellung folgt vor allem Beobachtungen fr\u00fchen Erforschern Neuseelands, wie Julius Haast, Georg Grey und Lyall.}}\n* {{cite magazine |author=Rearden, Jim |title=Die letzten Tage des Kakapo |magazine=[[GEO (Zeitschrift)|Geo-Magazin.]] |location=Hamburg |date=Feb 1978 |pages=88\u2013102 |quote=\u00fcber die Erhaltungsbem\u00fchungen in Fiordland |ISSN=0342-8311}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Vom Leben eines totgesagten Vogels |magazine=Geo-Magazin. |location=Hamburg |date=Oct 2006 |pages=176\u2013180 |ISSN=0342-8311}}\n* {{cite book |chapter=Eulenpapagei. Brummend balzt das letzte M\u00e4nnchen |editor1=Schreiber, R.L. |editor2=Diamond, A.W. |editor3=Stern, H. |editor4=Thielcke, G. |title=Rettet die Vogelwelt |publisher=O. Maier |location=Ravensburg |year=1987 |pages=198\u2013201 |isbn=3-473-46160-1}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Douglas |last1=Adams |authorlink1=Douglas Adams |first2=Mark |last2=Carwardine |authorlink2=Mark Carwardine |title=Last Chance to See |publisher=Pan Books |year=1990 |isbn=978-0-345-37198-0 |title-link=Last Chance to See}}\n* {{cite journal |author1-link=Don Merton |first1=Don V. |last1=Merton |first2=Rodney B. |last2=Morris |first3=Ian A.E. |last3=Atkinson |title=Lek behaviour in a parrot: The kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' of New Zealand |journal=Ibis |location=Oxford |volume=126 |year=1984 |issn=0019-1019}}\n* {{cite book |first1=David |last1=Cemmick |first2=Dick |last2=Veitch |title=Kakapo Country: The story of the world's most unusual bird |others=Foreword by David Bellamy. Photos by D. Cemmick |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |location=Auckland |year=1987 |isbn=0-340-41647-5}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Rod |last1=Morris |first2=Hal |last2=Smith |title=Wild South. Saving New Zealand's endangered birds |publisher=TVNZ and Century Hutchinson |location=Auckland |year=1988 |isbn=1-86941-043-2}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Philip |last1=Temple |first2=Chris |last2=Gaskin |title=The Story of the kakapo. Parrot of the Night. |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |location=Auckland |year=1988 |quote=Prizewinner: Children's Picture Book of the Year Award 1990 |isbn=0-340-51967-3}}\n* {{cite book |first=Ralph |last=Powlesland |title=Kakapo Recovery Plan 1989\u20131994 |publisher=Department of Conservation (DOC) |location=Wellington |year=1989 |isbn=0-478-01114-8}}\n* {{cite journal |author1=Powlesland, R.G. |author2=Roberts, A. |author3=Lloyd, B.D. |author4-link=Don Merton |author4=Merton, D. |url=http://www.rsnz.org/publish/nzjz/1995/69.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040922044514/http://www.rsnz.org/publish/nzjz/1995/69.pdf |archive-date=2004-09-22 |df=dmy-all |via=rsnz.org |title=Number, fate, and distribution of Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') found on Stewart Island, New Zealand 1979\u20131992 |journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology |volume=22 |issue=3 |year=1995 |pages=239\u2013248 |issn=0301-4223|doi=10.1080/03014223.1995.9518039 }}\n* {{cite book |first=Mary |last=Cresswell |department=Kakapo Management Group |url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz//then/recoveryplan.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071110154242/http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz//then/recoveryplan.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-11-10 |via=kakaporecovery.org.nz |title=Kakapo Recovery Plan 1996\u20132005 |series=Threatened Species Recovery Plan |id=No. 21. |publisher=Department of Conservation (DoC) |location=Wellington |year=1996 |isbn=0-478-01773-1}}\n* {{cite book |author-link=Don Merton |first=Don |last=Merton |article=Kakapo |editor-first=P.J. |editor-last=Higgins |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand, and Antarctic Birds |id=Bd 4. RAOU. |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Melbourne |year=1999 |pages=633\u2013646 |isbn=0-19-553071-3}}\n* {{cite magazine |first=Tim |last=Higham |date=July\u2013September 1992 |title=The kakapo of Codfish Island |magazine=New Zealand Geographic |volume=15 |pages=30\u201338 |ISSN=0113-9967}}\n* {{cite magazine |first=Derek |last=Grzelewski |title=Kakapo: Bird on the brink |url=http://www.nzgeographic.co.nz/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060720125029/http://www.nzgeographic.co.nz/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-07-20 |magazine=New Zealand Geographic Magazine |publisher=Ohakune |volume=56 |date=March\u2013April 2002 |ISSN=0113-9967}}\n* {{cite book |first=Gerard |last=Hutching |title=Back from the Brink: The fight to save our endangered birds |publisher=Penguin Books |location=Auckland |year=2004 |isbn=0-14-301948-1}}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/celebration-kakapo-progress-conservation-enigmatic-parrot |title=A celebration of kakapo |journal=Notornis |publisher=Ornithological Society of New Zealand |location=Wellington, NZ |volume=53 |issue=Special |date=Jan 2006 |issn=0029-4470}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons+cat|Strigops habroptila|Strigops habroptila}}\n{{Wikispecies|Strigops habroptila|Kakapo}}\n* [http://www.parrots.org/index.php/encyclopedia/profile/kakapo/ World Parrot Trust] Parrot Encyclopedia \u2013 Species Profiles\n* [http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/ Kakapo Recovery]\n* [http://www.terranature.org/kakapo.htm TerraNature page on Kakapo]\n* [http://www.doc.govt.nz/kakapo/ New Zealand Department of Conservation Kakapo Page]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/4485295.stm Rare parrot receives special care] \u2013 article from [[BBC]] News\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160917114144/http://www.wildlifeextra.com/go/news/kakapo-breeding090.html Start of the Breeding season 2009]\n* [[ARKive]] \u2013 [https://web.archive.org/web/20060409092036/http://www.arkive.org/species/GES/birds/Strigops_habroptilus/ images and movies of the kakapo]\n* [http://www.stuff.co.nz/stuff/4612100a7693.html Kakapo in successful return journey] (Archived by WebCite at https://www.webcitation.org/5ZBDZlnw3)\n* [http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/saving-kakapo-illustrated-history ''Saving Kakapo: an illustrated history'' by Murray Williams and [[Don Merton]], in: 'Notornis (Journal), vol. 53/1, 2006'] Abstract provided by the Ornithological Society of New Zealand.\n* BBC Wildlife Finder [https://web.archive.org/web/20090930080400/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/species/Kakapo News stories, and clips from the BBC archive]\n* [http://www.radiolive.co.nz/Environews-Kakapo-Alison-Balance--Don-Merton/tabid/506/articleID/17307/Default.aspx Interview with NZ conservationists Alison Ballance and the late Don Merton]\n* [http://channel.tepapa.govt.nz/video/mission-kakapo-copulation/ Mission K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Copulation] \u2013 a video on the [http://channel.tepapa.govt.nz Te Papa Channel]\n* [http://nzbirdsonline.org.nz/species/kakapo Kakapo information on NZ Birds Online]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090930080400/http://www.bbc.co.uk/nature/species/Kakapo Video footage from the BBC] including ''[[Last Chance to See (TV series)|Last Chance to See]]'' and ''[[Wild Down Under]]''\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5v5ViXUeofA Kakapo- Video from April 2003, with footage of Richard-Henry (Kakapo) and Chalky Island, from YouTube]\n* \"Birds of New Zealand \u2013 A Rare View\" by Rob Morris & Rod Hayden. About 3 Birds: Takahe, Kakapo, Black Robin. Wild South/Natural History Series. TV NZ Enterprises, Auckland /Dunedin 1990. 98 minutes (Kakapo footage from 1982; with rare pictures of Fiordland and Stewart Island)\n* \"To Save the kakapo\" by Alison Ballance. Wild South Videos, Natural History New Zealand Ltd. Dunedin 1998. (60 minutes, during the 1997 breeding season on Codfish Island)\n\n{{Strigopidae}}\n{{Birds}}\n{{Birds of New Zealand}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q179959}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Birds described in 1845]]\n[[Category:Birds of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Flightless birds]]\n[[Category:Herbivorous vertebrates]]\n[[Category:M\u0101ori culture]]\n[[Category:Parrots of Oceania]]\n[[Category:Strigopidae]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by George Robert Gray]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A large flightless nocturnal parrot endemic to New Zealand }}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{engvarB|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| name = Kakapo\n| image = Sirocco full length portrait.jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1\n| image_caption = A male named [[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] on [[Maud Island]]\n| status = CR\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref =<ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22685245/0 |title=''Strigops habroptila'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2013 |accessdate=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| status2 = NC\n| status2_system = NZTCS\n| status2_ref = <ref name=\"NZTCS\"/>\n| genus = Strigops\n| parent_authority = [[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1845\n| species = habroptilus\n| authority = [[George Robert Gray|G.R. Gray]], 1845\n| synonyms = ''Strigops habroptila''\n}}\n\nThe '''kakapo''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|p|o\u028a}} {{respell|KAH|k\u0259|poh}}, {{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|k|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259|\u02c8|p|o\u028a}} {{respell|-|POH}}; from {{lang-mi|k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d||night parrot}}), also called '''owl parrot''' (''Strigops habroptilus''), is a species of large, [[Flightless bird|flightless]], [[Nocturnal animal|nocturnal]], ground-dwelling parrot of the super-family [[New Zealand parrot|Strigopoidea]], [[Endemism in birds|endemic]] to [[New Zealand]].<ref name=\"Best1984\">{{cite journal|first=H. A. |last=Best| title=The foods of kakapo on Stewart Island as determined from their feeding sign| journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology|year=1984| volume=7| pages=71\u201383| url=http://newzealandecology.org/nzje/1599.pdf|accessdate=15 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt has finely blotched yellow-green plumage, a distinct facial disc, a large grey beak, short legs, large feet, and relatively short wings and tail. A combination of traits make it unique among its kind; it is the world's only flightless [[parrot]], the heaviest parrot, nocturnal, herbivorous, visibly [[sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]] in body size, has a low [[basal metabolic rate]] and no male parental care, and is the only parrot to have a [[Polygyny in animals|polygynous]] [[Lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system. It is also possibly one of the world's longest-living birds.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\">{{cite journal |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |year=2006 |first1=Ralph G. |last1=Powlesland |first2=Don V. |last2=Merton |authorlink2=Don Merton |first3=John F. |last3=Cockrem| pages=3\u201326 |title=A parrot apart: the natural history of the kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus''), and the context of its conservation management |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_3.pdf}}</ref>\n\nIts anatomy typifies the tendency of bird evolution on oceanic islands, with few predators and abundant food: a generally robust physique at the expense of flight abilities, resulting in reduced wing muscles and a diminished [[Keel (bird)|keel]] on the [[sternum]]. Like many other New Zealand bird species, the kakapo was historically important to  [[M\u0101ori people|M\u0101ori]], the indigenous people of New Zealand, appearing in many of their traditional legends and folklore; however it was also heavily hunted and used as a resource by M\u0101ori, both for its meat as a food source and for its feathers, which were used to make highly valued pieces of clothing. Kakapo were also occasionally kept as pets.\n\nThe kakapo is critically endangered; the total known adult population is {{Number_of_Living_Kakapo}}<!-- see link on talk page for editing this number --> [[List of kakapo|living individuals]], all of which are named and tagged, confined to four small islands off the coast of New Zealand that have been cleared of predators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/12/26/world/kakapo-conservation-scn-c2e-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Can tech save New Zealand's 'gorgeous, hilarious' parrot?|first=Sarah |last=Lazarus|website=CNN|access-date=2019-12-26}}</ref> The [[Invasive species in New Zealand|introduction of predators]] such as cats, rats, ferrets, and stoats during British colonisation  almost wiped out the kakapo. Conservation efforts began in the 1890s, but they were not very successful until the implementation of the Kakapo Recovery Programme in 1995.\n\nMost kakapo are kept on two predator-free islands, [[Codfish Island|Codfish / Whenua Hou]] and [[Anchor Island|Anchor]], where they are closely monitored, and [[Little Barrier Island|Little Barrier / Hauturu Island]] is being trialled as a third home for the species.\n\n==Taxonomy, systematics and naming==\n[[File:Kakapo2.jpg|thumb|left|Illustration of a kakapo from the book ''A History of the Birds of New Zealand'' by Walter Lawry Buller, published in 1873.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzbirds.com/birds/kakapo.html |title=New Zealand Birds &#124; Birds &#124; Gallery &#124; Kakapo, ''Strigops habroptilus'' |publisher=Nzbirds.com |date=9 October 2010 |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref>]]\nThe common English name \"kakapo\" comes from the [[M\u0101ori language|M\u0101ori]] \"k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d\", from ''k\u0101k\u0101'' (\"parrot\") + ''p\u014d'' (\"night\"); the name is both singular and plural. \"K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d\" is increasingly written in New Zealand English with the [[Macron (diacritic)|macrons]] that indicate long vowels.\n\nThe kakapo was originally described by English [[Ornithology|ornithologist]] [[George Robert Gray]] in 1845 and named ''Strigops habroptilus''.<ref group=lower-alpha>Some sources give the kakapo's Latin name as ''Strigops habroptila'', from the belief that the word ''Strigops'' is feminine, and the species name is required to agree in gender; neither of which is true \u2013 ''Strigops'' is a masculine compound, and ''habroptilus'' is a noun in apposition, not an adjective. ''S. habroptilus'' is the most common form used in the scientific literature.</ref> Its generic name ''Strigops'' is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''strix'', genitive ''strigos'' \"owl\", and ''ops'' \"face\", while its specific [[epithet]] ''habroptilus'' comes from ''habros'' \"soft\", and ''ptilon'' \"feather\".<ref name=\"Liddell1980\">{{Cite book| authorlink1 = Henry George Liddell | last1=Liddell | first1=Henry George | authorlink2=Robert Scott (philologist) | first2=Robert | last2=Scott | year = 1980 | title = A Greek-English Lexicon (Abridged Edition) | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = United Kingdom | isbn =978-0-19-910207-5| title-link=A Greek-English Lexicon }}</ref>\n\nThe bird has so many unusual features that it was initially placed in its own [[tribe (biology)|tribe]], Strigopini. Recent [[phylogenetic]] studies have confirmed the unique position of this genus as well as the closeness to the [[k\u0101k\u0101]] and the [[kea]], both belonging to the New Zealand parrot genus ''Nestor''.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Rheindt|first=Frank E.|last2=Christidis|first2=Les|last3=Kuhn|first3=Sylvia|last4=de Kloet|first4=Siwo|last5=Norman|first5=Janette A.|last6=Fidler|first6=Andrew|date=2013|title=The timing of diversification within the most divergent parrot clade|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|language=en|volume=45|issue=2|pages=140\u2013148|doi=10.1111/j.1600-048x.2013.00200.x|issn=0908-8857}}</ref> Together, they are now considered a separate superfamily within the parrots, Strigopoidea, the most basal of all living parrots.<ref name=\"revision\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2012/f/z03205p040f.pdf|author=Joseph, Leo|year=2012|title= A revised nomenclature and classification for family-group taxa of parrots (Psittaciformes)|journal= Zootaxa|volume= 3205|pages= 26\u201340|display-authors=etal|doi=10.11646/zootaxa.3205.1.2}}</ref>\n\nWithin the Strigopoidea, the kakapo is placed in its own [[family (biology)|family]], Strigopidae. The common ancestor of the kakapo and the genus ''[[Nestor (genus)|Nestor]]'' became isolated from the remaining parrot species when New Zealand broke off from [[Gondwana]], around 82 million years ago. Around 30&nbsp;million years ago, the kakapo diverged from the genus ''Nestor''.<ref name=\"Wright\">{{cite journal|title=A Multilocus Molecular Phylogeny of the Parrots (Psittaciformes): Support for a Gondwanan Origin during the Cretaceous|journal=Mol Biol Evol|year=2008|first=T. F. |last=Wright|last2=Schirtzinger |first2=E. E. |last3=Matsumoto |first3=T. |last4=Eberhard |first4=J. R. |last5=Graves |first5=G. R. |last6=Sanchez |first6=J. J. |last7=Capelli |first7=S. |last8=Muller |first8=H. |last9=Scharpegge |first9=J. |last10=Chambers |first10=G. K. |last11=Fleischer |first11=R. C.|volume=25|issue=10|pages=2141\u20132156|doi= 10.1093/molbev/msn160|url=|accessdate=|pmid=18653733|pmc=2727385 }}</ref><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarlier ornithologists felt that the kakapo might be related to the [[Pezoporus|ground parrots]] and [[night parrot]] of Australia due to their similar colouration, but this is contradicted by recent studies;<ref>[[Richard Schodde|Schodde, R.]] & [[Ian J. Mason|Mason, I.J.]] (1981). Nocturnal Birds of Australia. Illustrated by Jeremy Boot. Melbourne: Lansdowne Edns 136 pp. 22 pls [35\u201336]</ref> rather, the [[crypsis|cryptic]] colour seems to be [[adaptation]] to terrestrial habits that evolved twice [[convergent evolution|convergently]].<ref name=Leeton>{{cite journal | last1 = Leeton | first1 = P.R.J. | last2 = Christidis | first2 = L. | last3 = Westerman | first3 = M. | last4 = Boles | first4 = W.E. | year = 1994 | title = Molecular phylogenetic relationships of the Night Parrot (''Geopsittacus occidentalis'') and the Ground Parrot (''Pezoporus wallicus'') | url = http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v111n04/p0833-p0843.pdf | journal = [[Auk (journal)|Auk]] | volume = 111 | issue = 4| pages = 833\u2013843 | doi = 10.2307/4088815 | jstor = 4088815 }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus 1-1c.jpg|thumb|A year-old kakapo on [[Codfish Island]].]]\nThe kakapo is a large, rotund parrot. Adults can measure from {{convert|58|to|64|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length, and weight can vary from {{convert|0.95|to|4|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} at maturity.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\">{{Cite book|last=Higgins |first=P. J.| year=1999| title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Volume 4: Parrots to Dollarbird| publisher=Oxford University Press| location=Melbourne| isbn=978-0-19-553071-1|title-link=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Cameron |first=M. |year=2012 |title=Parrots: The animal answer guide |url=https://archive.org/details/parrotsanimalans0000came |url-access=registration |publisher=JHU Press}}</ref> Males are larger than females. Twenty-eight males were found to average {{convert|2|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in one study, and 39 males were found to average {{convert|2.06|kg|lb|abbr=on}} in another. In the same studies, 28 females were found to average {{convert|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and 18 females were found to average {{convert|1.28|kg|lb|abbr=on}}, respectively.<ref name=\"CRC\">''CRC Handbook of Avian Body Masses, 2nd Edition'' by John B. Dunning Jr. (Editor). CRC Press (2008), {{ISBN|978-1-4200-6444-5}}.</ref><ref name=\"Merton1984\">{{Cite journal |last1=Merton |first1=D. V. | authorlink1=Don Merton| last2=Morris |first2=R. B. |last3=Atkinson |first3=I. A. |date=1984 |title=Lek behaviour in a parrot: the kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' of New Zealand. |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=126 |issue=3 |pages=277\u2013283 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1984.tb00250.x}}</ref> Kakapo are the heaviest living species of parrot and on average weigh about {{convert|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} more than the largest flying parrot, the [[hyacinth macaw]].<ref name = \"CRC\"/>\n\nThe kakapo cannot fly, having relatively short wings for its size and lacking the [[Keel (bird anatomy)|keel]] on the [[sternum]] (breastbone), where the flight muscles of other birds attach.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> It uses its wings for balance and to break its fall when leaping from trees. Unlike many other land birds, the kakapo can accumulate large amounts of body fat.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nThe upper parts of the kakapo have yellowish moss-green feathers barred or mottled with black or dark brownish grey, blending well with native vegetation. Individuals may have strongly varying degrees of mottling and colour tone and intensity \u2013 museum specimens show that some birds had completely yellow colouring. The breast and flank are yellowish-green streaked with yellow. The belly, undertail, neck, and face are predominantly yellowish streaked with pale green and weakly mottled with brownish-grey. Because the feathers do not need the strength and stiffness required for flight, they are exceptionally soft, giving rise to the [[specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''habroptilus''. The kakapo has a conspicuous facial disc of fine feathers resembling the face of an owl; thus, early European settlers called it the \"owl parrot\". The beak is surrounded by delicate feathers which resemble [[whiskers|vibrissae]] or \"whiskers\"; it is possible kakapo use these to sense the ground as they walk with its head lowered, but there is no evidence for this. The mandible is variable in colour, mostly ivory, with the upper part often bluish-grey. The eyes are dark brown. Kakapo feet are large, scaly, and, as in all parrots, [[dactyly|zygodactyl]] (two toes face forward and two backward). The pronounced claws are particularly useful for climbing. The ends of the tail feathers often become worn from being continually dragged on the ground.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n[[File:K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d head.jpg|thumb|left|The \"whiskers\" around the beak.]]\nFemales are easily distinguished from males as they have a narrower and less domed head, narrower and proportionally longer beak, smaller [[Beak#Cere|cere]] and [[Beak#Nares|nostrils]], more slender and pinkish grey legs and feet, and proportionally longer tail. While their plumage colour is not very different from that of the male, the toning is more subtle, with less yellow and mottling. Nesting females also have a [[brood patch]] of bare skin on the belly.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nThe kakapo's [[Altriciality|altricial]] young are first covered with greyish white down, through which their pink skin can be easily seen. They become fully feathered at approximately 70 days old. Juvenile individuals tend to have duller green colouration, more uniform black barring, and less yellow present in their feathers. They are additionally distinguishable because of their shorter tails, wings, and beaks. At this stage, they have a ring of short feathers surrounding their irises that resemble eyelashes.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" />\n\nLike many other parrots, kakapo have a variety of calls. As well as the ''booms'' (see [[Kakapo#Media|below]] for a recording) and ''chings'' of their mating calls, they will often loudly ''skraark''.<ref name=\"CloseUp\"/>\n\nThe kakapo has a well-developed [[Olfaction|sense of smell]], which complements its nocturnal lifestyle.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\">{{Cite journal\n| last1 = Hagelin | first1 = Julie C.\n| doi = 10.1111/j.1474-919X.2004.00212.x\n| title = Observations on the olfactory ability of the kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'', the critically endangered parrot of New Zealand\n| journal = [[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]]\n| volume = 146\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 161\u2013164\n|date=January 2004\n}}</ref> It can distinguish between odours while foraging, a behaviour reported in only one other parrot species.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\"/> The kakapo has a large olfactory bulb ratio (longest diameter of the olfactory bulb/longest diameter of the brain) indicating that it does, indeed, have a more developed sense of smell than other parrots.<ref name=\"Hagelin04\" /> One of the most striking characteristics of the kakapo is its distinct musty-sweet odour.<ref name=\"CloseUp\">{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/up-close-and-personal/|title=Up Close & Personal|publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> The smell often alerts predators to the presence of kakapo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wildinfo.net/facts/Kakapo.asp?page=/facts/Kakapo.asp|title=Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'')|publisher=Wild Magazine}}</ref>\n\nAs a nocturnal species, the kakapo has adapted its senses to living in darkness. Its [[optic tectum]], [[nucleus rotundus]], and [[Avian pallium|entopallium]] are smaller in relation to its overall brain size than those of diurnal parrots. Its retina shares some qualities with that of other nocturnal birds but also has some qualities typical of diurnal birds, lending to best function around twilight. These modifications allow the kakapo to have enhanced light sensitivity but with poor visual acuity.<ref>{{cite journal\n| last1=Corfield | first1=J. R.\n| last2=Gsell | first2=A. C.\n| last3=Brunton | first3=D.\n| last4=Heesy | first4=C. P.\n| last5=Hall | first5=M. I.\n| last6=Acosta | first6=M. L.\n| last7=Iwaniuk | first7=A. N.\n| year=2011\n| title=Anatomical Specializations for Nocturnality in a Critically Endangered Parrot, the Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'')\n| journal=PLoS ONE\n| volume=6\n| issue=8\n| page=e22945\n| doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0022945\n| pmid=21860663\n| pmc=3157909\n}}</ref>\n\n===Internal anatomy===\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus (AM LB299).jpg|thumb|upright|Skeleton]] \nThe skeleton of the kakapo differs from other parrots in several features associated with flightlessness. Firstly, it has the smallest relative wing size of any parrot. Its wing feathers are shorter, more rounded, less asymmetrical, and have fewer distal barbules to lock the feathers together. The sternum is small and has a low, [[vestigial]] keel and a shortened [[spina externa]]. As in other flightless birds and some flighted parrots, the [[furcula]] is not fused but consists of a pair of [[clavicles]] lying in contact with each [[coracoid]]. As in other flightless birds, the angle between the coracoid and sternum is enlarged. The kakapo has a larger pelvis than other parrots. The proximal bones of the leg and arm are disproportionately long and the distal elements are disproportionately short.<ref name=\"Livezey1992\">{{Cite journal\n| last1 = Livezey | first1 = Bradley C.\n| doi = 10.1002/jmor.1052130108\n| pmid = 29865598\n| title = Morphological corollaries and ecological implications of flightlessness in the kakapo (Psittaciformes: ''Strigops habroptilus'')\n| journal = Journal of Morphology\n| volume = 213\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 105\u2013145\n|date=July 1992\n}}</ref>\n\nThe [[pectoralis major muscle|pectoral]] musculature of the kakapo is also modified by flightlessness. The [[pectoralis major muscle|pectoralis]] and [[supracoracoideus]] muscles are greatly reduced. The [[propatagialis tendo longus]] has no distinct muscle belly. The [[sternocoracoideus]] is tendinous. There is an extensive [[cucularis capitis clavicularis]] muscle that is associated with the large crop.<ref name=\"Livezey1992\"/>\n\n===Genetics===\nBecause kakapo passed through a [[Population_bottleneck|genetic bottleneck]], in which the world population was reduced to 49 birds, they are extremely inbred and have low genetic diversity. This manifests in lower disease resistance and fertility problems: 40% of kakapo eggs are infertile.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=White|first=Rebekah|date=Sep\u2013Oct 2016|title=Decoding K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d|url=https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/decoding-kakapo/|journal=New Zealand Geographic|volume=141|pages=|via=}}</ref> Beginning in 2015, the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d 125 project aimed to sequence the [[genome]] of all living kakapo, as well as some museum specimens \u2013 the first time an entire species has had its genome sequenced.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/science/77878783/kakapo-to-have-genomes-sequenced-in-a-world-first-for-science|title=Kakapo to have genomes sequenced in a world first for science|last=Thomas|first=Rachel|date=14 March 2016|work=Stuff|access-date=5 December 2018}}</ref> The project is a collaboration between [[Duke University]] and the New Zealand Genomics lab in [[Dunedin]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Habitat ==\nBefore the arrival of humans, the kakapo was distributed throughout both main islands of New Zealand. Although it may have inhabited [[Stewart Island]] before human arrival, it has so far not been found in the extensive fossil collections from there.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wood|first=Jamie R.|date=2016|title=Spatial distribution of late Holocene bird bones in the Mason Bay dune system, Stewart Island, New Zealand|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand|language=en|volume=46|issue=2|pages=103\u2013116|doi=10.1080/03036758.2016.1149497|issn=0303-6758}}</ref> Kakapo lived in a variety of habitats, including [[tussock grass|tussocklands]], scrublands and coastal areas. It also inhabited [[forest]]s dominated by [[Podocarpaceae|podocarps]] ([[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]], [[Prumnopitys taxifolia|matai]], [[Dacrycarpus dacrydioides|kahikatea]], [[Podocarpus totara|totara]]), [[Nothofagus|beeches]], [[tawa (tree)|tawa]], and [[Metrosideros umbellata|rata]]. In [[Fiordland]], areas of avalanche and slip debris with regenerating and heavily fruiting vegetation \u2013 such as five finger, [[Aristotelia serrata|wineberry]], [[bush lawyer (plant)|bush lawyer]], [[tutu (plant)|tutu]], [[hebe (plant)|hebes]], and [[coprosma]]s \u2013 became known as \"kakapo gardens\".<ref>{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=P. N.|date=1975|title=Vegetation associated with kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'' Gray) in Sinbad Gully, Fiordland, New Zealand|journal=New Zealand Journal of Botany|volume=14|issue=2|pages=151\u2013159|doi=10.1080/0028825x.1976.10428889}}</ref>\n\nThe kakapo is considered to be a \"habitat generalist\".<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> Though they are now confined to islands free of predation, they were once able to live in nearly any climate present on the islands of New Zealand. They survived dry, hot summers on the North Island as well as cold winter temperatures in the sub-alpine areas of Fiordland. Kakapo seem to have preferred broadleaf or [[Nothofagus solandri var. cliffortioides|mountain beech]] and [[Podocarpus laetus|Hall's t\u014dtara]] forest with mild winters and high rainfall,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lentini|first=Pia E.|last2=Stirnemann|first2=Ingrid A.|last3=Stojanovic|first3=Dejan|last4=Worthy|first4=Trevor H.|last5=Stein|first5=John A.|date=2018|title=Using fossil records to inform reintroduction of the kakapo as a refugee species|journal=Biological Conservation|volume=217|pages=157\u2013165|doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2017.10.027|issn=0006-3207}}</ref> but the species was not exclusively forest-dwelling. All kakapo that were transferred to predator-free islands in the last decades have adapted well to any changes in environment and food plants.\n\n==Ecology and behaviour==\n[[File:Kakapohist.svg|thumb|250px|Historic distribution of the kakapo.\n{{legend|#44a844|Maximum distribution since 1840}}\n{{legend|#ced362|Fossil evidence}}]]\nIt seems that the kakapo \u2013 like many of New Zealand's bird species \u2013 has [[evolution|evolved]] to occupy an [[ecological niche]] normally filled by various species of mammal (the only non-marine mammals native to New Zealand are [[List of mammals of New Zealand#Order: Chiroptera (bats)|three species of small bats]]).\n\nThe kakapo is primarily nocturnal; it roosts under cover in trees or on the ground during the day and moves around its territories at night.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/>\n\nThough the kakapo cannot fly, it is an excellent climber, ascending to the crowns of the tallest trees. It can also \"parachute\" \u2013 descending by leaping and spreading its wings. In this way it may travel a few metres at an angle of less than 45 degrees.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> With only 3.3% of its mass made up of pectoral muscle, it is no surprise that the kakapo cannot use its wings to lift its heavy body off the ground. Because of its flightlessness, it has very low metabolic demands in comparison to flighted birds. It is able to survive easily on very little or on very low quality food sources. Unlike most other bird species, the kakapo is entirely herbivorous, feeding on fruits, seeds, leaves, stems, and rhizomes. When foraging, kakapo tend to leave crescent-shaped wads of fiber in the vegetation behind them, called \"browse signs\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHaving lost the ability to fly, it has developed strong legs. [[Animal locomotion|Locomotion]] is often by way of a rapid \"jog-like\" gait by which it can move several kilometres.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/> A female has been observed making two return trips each night during nesting from her nest to a food source up to {{convert|1|km|mi|1|abbr=on}} away<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Powlesland |first1=R.G. |last2=Lloyd |first2=B.D. |last3=Best |first3=H.A. |last4=Merton |first4=D.V. |authorlink4=Don Merton |title=Breeding Biology of the kakapo ''Strigops-Habroptilus'' on Stewart Island, New Zealand |journal=[[Ibis (journal)|Ibis]] |volume=134 |issue=4 |pages=361\u2013373 |date=1992 |doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1992.tb08016.x}}</ref> and the male may walk from its home range to a mating arena up to {{convert|5|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} away during the mating season (October\u2013January).<ref name=\"Best1985\">{{cite book |first1=H.A. |last1=Best |first2=R.G. |last2=Powlesland |year=1985 |title=Kakapo |publisher=John McIndoe and New Zealand Wildlife Service |location=Dunedin}}</ref>\n[[File:Kakapo Trevor feeding on poroporo fruit.jpg|thumb|left|Individual nicknamed Trevor feeding on [[poroporo]] fruits, Maud Island]] \nYoung birds indulge in play fighting, and one bird will often lock the neck of another under its chin.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=Judy |last1=Diamond |first2=Daryl |last2=Eason |first3=Clio |last3=Reid |first4=Alan B. |last4=Bond|year=2006|journal=Behaviour |volume=143 |pages=1397\u20131423 |title=Social play in kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') with comparisons to kea (Nestor notabilis) and kaka (Nestor meridionalis) |doi=10.1163/156853906778987551 |issue=11 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1031&context=bioscibehavior}}</ref> The kakapo is curious by nature and has been known to interact with humans. Conservation staff and volunteers have engaged extensively with some kakapo, which have distinct personalities.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/behaviour/ |title=Behaviour |accessdate=6 March 2014 |publisher=Kakapo Recovery}}</ref> While they are curious toward humans, kakapo are not social birds.\n\nThe kakapo was a very successful species in pre-human New Zealand, and was well adapted to avoid the birds of prey which were their only predators. As well as the [[New Zealand falcon]], there were two other birds of prey in pre-human New Zealand: [[Haast's eagle]] and [[Eyles' harrier]].<ref name=\"GOG\"/> All these [[Bird of prey|raptors]] soared overhead searching for prey in daylight, and to avoid them the kakapo evolved camouflaged plumage and became nocturnal. When a kakapo feels threatened, it freezes, so that it is more effectively camouflaged in the vegetation its plumage resembles. Kakapo were not entirely safe at night, when the [[laughing owl]] was active, and it is apparent from owl nest deposits on Canterbury limestone cliffs that kakapo were among their prey.<ref name=\"LWOTM\">{{Cite book|title=The Lost world of the Moa: Prehistoric life in New Zealand|last1=Worthy|first1=T. H.|last2=Holdaway|first2=R. N.|publisher=Canterbury University Press|year=2002|location=Christchurch|page=718}}</ref>\n\nKakapo defensive adaptations were no use, however, against the mammalian predators introduced to New Zealand by humans. Birds hunt very differently from mammals, relying on their powerful vision to find prey, and thus they usually hunt by day.<ref name=\"GOG\" /> Mammalian predators, in contrast to birds, often hunt by night, and rely on their sense of smell and hearing to find prey; a common way for humans to hunt kakapo was by releasing trained dogs.<ref>{{cite book |title=The habits of flightless birds of New Zealand: with notes on other flightless New Zealand birds |last=Henry |first=R. |publisher=Government Printer |year=1903 |location=Wellington}}</ref><ref name=\"GOG\" /> The kakapo's adaptations to avoid avian predation have thus been useless against its new enemies, and the reason for its massive decline since the introduction of dogs, cats and [[Mustelidae|mustelids]] (see ''[[Kakapo#Human impact|Conservation: Human impact]]''). \n[[File:051226-kakapo-billbooming.ogg|thumb|The sound of a kakapo booming]]\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Kakapo egg hatching.jpg|thumb|left|Hatching kakapo egg]] \nThe kakapo is the only extant species of flightless parrot in the world,<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> and the only flightless bird that has a [[lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\">{{cite book |title=Collins Field Guide to New Zealand Wildlife |first1=Terrence |last1=Lindsey |first2=Rod |last2=Morris |publisher=HarperCollins New Zealand |year=2000 |isbn=978-1-86950-300-0}}</ref> Males loosely gather in an arena and compete with each other to attract females. Females listen to the males as they display, or \"lek\".<ref name=\"Merton77\">{{cite book |author-link=Don Merton |author=Merton, D.V. |year=1976 |chapter=Conservation of the kakapo: A progress report. |title=Proc. Science in Nat. Parks. |publisher=National Parks Authority |location=Wellington, N.Z. |series=National Parks Series |volume=6 |pages=139\u2013148}}</ref> They choose a mate based on the quality of his display; they are not pursued by the males in any overt way. No pair bond is formed; males and females meet only to mate.\n\nDuring the courting season, males leave their home ranges for hilltops and ridges where they establish their own mating courts. These leks can be up to {{convert|5|km|mi|0}} from a kakapo's usual territory and are an average of {{Convert|50|m|ft|-1}} apart within the lek arena. Males remain in the region of their court throughout the courting season. At the start of the breeding season, males will fight to try to secure the best courts. They confront each other with raised feathers, spread wings, open beaks, raised claws and loud screeching and growling. Fighting may leave birds with injuries or even kill them.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1017/S0959270900001933 |last1=Clout |first1=M. N. |last2=Merton |first2=D. V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |date=1998 |title=Saving the kakapo: The conservation of the world's most peculiar parrot |journal=Bird Conservation International |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=281\u2013295}}</ref> Mating occurs only approximately every five years, with the ripening of the rimu fruit. In mating years, males making \"booming\" calls for 6\u20138&nbsp;hours every night for more than four months.\n\nEach court consists of one or more saucer-shaped depressions or \"bowls\" dug in the ground by the male, up to {{Convert|10|cm|in|0}} deep and long enough to fit the half-metre length of the bird. The kakapo is one of only a handful of birds in the world which actually constructs its leks.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\"/> Bowls are often created next to rock faces, banks, or tree trunks to help reflect sound:<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> the bowls themselves function as amplifiers to enhance the projection of the males' booming mating calls.<ref name=\"CFGNZW\"/> Each male's bowls are connected by a network of trails or tracks which may extend {{Convert|50|m|ft|-1}} along a ridge or {{Convert|20|m|ft|-1}} in diameter around a hilltop.<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> Males meticulously clear their bowls and tracks of debris. One way researchers check whether bowls are visited at night is to place a few twigs in the bowl; if the male visits overnight, he will pick them up in his beak and toss them away.\n\nTo attract females, males make loud, low-frequency (below 100&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]]) booming calls from their bowls by inflating a [[thorax|thoracic]] sac.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/><ref name=\"Cockrem2002\">{{cite journal |last=Cockrem |first=J. F. |title=Reproductive biology and conservation of the endangered kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') in New Zealand |journal=Avian and Poultry Biology Reviews |date=2002 |volume=13 |issue=3 |pages=139\u2013144 |doi=10.3184/147020602783698548}}</ref> They start with low grunts, which increase in volume as the sac inflates. After a sequence of about 20 loud booms, the male kakapo emits a high-frequency, metallic \"ching\" sound.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the kakapo: Breeding |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/breeding/ |website=Kakapo Recovery |accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref> He stands for a short while before again lowering his head, inflating his chest and starting another sequence of booms. The booms can be heard at least {{Convert|1|km|mi}} away on a still night; wind can carry the sound at least {{Convert|5|km|mi}}.<ref name=\"Merton1984\"/> Males boom for an average of eight hours a night; each male may produce thousands of booms in this time. This may continue every night for three or four months during which time the male may lose half his body weight. Each male moves around the bowls in his court so that the booms are sent out in different directions. These booms are also notorious for attracting predators, because of the long range at which they can be heard.\n\nFemales are attracted by the booms of the competing males; they too may need to walk several kilometres from their territories to the arena. Once a female enters the court of one of the males, the male performs a display in which he rocks from side to side and makes clicking noises with his beak.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> He turns his back to the female, spreads his wings in display and walks backwards towards her. He will then attempt copulation for 40 minutes or more.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite book|title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d: rescued from the brink of extinction |last=Ballance |first=Alison |publisher=Potton and Burton |year=2018 |isbn=9781877517273 |edition=2nd revised |location=Nelson, New Zealand}}</ref> Once the birds have mated, the female returns to her home territory to lay eggs and raise the chicks. The male continues booming in the hope of attracting another female.\n\n[[File:Kakapo chicks.jpg|thumb|Hatchlings]] \nThe female kakapo lays 1\u20134&nbsp;eggs per breeding cycle, with several days between eggs.<ref name=\"Cockrem2002\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> She nests on the ground under the cover of plants or in cavities such as hollow tree trunks. The female incubates the eggs faithfully, but is forced to leave them every night in search of food. Predators are known to eat the eggs, and the embryos inside can also die of cold in the mother's absence. Kakapo eggs usually hatch within 30&nbsp;days,<ref name=\"Easton2006\">{{cite journal |title=Breeding biology of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') on offshore island sanctuaries, 1990\u20132002 |last1=Eason |first1=Daryl K. |last2=Elliott |first2=Graeme P. |last3=Merton |first3=Don V. |authorlink3=Don Merton |last4=Jansen |first4=Paul W. |last5=Harper |first5=Grant A. |last6=Moorhouse |first6=Ron J. |journal=Notornis |volume=54 |issue=1 |date=2006 |pages=27\u201336 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_27.pdf}}</ref> bearing fluffy grey chicks that are quite helpless. After the eggs hatch, the female feeds the chicks for three months, and the chicks remain with the female for some months after [[fledge|fledging]].<ref name=\"Cockrem2002\"/> The young chicks are just as vulnerable to predators as the eggs, and young have been killed by many of the same predators that attack adults. Chicks leave the nest at approximately 10 to 12&nbsp;weeks of age. As they gain greater independence, their mothers may feed the chicks sporadically for up to 6&nbsp;months.\n\nBecause the kakapo is long-lived, with an average life expectancy of 60 (plus or minus 20) years, it tends to have an adolescence before it starts breeding.<ref name=\":2\" /> Males start booming at about 5&nbsp;years of age.<ref name=\"Higgins1999\"/> It was thought that females reached [[sexual maturity]] at 9 years of age, but four five-year-old females have now been recorded reproducing.<ref name=\"Easton2006\"/><ref name=\":2\" /> The kakapo does not breed every year and has one of the lowest rates of reproduction among birds. Breeding occurs only in years when trees mast (fruit heavily), providing a plentiful food supply. [[Dacrydium cupressinum|Rimu]] mast occurs only every three to five years, so in rimu-dominant forests, such as those on Whenua Hou, kakapo breeding occurs as infrequently.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Nutrient composition of the diet of parent-raised kakapo nestlings |first1=Yvette |last1=Cottam |first2=Don V. |last2=Merton  |authorlink2=Don Merton |first3=Wouter |last3=Hendriks |pages=90\u201399|journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |year=2006 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_90.pdf}}</ref>\n\nAnother aspect of the kakapo's breeding system is that a female can alter the sex ratio of her offspring depending on her condition. A female in good condition produces more male offspring (males have 30%\u201340% more body weight than females<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>). Females produce offspring biased towards the dispersive sex when competition for resources (such as food) is high and towards the non-dispersive sex when food is plentiful. A female kakapo will likely be able to produce eggs even when there are few resources, while a male kakapo will be more capable of perpetuating the species when there are plenty, by mating with several females.<ref name=\"berkeley_kakapo_reproduction\">{{cite web |url=http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/news/060401_kakapo |title=Conserving the kakapo |accessdate=22 March 2008 |date=April 2006 |work=Understanding Evolution |publisher=University of California, Berkeley}}</ref> This supports the [[Trivers\u2013Willard hypothesis]]. The relationship between clutch sex ratio and maternal diet has conservation implications, because a captive population maintained on a high quality diet will produce fewer females and therefore fewer individuals valuable to the recovery of the species.<ref name=\"sutherland-sciencesexkakapo\">{{cite journal |last=Sutherland |first=William J. |title=Conservation biology: Science, sex and the kakapo |journal=Nature |volume=419 |year=2002 |pages=265\u2013266 |doi=10.1038/419265a |pmid=12239554 |issue=6904}}</ref>\n\n===Feeding===\nThe beak of the kakapo is adapted for grinding food finely. For this reason, the kakapo has a very small [[gizzard]] compared to other birds of their size. It is entirely [[Herbivore|herbivorous]], eating native plants, seeds, fruits, pollen and even the sapwood of trees. A study in 1984 identified 25 plant species as kakapo food.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/> It is particularly fond of the fruit of the [[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]] tree, and will feed on it exclusively during seasons when it is abundant. The kakapo strips out the nutritious parts of the plant out with its beak, leaving a ball of indigestible fibre. These little clumps of plant fibres are a distinctive sign of the presence of the bird.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Gray |first=R. S. |year=1977| title=The kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'', Gray 1847), its food, feeding and habitat in Fiordland and Maud Island| version=MSc thesis| publisher=Massey University, Palmerston North, New Zealand}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal |last1=Atkinson |first1=I.A.E. |last2=Merton |first2=D.V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |year=2006 |title=Habitat and diet of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') in the Esperance Valley, Fiordland, New Zealand |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |pages=37\u201354 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_37.pdf}}</ref> The kakapo is believed to employ bacteria in the fore-gut to ferment and help digest plant matter.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Lopez-Calleja |first1 = M. Victoria |last2=Bozinovic | first2 = F. |doi=10.4067/S0716-078X2000000300005 |title=Energetics and nutritional ecology of small herbivorous birds |journal=Revista Chilena de Historia Natural |volume=73 |issue=3 |year=2000 |pages=411\u2013420}}</ref>\n\nKakapo diet changes according to the season. The plants eaten most frequently during the year include some species of ''[[Lycopodium ramulosum]]'', ''Lycopodium fastigium'', ''Schizaea fistulosa'', ''Blechnum minus'', ''Blechnum procerum'', ''Cyathodes juniperina'', ''Dracophyllum longifolium'', ''Olearia colensoi'' and ''Thelymitra venosa''. Individual plants of the same species are often treated differently. Kakapo leave conspicuous evidence of their feeding activities, over feeding areas that range between {{Convert|10|\u00d7|10|m|ft|-1}} and {{Convert|50|\u00d7|100|m|ft|-1}} per individual.<ref name=\"Best1984\"/> Kakapo feeding grounds almost always host [[Leptospermum scoparium|manuka]] and yellow silver pine (''[[Lepidothamnus intermedius]]'') scrubs.\n\n==Conservation==\nFossil records indicate that in pre-Polynesian times, the kakapo was New Zealand's third most common bird<ref name=\"GOG\">{{Cite book |title=Ghosts of Gondwana; The history of life in New Zealand |first=George |last=Gibbs |publisher=Craig Potton Publishing |year=2007}}</ref> and it was widespread on all three main islands. However, the kakapo population in New Zealand has declined massively since human settlement of the country, and its conservation status as ranked by the Department of Conservation continues to be \"Nationally Critical\".<ref name=\"NZTCS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nztcs.org.nz/#/assessments/31698|title=NZTCS Assessment Details |website=www.nztcs.org.nz |access-date=2019-01-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190122223418/https://nztcs.org.nz/#/assessments/31698 |archive-date=22 January 2019 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Since 1891, conservation efforts have been made to prevent extinction. The most successful scheme has been the Kakapo Recovery Programme; this was implemented in 1995 and continues.\n\n===Human impact===\n[[File:Naturhistorisches Museum, Kakapo.jpg|thumb| [[Zoological specimen|Specimens]] at the [[Vienna Museum of Natural History]]; thousands of kakapo were collected for museums across the world]]\nThe first factor in the decline of the kakapo was the arrival of humans. [[M\u0101ori mythology|M\u0101ori folklore]] suggests that the kakapo was found throughout the country when the [[Polynesians]] first arrived in [[Aotearoa]] 700 years ago.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> [[Subfossil]] and [[midden]] deposits show that the bird was present throughout the North and South Island before and during early M\u0101ori times.<ref name=\"FGNZB\">{{cite book |first1=Barrie |last1=Heather |first2=Hugh |last2=Robertson |others=illustrated by Derek Onley |title=The Field Guide to the Birds of New Zealand |publisher=Viking |edition=revised |year=2005}}</ref> M\u0101ori hunted the kakapo for food and for their skins and feathers, which were made into [[M\u0101ori traditional textiles|cloaks]].<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> They used the dried heads as ear ornaments.\n\nDue to its inability to fly, strong scent and habit of freezing when threatened, the kakapo was easy prey for the M\u0101ori and their dogs. Its eggs and chicks were also preyed upon by the [[Polynesian rat]] or kiore, which the M\u0101ori brought to New Zealand as a stowaway.<ref name=\"Merton77\"/> Furthermore, the deliberate clearing of vegetation by M\u0101ori reduced the habitable range for kakapo. Although the kakapo was extinct in many parts of the islands by the time Europeans arrived,<ref name=\"Williams1956\">{{cite journal |journal=Notornis |first=G.R. |last=Williams |title=The kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'', Gray): A review and reappraisal of a near-extinct species |volume=7 |issue=2 |year=1956 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_7_2.pdf |pages=29\u201356}}</ref> including the [[Tararua Ranges|Tararua]] and [[Aorangi Range]]s,<ref name=\"FLM\">{{cite book |last=Best |first=Elsdon |authorlink=Elsdon Best |title=Forest Lore of the Maori |url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-BesFore.html |access-date=11 May 2012 |series=Memoirs of the Polynesian Society. '''18'''. Dominion Museum bulletin |volume=14 |year=1977 |origyear=1942 |publisher=E.C. Keating, Government Printer |location=[[Wellington]], New Zealand |oclc=639613989 |pages=170\u2013175 |chapter=Bird Lore: How birds were taken \u2013 K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d (''Strigops habroptilus'') |chapter-url=http://www.nzetc.org/tm/scholarly/tei-BesFore-t1-body-d2-d6-d3.html}}</ref> it was locally abundant in parts of New Zealand, such as the central North Island and forested parts of the South Island.<ref name=\"FGNZB\"/>\n\nAlthough kakapo numbers were reduced by M\u0101ori settlement, they declined much more rapidly after European colonisation.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Bergner|first=Laura M. |last2=Dussex |first2=Nicolas |last3=Jamieson |first3=Ian G. |last4=Robertson |first4=Bruce C. |date=2016 |title=European colonization, not Polynesian arrival, impacted population size and genetic diversity in the critically endangered New Zealand k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |journal=Journal of Heredity |language=en |volume=107 |issue=7 |pages=593\u2013602 |doi=10.1093/jhered/esw065 |pmid=27694405 |issn=0022-1503}}</ref> Beginning in the 1840s, [[P\u0101keh\u0101]] settlers [[Deforestation in New Zealand#European settlement|cleared vast tracts of land]] for farming and grazing, further reducing kakapo habitat. They brought more dogs and other mammalian predators, including domestic cats, black rats and [[Stoats in New Zealand|stoats]].<ref name=\"Sutherland2002\">{{cite journal |journal=Nature |title=Conservation biology: Science, sex, and the kakapo |volume=419 |issue=6904 |first=W.J. |last=Sutherland |pages=265\u2013266 |doi=10.1038/419265a |pmid=12239554 |year=2002}}</ref> Europeans knew little of the kakapo until [[George Robert Gray|George Gray]] of the [[British Museum]] described it from a skin in 1845. As the M\u0101ori had done, early European explorers and their dogs ate kakapo. In the late 19th century, the kakapo became well known as a scientific curiosity, and thousands were captured or killed for zoos, museums and collectors. Most captured specimens died within months. From at least the 1870s, collectors knew the kakapo population was declining; their prime concern was to collect as many as possible before the bird became extinct.\n\nIn the 1880s, large numbers of [[Mustelidae|mustelids]] (stoats, ferrets and weasels) were released in New Zealand to reduce rabbit numbers,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Murphy |first1=E. |last2=Dowding |first2=J. | year=1995 |title=Ecology of the stoat in ''Nothofagus'' forest: home range, habitat use and diet at different stages of the beech mast cycle |journal=New Zealand Journal of Ecology |volume=19 |issue=2 |pages=97\u2013109 |url=http://www.nzes.org.nz/nzje/free_issues/NZJEcol19_2_97.pdf}}</ref> but they also preyed heavily on many native species including the kakapo. Other browsing animals, such as introduced deer, competed with the kakapo for food, and caused the extinction of some of its preferred plant species. The kakapo was reportedly still present near the head of the [[Whanganui River]] as late as 1894, with one of the last records of a kakapo in the North Island being a single bird caught in the [[Kaimanawa Range]]s by Te Kepa Puawheawhe in 1895.<ref name=\"FLM\"/>\n\n===Early protection efforts===\nIn 1891, the New Zealand government set aside [[Resolution Island, New Zealand|Resolution Island]] in Fiordland as a nature reserve. In 1894, the government appointed [[Richard Treacy Henry|Richard Henry]] as caretaker. A keen naturalist, Henry was aware that native birds were declining, and began catching and moving kakapo and [[kiwi]] from the mainland to the predator-free Resolution Island. In six years, he moved more than 200&nbsp;kakapo to Resolution Island. By 1900, however, [[stoat]]s had swum to Resolution Island and colonised it; they wiped out the nascent kakapo population within 6&nbsp;years.<ref name=\"Hill1987\">{{cite book |author1=Hill, S. |author2=Hill, J. |year=1987 |title=Richard Henry of Resolution Island |location=Dunedin |publisher=John McIndoe}}</ref>\n\nIn 1903, three kakapo were moved from Resolution Island to the nature reserve of [[Little Barrier Island]] (Hauturu-o-Toi) north-east of [[Auckland]], but [[feral cats]] were present and the kakapo were never seen again. In 1912, three kakapo were moved to another reserve, [[Kapiti Island]], north-west of [[Wellington]]. One of them survived until at least 1936, despite the presence of feral cats for part of the intervening period.<ref name=\"Hill1987\"/>\n\nBy the 1920s, the kakapo was extinct in the [[North Island]] and its range and numbers in the [[South Island]] were declining.<ref name=\"Williams1956\"/> One of its last refuges was rugged Fiordland. There, during the 1930s, it was often seen or heard, and occasionally eaten, by hunters or roadworkers. By the 1940s, reports of kakapo were becoming scarce.\n{{clear}}\n\n===1950\u20131989 conservation efforts===\n[[File:Milford Sound and Sinbad Gully -New Zealand-9Jan2009.jpg|right|thumb|Sinbad Gully in Fiordland, seen between the mountains on the far side of a [[fjord]], was one of the last strongholds of the kakapo on mainland New Zealand.<ref name=LCTSee-2009>{{cite episode |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00mg3qk |title=Last Chance to See |network=[[BBC]] |station=[[BBC Two]] |series=Last Chance to See |series-link=Last Chance to See (TV series) |airdate=2009-10-04 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>]]\nIn the 1950s, the [[New Zealand Wildlife Service]] was established and began making regular expeditions to search for the kakapo, mostly in Fiordland and what is now the [[Kahurangi National Park]] in the northwest of the South Island. Seven Fiordland expeditions between 1951 and 1956 found only a few recent signs. Finally, in 1958 a kakapo was caught and released in the [[Milford Sound]] catchment area in Fiordland. Six more kakapo were captured in 1961; one was released and the other five were transferred to the [[aviary|aviaries]] of the Mount Bruce Bird Reserve near [[Masterton]] in the North Island. Within months, four of the birds had died and the fifth died after about four years. In the next 12&nbsp;years, regular expeditions found few signs of the kakapo, indicating that numbers were continuing to decline. Only one bird was captured in 1967; it died the following year.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Donald |first1=Paul F. |last2=Collar |first2=Nigel J.|last3=Marsden |first3=Stuart J. |last4=Pain |first4=Deborah J. |title=Facing Extinction: The World's Rarest Birds and the Race to Save Them |year=2010 |publisher=T & A D Poyser |location=London |isbn=978-0-7136-7021-9 |p=167}}</ref>\n\nBy the early 1970s, it was uncertain whether the kakapo was still an extant species. At the end of 1974, scientists located several more male kakapo and made the first scientific observations of kakapo booming. These observations led [[Don Merton]] to speculate for the first time that the kakapo had a [[Lek (mating arena)|lek]] breeding system.<ref name=\"Merton77\"/> From 1974 to 1978 a total of 18&nbsp;kakapo were discovered in Fiordland, but all were males. This raised the possibility that the species would become extinct, because there might be no surviving females. One male bird was captured in the Milford area in 1975, christened \"Richard Henry\", and transferred to [[Maud Island]]. All the birds the Wildlife Service discovered from 1951 to 1976 were in U-shaped [[glaciated valley]]s flanked by almost-vertical cliffs and surrounded by high mountains. Such extreme terrain had slowed colonisation by browsing mammals, leaving islands of virtually unmodified native vegetation. However, even here, stoats were present and by 1976 the kakapo was gone from the valley floors and only a few males survived high on the most inaccessible parts of the cliffs.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/>\n\nBefore 1977, no expedition had been to [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]] to search for the bird. In 1977, sightings of kakapo were reported on [[Stewart Island]].<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> An expedition to the island found a track and bowl system on its first day; soon after, it located several dozen kakapo. The finding in an 8,000-hectare area of fire-modified [[scrubland]] and forest raised hope that the population would include females. The total population was estimated at 100 to 200&nbsp;birds.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/03014223.1995.9518039 |last1=Powlesland |first1=R.G. |last2=Roberts|first2=A. |last3=Lloyd |first3=B.D. |last4=Merton |first4=D.V. |authorlink4=Don Merton |year=1995 |title=Number, fate and distribution of kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') found on Stewart Island, New Zealand, 1979\u201392 |journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=239\u2013248}}</ref>\n\n[[Mustelid]]s have never colonised [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]], but feral cats were present. During a survey, it was apparent that cats killed kakapo at a rate of 56% per year.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Karl |first1=B.J |last2=Best |first2=H.A. |title=Feral cats on Stewart Island: their foods and their effects on kakapo |journal=New Zealand Journal of Zoology |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=287\u2013294 |year=1982 |doi=10.1080/03014223.1982.10423857}}</ref> At this rate, the birds could not survive on the island and therefore an intensive cat control was introduced in 1982, after which no cat-killed kakapo were found.<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\"/> However, to ensure the survival of the remaining birds, scientists decided later that this population should be transferred to predator-free islands; this operation was carried out between 1982 and 1997.<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\">{{cite journal |first1=B.D. |last1=Lloyd |first2=R.G. |last2=Powlesland |title=The decline of kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' and attempts at conservation by translocation |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=69 |issue=1 |year=1994 |pages=75\u201385 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(94)90330-1}}</ref>\n\n===Kakapo Recovery programme===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Kakapo Translocations 1974\u20131992<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\"/>\n|-\n! Translocated to !! Number of kakapo !! Deaths < 6 months !! Survived as of November 1992\n|-\n| Maud Island (1974\u201381) || 9 (6\u2642, 3\u2640) || 3 (2\u2642, 1\u2640) || 4 (2\u2642, 2\u2640)\n|-\n| Little Barrier Island (1982) || 22 (13\u2642, 9\u2640) || 2 (1\u2642, 1\u2640) || 15\u201319 (10\u201312\u2642, 5\u20137\u2640)\n|-\n| Codfish Island (1987\u201392) || 30 (20\u2642, 10\u2640) || 0 || 20\u201330 (13\u201320\u2642, 7\u201310\u2640)\n|-\n| Maud Island (1989\u201391) || 6 (4\u2642, 2\u2640) || 0 || 5 (3\u2642, 2\u2640)\n|-\n| Mana Island (1992) || 2 (2\u2640) || 1 (1\u2640) || 1 (1\u2640)\n|-\n| '''Total''' || 65 (43\u2642, 22\u2640) || 6 (3\u2642, 3\u2640) || 41\u201355 (27\u201336\u2642, 14\u201319\u2640)\n|-\n| colspan=4 |'''Note:''' \u2642 = males, \u2640 = females.\n|}\n\nIn 1989, a Kakapo Recovery plan was developed, and a Kakapo Recovery programme was established in 1995.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Powlesland|first=R. G.| year=1989 | title=Kakapo recovery plan 1989\u20131994| publisher=Department of Conservation| location=Wellington}}</ref> The New Zealand [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] replaced the Wildlife Service for this task.\n\nThe first action of the plan was to relocate all the remaining kakapo to suitable islands for them to breed. None of the New Zealand islands were ideal to establish kakapo without [[Island restoration|rehabilitation]] by extensive re-vegetation and the eradication of introduced mammalian predators and competitors. Four islands were finally chosen: [[Maud Island|Maud]], [[Little Barrier Island|Hauturu/Little Barrier]], [[Codfish Island|Codfish]] and [[Mana Island, New Zealand|Mana]].<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\" /> Sixty-five kakapo (43 males, 22 females) were successfully transferred onto the four islands in five translocations.<ref name=\"Lloyd1994\" /> Some islands had to be rehabilitated several times when feral cats, stoats and [[weka]] kept appearing. Little Barrier Island was eventually viewed as unsuitable due to the rugged landscape, the thick forest and the continued presence of rats, and its birds were evacuated in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/little-barrier-island/|title=Little Barrier Island |publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> Along with Mana Island, it was replaced with two new kakapo sanctuaries: [[Chalky Island (New Zealand)|Chalky Island (Te Kakahu)]] and [[Anchor Island]].<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> The entire kakapo population of Codfish Island was temporarily relocated in 1999 to [[Pearl Island (New Zealand)|Pearl Island]] in [[Port Pegasus]] while rats were being eliminated from Codfish.<ref name=\"Whitehead\">{{cite thesis | first = Joanna K. | last = Whitehead | title = Breeding success of adult female kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') on Codfish Island (Whenua Hou): correlations with foraging home ranges and habitat selection | year = 2007 |publisher=Lincoln University |type=MSc thesis | hdl = 10182/640 }}</ref> All kakapo on Pearl and Chalky Islands were moved to Anchor Island in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=57&Itemid=223|title=Updates: June to September 2005 |publisher=Kakapo Recovery|accessdate=12 April 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616192606/http://www.kakaporecovery.org.nz/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=57&Itemid=223|archivedate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Supplementary feeding====\nA key part of the Recovery Programme is the supplementary feeding of females. Kakapo breed only once every two to five years, when certain plant species, primarily [[Dacrydium cupressinum|''Dacrydium cupressinum'' (rimu)]], produce protein-rich fruit and seeds. During breeding years when rimu masts supplementary food is provided to kakapo to increase the likelihood of individuals successfully breeding.<ref name=\"Elliott2001\">{{cite journal |last1=Elliott |first1=G.P. |last2=Merton |first2=D.V. |authorlink2=Don Merton |last3=Jansen |first3=P. W. |year=2001 |title=Intensive management of a critically endangered species: the kakapo |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=99 |pages=121\u2013133 |issue=1 |doi=10.1016/S0006-3207(00)00191-9}}</ref> In 1989, six preferred foods (apples, sweet potatoes, almonds, Brazil nuts, sunflower seeds and walnuts) were supplied ''[[ad libitum]]'' each night to 12&nbsp;feeding stations. Males and females ate the supplied foods, and females nested on Little Barrier Island in the summers of 1989\u20131991 for the first time since 1982, although nesting success was low.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=R.G. |last1=Powlesland |first2=B.D. |last2=Lloyd |title=Use of supplementary feeding to induce breeding in free-living kakapo ''Strigops habroptilus'' in New Zealand |journal=Biological Conservation |volume=69 |issue=1 |year=1994 |pages=97\u2013106 |doi=10.1016/0006-3207(94)90332-8}}</ref>\n\nSupplementary feeding affects the [[sex ratio]] of kakapo offspring, and can be used to increase the number of female chicks by deliberately manipulating maternal condition.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite journal |last1=Robertson |first1=B.C. |last2=Elliott |first2=G.P. |last3=Eason |first3=D.K. |last4=Clout |first4=M.N. |last5=Gemmell |first5=N.J. |year=2006 |title=Sex allocation theory aids species conservation |journal=[[Biology Letters]] |pmid=17148369 |pages=229\u2013231 |volume=2 |pmc=1618899 |issue=2 |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2005.0430}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> During the winter of 1981, only females lighter than {{convert|1.5|kg|abbr=on}} were given supplementary feeding to avoid raising their body condition, and the sex ratio results in 1982 were close to parity, eliminating the male-biased sex ratios in the unrestricted feeding.\n\nToday commercial parrot food is supplied to all individuals of breeding age on Whenua Hou and Anchor. The amount eaten and individual weights are carefully monitored to ensure that optimum body condition is maintained.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n====Nest management====\n[[File:Stephen Bragg with kakapo chicks.jpg|thumb|left|Department of Conservation worker with chicks]]Kakapo nests are intensively managed. Before [[Polynesian rat]]s were removed from Whenua Hou, they were a threat to the survival of young kakapo. Of 21 chicks that hatched between 1981 and 1994, nine were either killed by rats or died and were subsequently eaten by rats.<ref name=\"Elliott2001\" /> Nest protection was intensified after 1995 by using [[rat trap|traps]] and poison stations as soon as a nest was detected. A small video camera and [[Infrared|infra-red light source]] would watch the nest continuously, and scare approaching rats with flashing lights and loud popping sounds.\n\nAll kakapo islands are now rat-free, but infrared cameras still allow rangers to remotely monitor the behaviour of females and chicks in nests. Data loggers record when mother kakapo come and go, allowing rangers to pick a time to check on the health of chicks, and also indicate how hard females are having to work to find food. Because mother kakapo often struggle to successfully rear multiple chicks, Kakapo Recovery rangers will move chicks between nests as needed.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nEggs are often removed from nests for incubation to reduce the likelihood of accidents, such as lost eggs or crushing. If chicks become ill, aren\u2019t putting on weight, or there are too many chicks in the nest (and no available nest to move them to) they will be hand-reared by the Kakapo Recovery team.<ref name=\":2\" /> In the 2019 season, eggs were also removed from nests to encourage females to re-nest. By hand-raising the first group of chicks in captivity and encouraging females to lay more eggs, the Kakapo Recovery Team hoped that overall chick production would be increased.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/programmes/kakapo-files/story/2018678725/super-studs-and-hitting-the-reset-button |title=Super-studs & hitting the reset button |website=RNZ |date=17 January 2019 |last=Ballance |first=A. |access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref> By the end of February 2020, the bird's summer breeding season, these efforts led to the production of 80 chicks, \"a record number.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2020/mar/14/worlds-fattest-parrot-comeback-from-extinction-aoe |title=How the world's fattest parrot came back from the brink |website=The Guardian|date=14 March 2020 |last=Evans|first=Kate |access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Monitoring====\nTo monitor the kakapo population continuously, each bird is equipped with a [[radio transmitter]].<ref name=\"Elliott2001\" /> [[List of kakapo|Every known kakapo, barring some young chicks, has been given a name]] by Kakapo Recovery Programme officials, and detailed data is gathered about every individual.<ref name=\":4\" /> GPS transmitters are also being trialled to provide more detailed data about the movement of individual birds and their habitat use.<ref name=\":2\" /> The signals also provide behavioural data, letting rangers gather information about mating and nesting remotely.<ref name=\":4\" /> Every individual kakapo receives an annual health check and has their transmitter replaced.\n\n====Reintroduction====\nThe Kakapo Recovery programme has been successful, with the numbers of kakapo increasing steadily. Adult survival rate and productivity have both improved significantly since the programme's inception. However, the main goal is to establish at least one viable, self-sustaining, unmanaged population of kakapo as a functional component of the [[ecosystem]] in a protected habitat.<ref>{{cite book |title=Kakapo recovery plan 1996\u20132005. Threatened Species Recovery Plan No. 21 .|last=Cresswell|first=M. |publisher=Department of Conservation |year=1996 |location=Wellington}}</ref> To help meet this conservation challenge, [[Resolution Island, New Zealand|Resolution Island]] (20,860&nbsp;ha) in Fiordland has been prepared for kakapo re-introduction with ecological restoration including the eradication of stoats.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.odt.co.nz/regions/southland/kakapo-overcrowding-may-force-return-island |title=Kakapo overcrowding may force return to island |last=McNeilly |first=Hamish |date=30 July 2011 |work=Otago Daily Times Online News |access-date=2018-12-04 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" /> Ultimately, the Kakapo Recovery vision for the species is to restore the \"mauri\" (Maori for \"life-force\") of the kakapo by breeding 150&nbsp;adult females.<ref name=\"PFTF\">{{cite web |url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/a-plan-for-the-future/ |title=A Plan for the Future 2006\u20132016|publisher=Kakapo Recovery |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127092154/http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/a-plan-for-the-future/ |archive-date=27 January 2018 |access-date=26 December 2018 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Fatal fungal infection====\nIn late April 2019, the first case of the fungal disease ''[[aspergillosis]]'' in New Zealand k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d was discovered. {{As of|2019|06|13|post=,}} almost 20% of the population, or 36 birds, have been flown by helicopter to veterinary hospitals around New Zealand for [[CT scan]] diagnosis and intensive treatment that usually lasted for several months.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Charles |title=World's fattest parrot, the endangered k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d, could be wiped out by fungal infection |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/13/worlds-fattest-parrot-endangered-kakapo-fungal-infection-new-zealand |website=Guardian International |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=13 June 2019 |quote=The world\u2019s fattest parrot is facing an existential threat in the form of a dangerous fungal infection which has already endangered a fifth of its species.  Seven of New Zealand\u2019s native k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d have died in recent months after falling victim to the respiratory disease aspergillosis. The latest was on Tuesday, where a 100-day-old chick died at the Auckland Zoo.  The nocturnal and flightless parrot ingratiated itself with world after it mated with a zoologist\u2019s head during a BBC documentary. The incident led it to being described as the \u201cparty parrot\u201d and finding a life-long fan in Stephen Fry.}}</ref>\n\n[[Dunedin]]'s Wildlife Hospital has treated 12 birds.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Van Velthooven |first1=Emily |title=Spate of k\u0101k\u0101po deaths 'the devastating outcome of the really great breeding season' |url=https://www.tvnz.co.nz/one-news/new-zealand/spate-k-po-deaths-devastating-outcome-really-great-breeding-season |accessdate=13 June 2019 |publisher=One News Now |quote=While aspergillosis isn\u2019t incurable, time is a defining factor. Dr.&nbsp;Chatterton says the best chance a k\u0101k\u0101po has is an early diagnosis with lots of medication. \"But that\u2019s really challenging with wild birds.\" It\u2019s not just Auckland helping, Massey University's Wild Base Hospital in Palmerston North has taken in six birds for treatment and Dunedin's Wildlife Hospital has taken in a further 12.}}</ref>\n\n==Population timeline==\n[[File:Kakapo-population-size.svg|thumb|upright=2|Cat control in 1982 arrested a sharp decline in kakapo numbers, and they have recently increased under the Kakapo Recovery plan. Red arrows indicate breeding years. Numbers become less precise before 1995, with the 1977 figure perhaps out by 50&nbsp;birds.]]\n\n* 1977: Kakapo rediscovered on [[Stewart Island|Stewart Island/Rakiura]]\n* 1989: Most kakapo are removed from Rakiura to Whenua Hou and Hauturu-O-Toi\n* 1995: Kakapo population consists of 51 individuals; beginning of the Kakapo Recovery Programme\n* 1999: Kakapo removed from Hauturu\n* 2002: A significant breeding season led to 24&nbsp;chicks being hatched\n* 2005: 41&nbsp;females and 45&nbsp;males, including four fledglings (3&nbsp;females and 1&nbsp;male); kakapo established on Anchor Island<ref name=\"Powlesland2006\" />\n* 2009: The total kakapo population rose to over 100 for the first time since monitoring began.<ref>{{cite news |author=NZPA |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/2251118/Kakapo-population-over-100-mark|title=Kakapo population over 100&nbsp;mark |work=stuff.co.nz |date=11 March 2009}}</ref> Twenty-two of the 34&nbsp;chicks had to be hand-reared because of a shortage of food on Codfish Island.<ref>{{cite news |author=NZPA |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/2328772/Keeping-kakapo-alive|title=Keeping kakapo alive |work=stuff.co.nz |date=11 April 2009}}</ref>\n* December 2010: Death of the oldest known kakapo, \"Richard Henry\", possibly 80 years old.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2011/kakapo-males-boom-on-as-legendary-bird-dies/ |title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d males 'boom' on as legendary bird dies |date=13 January 2011 |website=DOC |accessdate=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n* 2012: Seven kakapo  transferred to Hauturu, in an attempt to establish a successful breeding programme. Kakapo were last on the island in 1999.<ref name=\"barrier\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/6746273/Kakapo-relocated-to-raise-chicks |title=Kakapo relocated to raise chicks|publisher=stuff.co.nz |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n* March 2014: With the kakapo population having increased to 126, the bird's recovery was used by [[Melbourne]] artist Sayraphim Lothian as a metaphor for the [[February 2011 Christchurch earthquake|recovery of Christchurch]], parallelling the \"indomitable spirit of these two communities and their determination to rebuild\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Kakapo sculptures hidden in Christchurch |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/9834934/Find-a-kakapo-keep-the-love |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140317050015/http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/christchurch-life/art-and-stage/9834934/Find-a-kakapo-keep-the-love |url-status=dead |archive-date=17 March 2014 |last=Harvie |first=Will |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=17 March 2014 |accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Journey \u2013 A new work by Sayraphim Lothian with support from Gap Filler |url=http://www.gapfiller.org.nz/journey-a-new-work-by-sayraphim-lothian-with-support-from-gap-filler/ |accessdate=17 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317092202/http://www.gapfiller.org.nz/journey-a-new-work-by-sayraphim-lothian-with-support-from-gap-filler/ |archivedate=17 March 2014 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2016: First breeding on Anchor; a significant breeding season, with 32&nbsp;chicks; kakapo population grows to over 150\n* 2018: After the death of 3&nbsp;birds, the population has been reduced to 149.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://createsend.com/t/i-FE4939184088B7162540EF23F30FEDED |title=News and updates from the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Recovery Team |website=createsend.com |access-date=2018-10-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180822231212/http://createsend.com/t/i-FE4939184088B7162540EF23F30FEDED |archive-date=22 August 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* 2019: An abundance of rimu fruit and the introduction of several new technologies (including [[artificial insemination]] and 'smart eggs') helped make 2019 the best breeding season on record, with over 200&nbsp;eggs laid and 72&nbsp;chicks fledged {{As of|2019|07|01|lc=y}}. According to the Kakapo Recovery Team at the New Zealand Department of Conservation, this was the earliest and longest breeding season yet.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.radionz.co.nz/programmes/kakapo-files/story/2018684744/kakapo-rangers |title=Breaking news from one of the world's favourite birds - New Zealand's rare flightless parrot, the k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |website=radionz.co.nz |access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2019/first-new-kakapo-chicks-hatch/ |title=News and updates from the K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d Recovery Team|website=govt.nz |access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref> Population reached 200 juvenile or older birds on 17 Aug 2019.<ref>{{cite tweet | last = Digby | first = Andrew |user=takapodigs |author-link=Andrew Digby|number= 1162835621523664898|date=17 Aug 2019 |title= 200 #kakapo! The population has reached 200 today, with the latest chick (Esperance-3-B-19) becoming a juvenile - when we add birds to the official tally. There are probably more k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d alive now than at any time for \u226570 years. #kakapo2019 #conservation pic: @deidre_vercoe}}</ref>\n\n==In M\u0101ori culture==\nThe kakapo is associated with a rich tradition of M\u0101ori folklore and beliefs. The bird's irregular breeding cycle was understood to be associated with heavy fruiting or \"[[Mast year|masting]]\" events of particular plant species such as the [[Dacrydium cupressinum|rimu]], which led M\u0101ori to credit the bird with the ability to tell the future.<ref name=\"MBL\">{{cite book |first=Murdoch |last=Riley |title=Maori Bird Lore; An introduction |publisher=Viking Sevenseas NZ LTD. |year=2001}}</ref> Used to substantiate this claim were reported observations of these birds dropping the berries of the [[Elaeocarpus dentatus|hinau]] and [[Tawa (tree)|tawa]] trees (when they were in season) into secluded pools of water to preserve them as a food supply for the summer ahead; in legend this became the origin of the M\u0101ori practice of immersing food in water for the same purpose.<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\n===Use for food and clothing===\n[[File:Strigops habroptilus (AM LB14666-3).jpg|thumb|upright|Feathers]] \nThe meat of kakapo made good eating and was considered by M\u0101ori to be a delicacy<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/> and it was hunted for food when it was still widespread.<ref name=\"WS\">{{Cite book |first1=Rod |last1=Morris |first2=Hal |last2=Smith |title=Wild South: Saving New Zealand's endangered birds |publisher=Random House |location=New Zealand |year=1995}}</ref> One source states that its flesh \"resembles [[Lamb and mutton|lamb]] in taste and texture\",<ref name=\"MBL\"/> although European settlers have described the bird as having a \"strong and slightly stringent [sic] flavour\".<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/>\n\nIn breeding years, the loud booming calls of the males at their [[Lek (mating arena)|mating arenas]] made it easy for M\u0101ori hunting parties to track the kakapo down, and it was also hunted while feeding or when dust-bathing in dry weather. The bird was caught, generally at night, using [[Trapping (Animal)#Snares|snares]], pitfall traps, or by groups of domesticated [[Kur\u012b|Polynesian dogs]] which accompanied hunting parties \u2013 sometimes they would use fire sticks of various sorts to dazzle a bird in the darkness, stopping it in their tracks and making the capture easier.<ref name=\"MBL\"/> Cooking was done in a [[h\u0101ngi]] or in gourds of boiling oil.<ref name=\"WS\"/> The flesh of the bird could be preserved in its own fat and stored in containers for later consumption \u2013 hunters of the [[Ng\u0101i Tahu]] tribe would pack the flesh in baskets made from the inner bark of [[totara]] tree or in containers constructed from [[kelp]].<ref name=\"KM\">{{cite web|url=http://kakaporecovery.org.nz/iwi-perspective/ |title=New Zealand Ma\u014dri and the k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d |publisher=Kakapo Recovery |year=2015 |accessdate=18 May 2016}}</ref> Bundles of kakapo tail feathers were attached to the sides of these containers to provide decoration and a way to identify their contents.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\">{{cite journal |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_191.pdf |first=Rob |last=Tipa |title=Short note: Kakapo in M\u0101ori lore |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |pages=193\u2013194 |year=2006 |issue=1}}</ref><ref name=\"KM\"/> Also taken by the M\u0101ori were the bird's eggs, which are described as whitish \"but not pure white\", and about the same size as a [[kerer\u016b]] egg.<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\nAs well as eating the meat of the kakapo, M\u0101ori would use kakapo skins with the feathers still attached or individually weave in kakapo feathers with flax fibre to create cloaks and capes.<ref name=\"WS\"/><ref name=\"KM\"/><ref>{{cite web| title = Kakapo feather cloak | work = Search the collection database | publisher = British Museum | url = https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/search_object_details.aspx?objectid=497615&partid=1&IdNum=Oc1936,0607.1&orig=/research/search_the_collection_database/museum_no__provenance_search.aspx | accessdate = 1 August 2010}}</ref> Each one required up to 11,000 feathers to make.<ref name=\"WNZB?\"/> Not only were these garments considered very beautiful, they also kept the wearer very warm.<ref name=\"WS\"/><ref name=\"WNZB?\">{{Cite book |first=Andrew |last=Crowe |title=Which New Zealand Bird? |publisher=Penguin |year=2001}}</ref> They were highly valued, and the few still in existence today are considered ''[[taonga]]'' (treasures) \u2013 indeed, the old M\u0101ori adage \"You have a k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d cape and you still complain of the cold\" was used to describe someone who is never satisfied.<ref name=\"WS\"/> Kakapo feathers were also used to decorate the heads of [[taiaha]], but were removed before use in combat.<ref name=\"Tipa2006\"/><ref name=\"KM\"/><ref name=\"WNZB?\"/>\n\nDespite this, the kakapo was also regarded as an affectionate pet by the M\u0101ori. This was corroborated by European settlers in New Zealand in the 19th century, among them [[George Edward Grey]], who once wrote in a letter to an associate that his pet kakapo's behaviour towards him and his friends was \"more like that of a dog than a bird\".<ref name=\"MBL\"/>\n\n==In the media==\nThe conservation of the kakapo has made the species well known. Many books and documentaries detailing the plight of the kakapo have been produced in recent years, one of the earliest being ''Two in the Bush'', made by [[Gerald Durrell]] for the [[BBC]] in 1962.<ref name=\"GeraldDurrellBBC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.durrellwildlife.org/index.cfm?a=51 |title=Gerald Durrell's career |publisher=durrellwildlife.org |accessdate = 8 August 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070725220741/http://www.durrellwildlife.org/index.cfm?a=51 |archive-date=25 July 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref> \n\nA feature-length documentary, ''The Unnatural History of the Kakapo''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elwin.co.nz/kakapo-film/ |title=The Unnatural History of the Kakapo |publisher=Elwin.co.nz |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref> won two major awards at the [[Reel Earth Environmental Film Festival]]. Two of the most significant documentaries, both made by [[NHNZ]], are ''Kakapo \u2013 Night Parrot'' (1982) and ''To Save the Kakapo'' (1997). \n\n[[File:Kakapo Sirocco 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.3|[[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] on Maud Island]]\nThe BBC's Natural History Unit also featured the kakapo, including a sequence with [[David Attenborough|Sir David Attenborough]] in ''[[The Life of Birds]]''. It was also one of the endangered animals [[Douglas Adams]] and [[Mark Carwardine]] set out to find for the radio series and book ''[[Last Chance to See]]''. An updated version of the series has been produced for BBC TV, in which [[Stephen Fry]] and Carwardine revisit the animals to see how they are getting on almost 20&nbsp;years later, and in January 2009, they spent time filming the kakapo on Codfish Island.<ref name=LCTSee-2009/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.odt.co.nz/news/national/38869/fry-making-kakapo-doco |title=Fry making kakapo doco |last=McNeilly |first=Hamish |date=10 January 2009 |publisher=Otago Daily Times |accessdate=9 January 2009}}</ref> Footage of a kakapo named [[Sirocco (parrot)|Sirocco]] attempting to mate with Carwardine's head was viewed by millions worldwide, leading to Sirocco becoming \"spokes-bird\" for New Zealand wildlife conservation in 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Starmer-Smith|first=Charles |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/7128042/Parrot-that-tried-to-mate-with-Mark-Carwardine-is-given-a-government-role.html |title=Parrot that tried to mate with Mark Carwardine is given a government role |work=The Telegraph |date=1 February 2010 |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe kakapo was featured in the episode \"Strange Islands\" of the documentary series ''[[South Pacific (TV series)|South Pacific]]'', originally aired on 13 June 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1486170 |title=Wild Pacific \u2013 Strange Evolutions |accessdate=29 March 2011 |website=IMDb}}</ref> in the episode \"Worlds Apart\" of the series ''[[The Living Planet]]'',<ref>{{cite web |title=The Living Planet [episode&nbsp;10] |url=http://topdocumentaryfilms.com/the-living-planet/ |website=Top Documentary Films}}</ref> and in episode&nbsp;3 of the BBC's ''New Zealand Earth's Mythical Islands''.<ref>{{cite media |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b07lslq4 |title=New Zealand Earth's Mythical Islands |medium=video |publisher=BBC |location=U.K.}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2019 kakapo awareness campaign, the Kakapo Recovery Programme New Zealand National Partner, [[Meridian Energy]], ran a ''Search for a Saxophonist'' to provide suitable mood music for encouraging mating to coincide with the 2019 kakapo breeding season. The search and footage from the islands where breeding was taking place were featured on the ''One News Breakfast'' programme.<ref>{{cite media |last=One News New Zealand|title=Saxophonist wanted by DOC to get endangered k\u0101k\u0101p\u014d in breeding mood with romantic music 1 NEWS NOW |date=2019-01-28 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsogD557D5I |access-date=2019-06-27 |medium=video |via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Cats in New Zealand]]\n* [[Conservation in New Zealand]]\n{{Portal bar|Birds|Animals|Biology|New Zealand}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist|1}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book |author=Ballance, Alison |title=K\u0101k\u0101p\u014d: Rescued from the brink of extinction |publisher=Craig Potton Publishing |location=Nelson |orig-year=2010 |edition=2nd |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-877517-27-3}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Butler |first=David |year=1989 |title=Quest for the kakapo |location=Auckland | publisher=Heinemann Reed |isbn=978-0-7900-0065-7}}\n* {{Cite book |last1=Climo |first1=Gideon |last2=Ballance |first2=Alison |year=1997 |title=Hoki: The story of a kakapo |location=Auckland |publisher=Godwit |isbn=978-1-86962-009-7}}\n* {{cite book |last=Jones |first=Jenny |year=2003 |title=The kakapo |location=Auckland |isbn=978-1-86948-662-4 |publisher=Reed}}\n* {{Cite journal |title=Saving kakapo: An illustrated history |year=2006 |first1=Murray |last1=Williams |first2=Don |last2=Merton |authorlink2=Don Merton |journal=Notornis |volume=53 |issue=1 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_53_1_i.pdf}}\n* {{cite magazine |title=Eulenpapagei oder Kakapo (''Strigops habroptilus'') |editor=Steinig, G\